[Black "1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A05"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Qb6 {The only challenging move, putting pressure on d4 and b2.} 11. Re1 $5 ({I believe this is the best move.} 11. Qb3 Qc5 12. Rac1 $146 {is the engine's suggestion, just sacrificing a pawn. 12.Nxc6 bxc6 13.Na4 Qh5 $132 isn't satisfying for White, as my own game showed: 0-1 Edouard - Bacrot, Cap d'Agde 2016.} Nxd4 13. exd4 Qxd4 14. Be3 Qe5 15. Rfd1 {And, although it took me time to believe it, it seems like Black is indeed under pressure. For example} Qa5 16. Nd5 Re8 {16...Qd8?! 17.c5 $16} 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Rd5 $1 {a nice maneuver.} Qa6 {18...Qd8?! 19.Rb5 $16} 19. Rb5 Rb8 20. Rb4 Bd7 21. Rxb7 Rxb7 22. Bxb7 Qa5 23. Bd5 Rc8 24. h4 Kg7 {and here Black should equalize, but precision was required. Anyhow, I definitely prefer 11. Re1.}) 11... Bg4 $5 (11... Qxb2 $2 12. Rb1 Qa3 13. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 14. Nxc6 {and White is much better thanks to the brilliant point} Re8 15. Nxe7+ $1 Rxe7 16. Qf3 {winning the piece back!}) 12. Qb3 $1 {Sort of an improvement of the more usual 11. Qb3.} (12. f3 $2 {would weaken the a7-g1 diagonal too badly and simply allow} Nxd4 $6) 12... Qc7 $146 {The most natural move: threatening ... Na5.} (12... Rfc8 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. b3 $16 {Donchenko - Narayanan, chess24.com 2020.}) 13. h3 Bd7 14. Rac1 $14 Z0 ({And Nd5 is coming, while the c4-pawn is untouchable:} 14... Na5 $2 15. Qd1 Nxc4 $2 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 b5 18. b3) *

