1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Qd3 {This queen retreat avoids potential problems on the h8-a1 diagonal. However White will have to watch out for ...Bf5 or a knight coming to e5. Now best and most played move is 10... a6. Other moves lead to an easy small advantage for White.} a6 {The critical move. Whatever comes next, Black needs ...a6 in order to try to play ...b5 as soon as possible. Nevertheless, it doesn't change much: it takes too long.} 11. Bg5 $5 (11. Bd2 $5 {is good as well - but I believe Bg5 is a slight improvement over it, tryig to provoke ... h6.}) 11... h6 12. Be3 $5 Qa5 (12... Ng4 13. Bd4 Ne5 14. Qd1 {and White is better as the c4-pawn is untouchable:} Nxc4 $4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Ne5 17. f4) 13. h3 Be6 14. b3 $14 {White's position is excellent: 1-0 Lee - Stukopin, Redmond 2021.} *

