1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld.} Nc6 8. e4 Nb6 9. d5 Na5 {Now Qe1 is an interesting try, while 10. Nc3 would just transpose to our mainline.} 10. Qe1 $5 {An interesting attempt at taking advantage of Black's move order. White wants to remove the black knight from ...a5 so Black has more difficulties pushing ...c6 (as he won't be able to take back with the knight).} Nac4 11. Nc3 c6 $2 (11... e6 {is analyzed starting from here [/variation/31706246/#/12/w].}) 12. b3 Nd6 13. e5 Nf5 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Qe4 {And White is clearly better: a weakness on c6 and a powerless g7-bishop is all Black tries to avoid in the Grunfeld.} *

