1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld.} c5 $6 {A try to go for a totally symmetrical position, but known as too slow. White has two interesting ways to play.} 8. dxc5 {This is probably the simplest path to an advantage: going for a symmetrical but dynamic position.} Na6 9. Ng5 $1 {Here Black has two options, both of them not being part of the fun.} e6 10. Ne4 Bd7 11. Bg5 $1 {The most disturbing move. Again, provoking ...f6 is very weakening for Black, as it weakens e6 and closes the diagonal of the g7-bishop.} Qc7 (11... f6 12. Bc1 Bc6 13. Nbc3 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxc5 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. Be3 {followed by Rfd1 and a very pleasant endgame for White.}) 12. Nbc3 Nxc3 13. Nxc3 $14 {With Rc1 to come, unless Black is willing to trade his fianchetto bishop on c3.} *

