1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} c6 8. Rb1 {Now Black has a dilemma: to include ...a5 and ...a3 or not. At first, you would say, why not to open the a-file when White pushes b4. But ...a5 has a downside: when Black plays ... d5, after an exchange on d5 the b5-square is weak.} a5 9. a3 {Black has many options, but White's plan remains similar.} Nbd7 10. h3 $5 (10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 d5 {is something I would like to avoid.}) 10... Nc5 (10... d5 $6 {is no longer a great move due to} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bg5 {and Black has concrete problems.}) 11. b4 axb4 12. axb4 Ne6 13. e3 Re8 14. Bb2 $14 {Again, White has more space and a more pleasant position.} *

