1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. c4 h5 $5 {A rare continuation.} (7... O-O 8. Nc3 {would transpose to Chapter 1 [/course/200248/1] 1... Nf6 lines with 2... g6 and 5... c5.}) 8. h3 O-O (8... h4 $2 9. g4 {does not help Black: the h4-pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 9. Nc3 Nxd4 ({After} 9... d6 10. Be3 $1 Bd7 11. b3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Qd2 $14 {White simply gets a dream position as we were trying to get in ...Nf6/...g6/... c5 chapters.}) 10. Qxd4 d6 11. Rd1 $146 {A logical move, but also a novelty. It is anyway hard to imagine that including ...h5 and h3 can be good for Black when both sides castled kingside.} Be6 (11... Bd7 12. c5 $1 {creates concrete problems for Black.}) 12. Qh4 Qc8 13. b3 Nh7 ({Now} 13... Ng4 {isn't good.} 14. hxg4 Bxc3 15. Rb1 Bxg4 16. Qxe7 Re8 17. Qxb7 {with material advantage for White.}) 14. Bb2 Re8 15. Na4 {As there is the threat of 15...Bf6, we prevent it and exchange the important black bishop.} Bxb2 16. Nxb2 Bd7 $1 17. Nd3 {White's advantage is indisputable.} *

