1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {The best line for Black in my opinion.} 6. Nb3 (6. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1 {would just be more than fine for Black.}) 6... d5 7. Bg5 Be6 8. O-O {Here Black has a decent position if he understands that he should push ...e4 at some point and grant the d4-square.} Be7 9. Bxf6 ({White needs react quickly, as after} 9. Nc3 d4 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Ne4 Qb6 {followed by ...f5 is problematic for White.}) 9... Bxf6 $5 (9... gxf6 {is analyzed starting from here [/variation/31927784/#/9/b].}) 10. c4 {The point of the previous move - White must destroy Black's center.} dxc4 11. Nc5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Na5 13. Nc3 Z0 ({With the idea of Nxe6 and Nb5 would be slightly unpleasant for Black, although} 13... Rc8 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Nb5 Ke7 16. Nxa7 Ra8 17. Nb5 e4 $1 {seems to be nearly equal, but more dangerous for Black.}) *

