1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b5 {A move Black sometimes plays when it's kind of clear that White's light-squared bishop will move to g2, thus not attacking the b5-pawn. Black gains spaces on the queenside and allows a vis-à-vis with the g2-bishop, more actively than with 1... b6.} 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 {As against ...b6 ideas we've seen, this seems to be the most logical to face ...Bb7. White will close the bishop's diagonal with e2-e4 unless Black closes it himself with ...d7-d5.} e6 (4... d5 $6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 b5 4.O-O Bb7 5.d3 e6 6.c4 .}) 5. e4 d6 (5... Be7 {will soon transpose as ... d6 is probably next.}) 6. O-O Be7 7. Na3 $5 {This idea is much less convincing against 6... c5.} c6 $5 8. e5 $1 (8. c4 b4 9. Nc2 c5 {is unclear.}) 8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Qc8 10. d4 a6 11. c4 Z0 ({White has a pleasant position, e. g.} 11... Nbd7 12. Qf3 $14 {pinning the c6-pawn, or 11...c5 12.cxb5 Bxg2 13.Kxg2 cxd4 14.Qf3 Nbd7 15.Nc6! Bxa3 16.bxa3 axb5 17.Bd2 followed by Bb4 or Rac1, and Black has problems castling.}) *

