1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Bf5 5. Nh4 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qd3 e6 8. e4 {This position has been played three times: all by GM Svane!} c6 (8... dxe4 $4 {falls into a beginner trick, though such things can always accidentally happen:} 9. Qb5+ c6 10. Qxh5) 9. exd5 $146 {An interesting novelty forcing Black to make a decision: weaken either the b5 or d5 square. The natural way to play is to try to get a symmetrical position, but White is more dynamic and obtains a good position as we will see.} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 {Taking with the queen is Black's best continuation.} 11. Bg2 Qd7 12. O-O Rd8 13. c3 {With a pleasant position for White, who will probably play Nf3, Re1, Ne5 next.} *

