1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... e5 {Black takes the center for himself - the downside of the King's Indian.} (4... Nf6 5. c4 {transposes.}) 5. d3 Nc6 {Black can decide to start with this move, which keeps the kingside flexible (the g8-knight won't necessarily go to e7) or with 5... Ne7 keeping the queenside flexible (the b8-knight won't necessarily go to c6).} 6. Nc3 ({After failing to find anything with both} 6. e4 {and}) (6. Nbd2 {, I've tried a few more things, and concluded this was the best try, However, with perfect play, Black is able to equalize. But this is chess! Trust me, if you know more than your opponent he'll be under psychological pressure and will most of the time fail to find the best moves!}) 6... Nge7 7. e4 dxe4 (7... d4 8. Ne2 {followed by Ne1 and f4, and White gets a perfect reversed King's Indian and can start an attack. It's all in the title: King's Indian Attack!}) 8. dxe4 O-O 9. Nd5 (9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Nb5 Rd7 {does not lead anywhere.}) (9. Nb5 Be6 $1 {is fine for Black as} 10. Qxd8 Raxd8 11. Nxc7 $6 {is met with} Bc4 12. Re1 Nb4 $1 {$15}) 9... Nxd5 (9... Be6 $6 10. c4 $14) 10. exd5 Nd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Qd3 $5 Bf5 14. Qb5 {White is able to put some pressure, even if Black should hold with precise play.} *

