1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 $1 ({The most challenging move.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {was popular at some point but after} Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 {with the idea of ... Ne6, it turns out Black is too solid.}) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nc3 $1 ({Black already has a difficult decision to make.} 11. f4 $2 {would be strong if it wasn't met by} g5 $3 12. g4 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Bxg4 $1 14. hxg4 h5 {with huge problems for White.}) 11... Nxe5 (11... f6 $5 {$146 deserves attention, although after} 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Qa4 Be7 14. e4 dxe4 15. Bg5 $5 O-O 16. Qb3+ {followed by Qxb7, White is slightly better.}) 12. g4 Bg6 13. f4 Bc5+ 14. e3 {Black loses a piece but White should be careful.} Nd3 15. f5 Nxc1 16. Qxc1 (16. Kh1 $5 {is an interesting prophylaxis, which keeps a big advantage as well.}) 16... Qe7 17. Rf3 O-O-O 18. Ne2 {Rerouting the knight to d4 or f4.} h5 19. fxg6 fxg6 20. Nf4 ({And White is just winning.} 20. gxh5 Rdf8 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Nd4 gxh5 {became less clear in Svane - Lettieri, chess.com 2022.}) *

