1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 $1 ({The most challenging move.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {was popular at some point but after} Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 {with the idea of ... Ne6, it turns out Black is too solid.}) 9... Ne4 10. Bxe4 (10. Nd2 {was Grischuk's try, but after the simple} Nxd2 {(instead of 10... f5)} 11. Bxd2 Be7 {I am not sure why White should be better.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nc3 f6 (11... f5 $2 12. Qb3 {is very problematic for Black.}) 12. Nc4 (12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Kh2 Bg6 $13 {Chos - Keymer, chess.com 2023.}) 12... Nb6 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Nxe4 (14. Be3 $5 {$146 Qd7 15.d5 Qxh3 16.dxc6 bxc6 17.Qc2 looks like a fine try, but after 17...Qe6 17...Kf7 18.Qxe4 Qe6 isn't bad either. 18.Bxb6 f5 Black seems to be doing well.}) 14... Qd7 {Unfortunately, objectively Black has enough compensation for the pawn. Practically speaking, again, a pawn is a pawn!} 15. Kh2 Bf7 16. Nc3 (16. a3 {Just avoid losing the a2-pawn once and for all.} Be7 17. Nc3 b5 18. Be3 O-O {seems to give Black enough compensation, though in practice, I would definitely prefer to be a pawn up, as there's nothing too concrete coming.}) (16. Be3 h5 17. f3 {is a possible try, with the idea to solidly meet ...h4 with g4. In the chapter, we will explore this line [/variation/35968166] in more detail.}) *

