1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... Bf5 3. Bg2 {will transpose.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bf5 (4... h6 {This prepares ...Bf5, making sure the bishop can hide on h7 if necessary.} 5. c4 Bf5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. d3 {We are going to transpose into similar positions as the main line, where ...h6 has cost a tempo and hasn't been particularly useful.}) 5. c4 e6 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. d3 {Playing with d3 makes perfect sense against ...Bf5 setups, so the black bishop is limited.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 {As usual, we wait for ...Nbd7 before taking on d5.} Qxb3 9. axb3 exd5 10. Bd2 ({Whatever Black does here, White's plan will remain the same. Starting} 10. Nd4 {followed by Bd2 also makes sense, preventing few options, like ...Nc5 followed by ...Bd7.}) 10... Bd6 11. Bc3 O-O 12. b4 {It makes the d4 square safe for the knight's jump.} Rfe8 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. Nd2 a6 15. N2b3 $14 {White has an enjoyable endgame, where Black is solid but has no plan at all. Svane - Quesada Perez, chess.com 2022.} *

