1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} b5 {The most sensible move for Black: starting a counter-attack on the queenside.} 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 a5 {Again, keeping the queenside expansion is the most sensible way to play.} 11. h4 b4 12. N1h2 a4 13. Ng4 a3 ({Here only two moves have been played according to the database:} 13... Ba6 {and}) (13... a3 {.}) (13... h5 $2 {$146 is always too weakening:} 14. Ngh2 Qc7 15. Bf4 {and the h5-pawn will become a target.}) 14. bxa3 bxa3 15. h5 h6 16. c3 $5 {We want to control the d4-square and also stop any possible central break, as again ...c4 allows d4 and ...d4 allows c4. Black is again under heavy pressure.} (16. Bxh6 $4 gxh6 17. Qd2 {fails again to} Nd4 $1 {-+}) (16. Nxh6+ gxh6 17. Bxh6 Kh8 {is at least fine for Black. In the chapter, we will explore this line [/variation/32014192] in more detail.}) *

