1. Nf3 c5 {A frequent move against 1. c4, but less so against 1. Nf3. The reason is simple: only Sicilian players can play it, as here White can play 2. e4 and transpose! Something I regularly do myself. I also like 2. c4 systems, but this is a KIA course so let's go for 2. g3!} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O (4. c4 {will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters (with ...Nf6 and ... c5) or one of the next ones.}) 4... d5 ({The same goes for} 4... Nc6 5. c4 {etc., this too will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters.}) 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3 Ne7 8. c4 {Of course we can't afford to leave Black to dominate the center.} d4 (8... dxc4 $2 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Na5 {is just awful for Black.}) 9. e3 O-O 10. exd4 exd4 {The previous moves were pretty much forced, or at least very natural. Now we need to make the d4-pawn a weakness and not a strength.} 11. Re1 $5 {The rook can't be bad there! We keep the option of not playing Bf4 right away depending on Black's next move.} Nbc6 12. Bf4 Be6 13. Na3 $5 ({Putting the knight on the edge may look weird, but we couldn't afford} 13. N1d2 {due to} g5 {. The knight isn't that bad yet, as it can sometimes jump to b5, while the other one is about to jump to c5.}) ({Now, after} 13. Na3 {, a sample line could be} d3 14. Qd2 Qb6 {Preventing Nc5.} 15. Qxd3 $5 Bxb2 16. Nb5 Bxa1 17. Rxa1 {With enormous compensation, e.g.} Rac8 18. Nd6 Rfd8 19. Nxc8 Rxd3 20. Nxb6 axb6 21. Bf1 $14 {and the black rook has to return while White enjoys the bishop pair.}) *

