1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Nf6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {This move transposes into similar positions as chapter 1 (lines with 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5), but Black had time to play ...d6 and ... Bd7 without having to sacrifice a pawn (...d6 Nxc6 bxc6 Bxc6). That means it is worth some attention.} 9. Nc2 $5 {It makes sense to keep as many pieces as possible due to our space advantage.} (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c5 d5 $1 {doesn't give White any advantage, e.g.} 11. e4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 O-O 14. Qc2 a5 {with equality.}) 9... h5 $5 {A logical reaction to a queenside move (Nc2).} 10. h4 ({The usual reaction is} 10. h3 {but this position is quite unique, as here it would be met with} Qc8 11. Kh2 $2 Ne5 12. b3 h4 $1 13. g4 Nexg4+ 14. hxg4 Nxg4+ {and the c3-knight is hanging: Black wins.}) 10... Ng4 11. Nd5 $1 {A good move here, though it is unusual to play it so early. We're taking advantage of the fact that the f6-knight is gone and the g5-square empty. In two games played by Ambartsumova, White got all she could dream of, though she only scored 0,5/2.} Rc8 (11... O-O 12. Rb1 Qa5 13. a3 Nf6 $6 14. Bg5 $16 {Ambartsumova - Pranav, chess.com 2023.}) 12. Rb1 $1 O-O 13. b3 $14 {Bb2 will follow and White enjoys a small but stable advantage.} *

