1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ {One of the two possible moves for Black.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best try, I believe. After} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Ne7 $1 {I could not even find a good continuation for White.}) 9... exd5 10. Nd6+ Kf8 11. O-O ({Critical. I've also checked} 11. Nxc8 Rxc8 12. O-O {but after} Nf6 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. e3 h5 $1 15. exd4 Bh6 16. Bxh6+ {it seemed pretty clear that Black had equalized in Iturrizaga, E (2607)-Pulvett, D (2476) Benasque 2021, when a draw was immediately agreed.}) 11... Be6 {One of the three natural moves.} 12. e4 $146 ({Oye! Let's go for a mess!} 12. Nf3 Qb4 13. Bf4 h6 {was played in Wojtaszek, R (2676) -Dominguez Perez, L (2739) Baku 2023, ½-½ (44), when I am not convinced White can really create problems.}) (12. Nxb7 Qb6 13. Nd6 $2 Rd8 {just loses the knight.}) 12... dxe3 (12... dxe4 $4 13. N2xe4 {with ideas like Nxb7 or Ng5 is just horrific for Black (the eval is already +2.5!).}) 13. Nb3 $1 ({The point. Let's give another pawn!} 13. fxe3 $2 Qb4 {just traps the d6-knight.}) 13... exf2+ {This is another crazy line.} 14. Rxf2 Qc7 $1 (14... Qb6 $2 15. Bxd5 {with serious problems.}) 15. Bf4 Be5 $1 {The best defense according to the engine, not letting White demolish Black's position on the dark squares.} 16. Nxb7 $1 Bxf4 17. N7c5 {Black is under huge pressure, but can hold with precise play. In chapter 21, we will explore this line [/variation/33970856] in more detail.} *

