1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} Nf6 $6 3. e4 $1 {'It is always too early to move the f-pawn' goes one of the most famous chess sayings (unfortunately, I cannot remember to whom it was attributed!). It simply means that playing ...f5 or ...f6 (or f4 or f3 as White) is always a weakening move. In this case, we use Black's early ...f5 to open the position as long as Black's king remains in the center.} d6 4. exf5 {White aims to follow up with d4, Bd3, and Black has problems on the light squares, and especially e6.} Bxf5 5. d4 Qd7 6. Nc3 {Following Magnus' steps is quite safe.} Nc6 (6... g6 $6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. O-O Nc6 9. d5 $1 {White is going to enjoy the e6-square very much!} Nb4 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. a3 Na6 12. Nd4 $16 {Carlsen - Rodriguez Vila, Caxias do Sul 2014.}) 7. Bb5 $146 a6 (7... e6 8. d5 exd5 9. O-O {! is similar to the mainline.}) 8. Ba4 e6 9. d5 $1 exd5 10. O-O $1 {There is no hurry to take the pawn back.} Be7 (10... O-O-O {?} 11. Nd4 $1 b5 12. Ncxb5 $1 {+-}) 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Be6 13. Qe4 {White is threatening Nd4.} b5 14. Bb3 Bxb3 15. axb3 O-O 16. c3 {White enjoys a slight advantage.} *

