1. Nf3 {Let's now have a look at b-pawn moves, which are very dubious for Black.} b6 2. e4 {We've transposed to an Owen Defense where White did not have time to play 3. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 to protect the e4-pawn without playing Nc3. The whole line remains quite dubious for Black anyway.} Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 Bb4 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. Nd2 $1 (6. Qe2 d5 $1 {with the idea of} 7. e5 Ne4 {isn't clear at all.}) 6... d5 7. e5 Ne4 8. Qg4 $1 Nxc3 $2 {This would be even worse than 8... Kf8, which we will see in chapter 24.} 9. Qxg7 Rf8 10. a3 $1 Ba5 11. b4 $1 Nc6 12. bxa5 Nxd4 13. a4 $16 ({Likely followed by Ba3. If} 13. Bb2 $6 {Black is lucky not to lose at once thanks to} Nf5 $1 14. Bxf5 Na4 {although he's far from having a healthy position.}) *

