1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 d6 {Transposes into a regular King's Indian with g3, where Black has this line as an option, called the Panno Variation.} 8. d5 Na5 {This knight move on the rim may seem awkward, but Black hits the c4-pawn. Winning this tempo will enable him to act fast in the center.} 9. Nd2 e6 10. Rb1 exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 {Now that the c4-pawn is gone, Black acts on the queenside.} b5 13. b3 {At first this could look like a good Benoni for Black, but the a5-knight is offside and White will take advantage of it. Next is probably Bb2 and then White will push his central pawns as in the game Vih - Scekic, Cetinje 2013.} *

