1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 d6 {Transposes into a regular King's Indian with g3, where Black has this line as an option, called the Panno Variation.} 8. d5 Na5 {This knight move on the rim may seem awkward, but Black hits the c4-pawn. Winning this tempo will enable him to act fast in the center.} 9. Nd2 a6 ({The main line.} 9... Rb8 10. Qc2 a6 11. b3 b5 {just transposes to 9... a6.}) (9... e5 10. e4 a6 11. Re1 Bd7 12. Bf1 Rb8 13. a3 {is just a nice King's Indian for White: what is the black knight doing on a5?}) 10. Rb1 Rb8 {Black wants to prepare ...b5.} 11. Qc2 {We decide to simply allow ...b5 and play against the a5-knight.} b5 12. b3 e5 (12... e6 {is a loss of time compared to 12... e5. Here I like} 13. e3 $5 {when after} e5 {Black could transpose to 12... a5 by pushing e3-e4, but instead} 14. Bb2 {keeping both options of playing e4 and f4!? seems stronger.}) (12... bxc4 $6 13. bxc4 Rxb1 14. Ncxb1 {is just pretty bad for Black due to the horribly placed a5-knight.}) 13. e4 {Let's make it simple and play for space. The a5-knight problem remains.} Bd7 {Let's now follow an online game, Giri-Fressinet.} 14. Bb2 (14. Nd1 $5 {to bring the knight to d3 as above also makes sense, and may even be stronger.}) 14... h5 15. Ne2 h4 16. Bc3 b4 17. Bb2 {White lost two tempi but with the queenside totally closed, the a5-knight is really useless. Note this is a double-edged position where I prefer White, and moves from both sides aren't forced.} Nb7 18. Rbe1 Qe7 19. Qd3 a5 20. f4 $1 hxg3 {And now Giri took a bad decision.} 21. Nxg3 $1 (21. hxg3 $2 Ng4 22. Nf3 a4 {was quite fine for Black and even ended in a victory for Black in the game Giri - Fressinet, chess24.com 2020.}) 21... exf4 22. Nf5 $1 gxf5 23. exf5 Qd8 24. Rxf4 Re8 25. Be4 $1 {And Black is so paralyzed that White's attack on the kingside will be decisive. Next could be Kh1, Qh3...} *

