1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} Ne5 10. Qe2 d6 11. Bd2 (11. h3 $5 {also makes sense to me, with the idea to fight} Qb4 {with} 12. f4 $1 {since} Nxc4 $2 {loses a piece to} 13. a3 Qc5 14. b4) 11... Bg4 12. f3 Bd7 13. b3 Rfc8 14. Rac1 a6 {Again, White enjoys a nice space advantage and easy-to-play position, as in Sadhwani - Bakalchuk, chess.com 2020, but here I would recommend to simply play Nd5.} 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bc3 Z0 ({And White is simply better. If} 17... Nc6 {(otherwise, next could be Rfd1 or Qb2) White can play} 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Bxf6 exf6 20. Rfd1 {and his advantage is pretty clear.}) *

