1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Qc5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {Sure, the d5-square is now covered, but Black's structure is inflexible and ... b5 is no longer a worry.} 12. b3 (12. Rc1 $5 {is possible as well.}) 12... Qb6 (12... d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rc1 Qd6 {was played in Vachier-Lagrave - Ragger, Novi Sad 2016, and here instead of} 15. e4 {I believe White should have played 15.Nb5! Qd7 16.Nc7! $146 Rb8 17.Bc3! $16 and next could be Be5, Bd4, or simply Nxd5. Black has concrete problems.}) 13. Na4 $146 {Attacking the queen and making room for the bishop on c3.} Qc7 14. Bc3 {This is pleasant for White: Black's structure is inflexible and White will try to push e4 soon.} *

