1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Qc5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {Sure, the d5-square is now covered, but Black's structure is inflexible and ... b5 is no longer a worry.} 12. b3 (12. Rc1 $5 {is possible as well.}) 12... Rb8 13. Rc1 Bd7 14. e4 (14. h3 $5 {followed by e4, Kh2, is also very pleasant for White.}) 14... Qh5 15. Qxh5 Nxh5 16. Be3 c5 17. f4 $14 Z0 ({White has a very pleasant space advantage. Here Black tried to complicate matters with} 17... Bd4 {in the only existing game (Nihal- Navara, chess24.com 2020), and instead of Kf2, White could have obtained a decisive advantage playing:} 18. Bxd4 $1 {$146 cxd4 19.Nd5 e6 20.Ne7+! Kh8 21.e5! and the power of White's queenside (especially the c-pawn) together with the weakness of Black's d4-pawn make White's position close to winning.}) *

