1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Bd7 11. b3 $5 (11. Rc1 $5 {is possible as well.}) 11... Rfc8 {This is a more logical way for Black to place his rook. The one on a8 may go to b8 to help Black push ...b5 after ...a6 (and after there is no vis-à-vis between the d2-bishop and the black queen, obviously)} 12. h3 $5 {Strong GM's favorite move. It prevents ideas like ...Bg4 and also makes g4 possible in the event of ... Qh5. But let's be clear that White is generally a bit better almost whatever he does.} Rab8 (12... a6 13. Qe2 Qd8 14. Rac1 Rab8 15. Rfe1 {was just nice for White in Fedoseev - Duda, Riyadh 2017, 1-0.}) 13. Qe2 $146 {Intending to continue with Rfd1, Rac1, seems to me like the best plan. Black is still far away from managing ...b5.} a6 14. Rac1 Qd8 15. Rfe1 $5 Na7 ({A clever prophylactic move, as the} 15... Nxd4 {alternative shows.}) (15... Nxd4 $2 16. exd4 b5 17. cxb5 axb5 {now allows} 18. Qxe7) 16. a4 {White simply prevents ...b5, and after 16...Nc6 Black will have to stay passive when White has free hands to improve his position slowly and one day go Nd5 or e4.} (16. Red1 $5 b5 17. cxb5 Nxb5 18. Ncxb5 axb5 19. Nc2 {followed by Nb4 should be a bit better for White too.}) *

