1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Qa6 $6 (10... Nxd4 $6 11. exd4 {is just a favourable structure for White, who can now put pressure on the e-file and continue enjoying his space advantage.}) 11. b3 Bg4 (11... Bd7 {occurred twice in two Oparin's games,} 12. Qe2 Rac8 13. Rac1 Rfd8 {and here I thik best for White would be} 14. Ndb5 $1 {$146 Qb6 15.e4 and Black has big problems getting rid off the b5-square since 15...a6?? loses the queen to 16.Na4+-}) 12. Qe1 (12. Qc1 $5 {wasn't bad either in Meier - Bacrot, Dubai 2014, 1-0. But I find more logical to avoid a vis-à-vis with a black rook on c8.}) 12... Rac8 13. Nc2 $146 (13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. h3 Bd7 15. e4 c5 16. f4 Bc6 {was no more than a little better for White in Giri - Navara, 2016.}) 13... Ne5 14. f3 Bd7 15. f4 {Time for White to push Black's pieces backwards.} Nc6 (15... Nd3 16. Qe2 Nc5 17. e4 {is probably even worse for Black.}) 16. e4 {With a wonderful position for White.} *

