1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5 {A tricky move that gained popularily some 5-10 years ago, but that we don't see very often nowadays.} 9. e3 {This is the latest trend, preventing some possible ... Qh5 and consolidating the d4-knight's position.} d6 {The best move. Alternatives lead to an easy advantage for White.} 10. Bd2 Bg4 $2 ({This is a blunder.} 10... Ne5 11. b3 {only helps White.}) 11. Nd5 $1 Bxd1 (11... Qd8 $2 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Qxg4) 12. Bxa5 {And White wins a clean pawn and Black is left with several weaknesses.} Nxd5 (12... Nxa5 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 14. Raxd1) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. cxd5 Bc2 {And now the strongest is Rac1!} 15. Rac1 $1 Bd3 16. Rfd1 Bxb2 17. Rxd3 Bxc1 18. dxc6 {And c7 next, as in the game Thybo - Chatalbashev, Svendborg 2021.} *

