4. Be3 Qe5 15. Rfd1 {And, although it took me time to believe it, it seems like Black is indeed under pressure. For example} Qa5 16. Nd5 Re8 {16...Qd8?! 17.c5 $16} 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Rd5 $1 {a nice maneuver.} Qa6 {18...Qd8?! 19.Rb5 $16} 19. Rb5 Rb8 20. Rb4 Bd7 21. Rxb7 Rxb7 22. Bxb7 Qa5 23. Bd5 Rc8 24. h4 Kg7 {and here Black should equalize, but precision was required. Anyhow, I definitely prefer 11. Re1.}) 11... Bg4 $5 (11... Qxb2 $2 12. Rb1 Qa3 13. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 14. Nxc6 {and White is much better thanks to the brilliant point} Re8 15. Nxe7+ $1 Rxe7 16. Qf3 {winning the piece back!}) 12. Qb3 $1 {Sort of an improvement of the more usual 11. Qb3.} (12. f3 $2 {would weaken the a7-g1 diagonal too badly and simply allow} Nxd4 $6) 12... Qc7 $146 {The most natural move: threatening ... Na5.} (12... Rfc8 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. b3 $16 {Donchenko - Narayanan, chess24.com 2020.}) 13. h3 Bd7 14. Rac1 $14 Z0 ({And Nd5 is coming, while the c4-pawn is untouchable:} 14... Na5 $2 15. Qd1 Nxc4 $2 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 b5 18. b3) *

