1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Qd3 {This queen retreat avoids potential problems on the h8-a1 diagonal. However White will have to watch out for ...Bf5 or a knight coming to e5. Now best and most played move is 10... a6. Other moves lead to an easy small advantage for White.} Be6 11. Bd2 Qd7 ({After} 11... Qc8 12. b3 Bh3 13. Rac1 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qc6+ 15. f3 e6 16. Rfd1 {GM Svidler played a model game up to some point, but eventually couldn't win:} Rad8 17. Bf4 Rd7 18. Qe3 b6 19. Rd3 Rc8 20. Qd2 Ne8 21. e4 $16 {Svidler - Kramnik, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014.}) 12. Rfd1 Ng4 13. b3 Ne5 14. Qe4 $1 {A nice idea, maneuvring the queen to h4. If the dark-squared bishops get traded Black will have zero counterplay.} Rab8 15. Rac1 Bf5 16. Qh4 Bf6 17. Bg5 Bxg5 18. Qxg5 $16 {Again, White has a pleasant edge. Kramnik - Anand, Moscow 2009.} *

