1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Qd3 {This queen retreat avoids potential problems on the h8-a1 diagonal. However White will have to watch out for ...Bf5 or a knight coming to e5. Now best and most played move is 10... a6. Other moves lead to an easy small advantage for White.} Bf5 {Black forces e2-e4 which takes extra space but has the down side of cutting the g2-h1 diagonal.} 11. e4 Be6 {White has two good moves here.} 12. Bd2 $5 ({This consolidates White's edge. He is likely to play b3 next, only when necessary.} 12. b3 $5 {is also for White, if for any reason you would like to investigate it. In both cases, Black's counterplay is not enough to compensate White's space advantage.}) 12... Ng4 (12... a6 13. b3 Nd7 14. a4 Ne5 15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Rab1 {transposes.}) (12... Nd7 13. b3 Ne5 {transposes to 12... Ng4.}) (12... Qc8 13. b3 Bh3 14. Rac1 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {is also an easy advantage for White, as in Cheparinov - Petrov, Kozloduy 2018, ½-½.}) (12... Qd7 13. b3 Bh3 14. Rad1 $14 {has no particular value for Black.}) 13. b3 {It's time to protect the c4-pawn.} Ne5 14. Qc2 $1 ({The easiest way to go.} 14. Qe3 a6 15. Rac1 {allowed} b5 {in Zilka - Plat, Zlin 2021, although here} 16. f4 $5 Nc6 17. e5 $1 Bd7 18. Nd5 dxe5 19. Bc3 bxc4 20. fxe5 cxb3 21. axb3 {deserves investigation.}) 14... a6 15. a4 Rc8 16. Rab1 $14 {White will regroupe his pieces, eventually ending with the bishop on e3 and queen on d2, and be better, He should just watch out for ...b5.} *

