1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 d5 $6 {This move just gives a pawn, although with perfect play Black may be able to draw. But who would want to suffer this way from the start of the game?} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd4 11. Bg5 Re8 (11... Nc6 $6 {is even worse.} 12. Qa4 $1 h6 13. Be3 Bd7 14. Rfd1 Nd4 15. Qb4 e5 {15...Nc2? 16.Nxe7+ Kh8 17.Qxb7+-} 16. Rd2 {White is clearly better. Next could be Bxd4 and Qxb7, or simply f4.}) 12. e3 Nc6 13. Nxe7+ (13. Qa4 h6) 13... Nxe7 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bxe7 Re8 {Now it is a question there to put the bishop, all options leading to a slight advantage.} 16. Bd6 Z0 ({I believe this is White's best chance. The game may continue with} 16... Bxb2 17. Rab1 Be5 18. Bxe5 Rxe5 19. Bxb7 Rb8 20. Bxc8 Rxc8 21. Rb2 {and Black will suffer for a very long time - if he can save the game!}) *

