1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 d6 $5 {A very interesting pawn sac, which I consider important for the assessment of the whole line. This is one of the three main moves, together with 8... Qa5 and 8... Nxd4.} 9. Nxc6 {I believe accepting the pawn sacrifice is the best try for an advantage.} (9. Nc2 $5 Be6 10. b3 Qd7 {followed by ...Bh3, a bishop trade, ...e6 trying to push ...d5, sometimes a6 to push ...b5, is very reasonable for Black. The move Nc2 has weakened the h8-g7 diagonal and I believe White might be symbolically better, but I prefer my suggestion. If you want to dig into this,} 11. e4 Bh3 12. Qe2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 a6 {followed by ...e6 should be the thing to look at.}) 9... bxc6 10. Bxc6 Bh3 $2 {After this natural move, that Black generally plays in blitz games, Black will stay a pawn down and never get it back.} 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. f3 Bxf1 13. Kxf1 Qc8 $5 (13... Rc8 14. Qd3 Qc6 15. Be3 {Targeting a7.} Qxc4 {15...a6 16.Rc1 Qxc4? 17.Nd5!} 16. Qxc4 Rxc4 17. Bxa7 Nd7 18. Nd1 {18.a4!?} Rc2 19. Rb1 {was an easy win for White in Harikrishna - Hambleton, Canada 2015.}) 14. Qd3 $1 ({After} 14. Be3 Qxc4 15. Bxa7 Nd7 {Black has problems too, but for exemple after} 16. Nd5 Bxb2 17. Nxe7+ Kg7 18. Rb1 Qxa2 19. Qc2 Qxa7 20. Qxb2+ Ne5 21. Nd5 Qc5 22. Nb6 Qc6 {Black won't have fun but should be able to save himself. There might be better moves than 16.Nd5 in this line, but anyhow I like my recommendation on move 15.}) 14... Nd7 15. Bf4 $1 h6 ({Perhaps the best try.} 15... Ne5 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Rc1 {is just a big extra pawn.}) 16. Rd1 $5 (16. Rc1 $5 g5 17. Be3 Ne5 18. Qe4 {is much better for White as well, although Black can push ...f5 to complicate the game a bit.}) 16... g5 17. Nd5 Re8 18. Bc1 Z0 ({And after, for instance,} 18... Ne5 {Black gets his pawn back but remains in big trouble, e.g.} 19. Qc2 Nxc4 20. b3 Qh3+ 21. Kg1 Nb6 22. Qc6 Qd7 23. Qxd7 Nxd7 24. Be3 $16 {with the idea of Rc1.}) *

