1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 d6 $5 {A very interesting pawn sac, which I consider important for the assessment of the whole line. This is one of the three main moves, together with 8... Qa5 and 8... Nxd4.} 9. Nxc6 {I believe accepting the pawn sacrifice is the best try for an advantage.} (9. Nc2 $5 Be6 10. b3 Qd7 {followed by ...Bh3, a bishop trade, ...e6 trying to push ...d5, sometimes a6 to push ...b5, is very reasonable for Black. The move Nc2 has weakened the h8-g7 diagonal and I believe White might be symbolically better, but I prefer my suggestion. If you want to dig into this,} 11. e4 Bh3 12. Qe2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 a6 {followed by ...e6 should be the thing to look at.}) 9... bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {White is facing a concrete problem with his c4-pawn, as playing b3 weakeneds the h8-a1 diagonal. Here I believe the most natural move, a retreat to g2, is the best try.} 11. Bg2 {)} (11. b3 Bh3 12. Bg2 {12.Re1?? Ng4! threatening ...Bxc3 and ...Qxb6 is a nasty trick.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Ne4 {is immediately fine for Black.}) ({I have also tried the move} 11. Qa4 {in order to prevent 11... Qa5 (the only annoying move after 11. Bg2) but found out that Black has enough counterplay after} Bh3 {11...Bd7 12.Bb5! $16 would be White's hope.} 12. Bg2 {12.Rd1 a5! = $13} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qd7 $1 14. Rb1 Qxa4 {14...Qe6!? is playable too.} 15. Nxa4 Rfc8 16. c5 dxc5 17. Be3 Nd5 $1 {$146 17...c4?! 18.Bxa7 Rb4 19.Nc3 $14 Kramnik - Topalov, Monte Carlo 1997.} 18. Bxc5 Bxb2 19. Bxa7 Ra8 {with total equality.}) 11... Qa5 $1 {Most moves allow 12.b3, making White's task easy. Now White has problems protecting his c4-pawn.} (11... Be6 $2 12. b3) (11... Qc7 $2 12. b3 d5 13. Nb5 $5 {+- followed by Bf4.}) 12. Qc2 {Again, I believe this is the best practical try. Black needs to find many only moves in order to escape. Here for the last time for a while, Black has two options that should hold a draw with perfect play.} (12. Nb5 Bb7 $1 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Bd2 Qa6 15. Bc3 Rc8 16. b3 d5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxd5 Bxa1 19. Rxa1 Rbb8 {and Black should easily be able to make a draw.}) 12... Bb7 $5 {Should hold as well.} 13. Bd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rfc8 15. b3 d5 $1 {Here's the problem. Now White should try to give the pawn back in a way that he keeps some pressure.} 16. Qd3 (16. Na4 $6 Qa6 17. Bf4 Rb7 18. c5 e5 $1 {$132}) (16. Rab1 dxc4 17. bxc4 Rb4 $1 {should be equal as well.}) 16... dxc4 17. bxc4 Qa6 18. Rab1 Ra8 19. Qf3 Qxc4 20. Rb7 {Black should be able to hold, as the position is very symetrical, but at least White has some pleasant pressure.} *

