1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nc3 c5 .}) (6... d6 7. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 6...Nc6 7.d4 d6 .}) 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 d6 $5 {A very interesting pawn sac, which I consider important for the assessment of the whole line. This is one of the three main moves, together with 8... Qa5 and 8... Nxd4.} 9. Nxc6 {I believe accepting the pawn sacrifice is the best try for an advantage.} (9. Nc2 $5 Be6 10. b3 Qd7 {followed by ...Bh3, a bishop trade, ...e6 trying to push ...d5, sometimes a6 to push ...b5, is very reasonable for Black. The move Nc2 has weakened the h8-g7 diagonal and I believe White might be symbolically better, but I prefer my suggestion. If you want to dig into this,} 11. e4 Bh3 12. Qe2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 a6 {followed by ...e6 should be the thing to look at.}) 9... bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {White is facing a concrete problem with his c4-pawn, as playing b3 weakeneds the h8-a1 diagonal. Here I believe the most natural move, a retreat to g2, is the best try.} 11. Bg2 (11. b3 Bh3 12. Bg2 {12.Re1?? Ng4! threatening ...Bxc3 and ...Qxb6 is a nasty trick.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Ne4 {is immediately fine for Black.}) ({I have also tried the move} 11. Qa4 {in order to prevent 11... Qa5 (the only annoying move after 11. Bg2) but found out that Black has enough counterplay after} Bh3 {11...Bd7 12.Bb5! $16 would be White's hope.} 12. Bg2 {12.Rd1 a5! = $13} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qd7 $1 14. Rb1 Qxa4 {14...Qe6!? is playable too.} 15. Nxa4 Rfc8 16. c5 dxc5 17. Be3 Nd5 $1 {$146 17...c4?! 18.Bxa7 Rb4 19.Nc3 $14 Kramnik - Topalov, Monte Carlo 1997.} 18. Bxc5 Bxb2 19. Bxa7 Ra8 {with total equality.}) 11... Qa5 $1 {Most moves allow 12.b3, making White's task easy. Now White has problems protecting his c4-pawn.} (11... Be6 $2 12. b3) (11... Qc7 $2 12. b3 d5 13. Nb5 $5 {+- followed by Bf4.}) 12. Qc2 {Again, I believe this is the best practical try. Black needs to find many only moves in order to escape. Here for the last time for a while, Black has two options that should hold a draw with perfect play.} (12. Nb5 Bb7 $1 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Bd2 Qa6 15. Bc3 Rc8 16. b3 d5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qxd5 Bxa1 19. Rxa1 Rbb8 {and Black should easily be able to make a draw.}) 12... Bf5 (12... Be6 $2 13. Bd2 $1 {+- followed by 14. b3.}) 13. e4 (13. Qd2 $5 {in order to transpose into 12. Qd2 after} Be6 {makes sense as well - and the variation 12. Qb2 Bb7 has been avoided.}) 13... Be6 14. Bd2 $1 (14. b3 $6 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxa1 16. Bg5 $2 {unfortunately fails due to} Bf5 $1 {and Black keeps an extra exchange as after} 17. Rxa1 $2 Bxe4 {the g5-bishop is hanging.}) 14... Bxc4 15. Nd5 {I like this line because Black should dare to enter a line where he should find several only moves and certainly not panic. Of course, if you play it once, you may for example switch to 12. Qd2 next.} Qa6 16. Nxe7+ (16. Nc7 Qc6 17. e5 {17.Ba5 Bd5 $132} Qxc7 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. b3 Bxf1 20. Qxc7 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Bxa1 22. Qxe7 Be5 {should be an easy draw for Black, although the engine claims White is a bit better as the black pawns are weaker.}) 16... Kh8 17. e5 $5 {An interesting try, especially if your opponent's time starts ticking. It's only move 17 and Black already had to find quite a few very precise moves!} (17. Rfe1 $6 Ng8 $1 {The whole point: do you really think your opponent would be able to foresee this?} 18. Nd5 {18.Nxg8 Rxb2 19.Qc1 Kxg8 $132} Rxb2 19. Qd1 Bxd5 20. exd5 Rxa2 $132) 17... Ng4 $5 18. Nc6 $5 (18. Rfe1 Bd3 19. Qc1 dxe5 $132) 18... Rbc8 19. Rfc1 Bb5 20. Qe4 f5 21. exf6 Nxf6 22. Qf3 Z0 ({And after} 22... Ng8 23. Nb4 Rxf3 24. Nxa6 Rxc1+ 25. Rxc1 Rd3 {should be a draw as well.}) *

