1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 (7... Nc6 {transposes to the mainline.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nb3 {The only dangerous move. Black has plenty of options and I've tried to find the move tricky answers as White.} (9. Nb5 Be6 10. Nd4 Bc8 {is just a repetition.}) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {with many trades to come.}) 9... Nb4 10. Nc3 N8c6 11. Bf4 Bf5 $1 (11... Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Bf5 13. a3 Nc2 14. Rac1 {is an improvement for White over 11... Bf5.}) (11... e5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3 Nc2 15. Rad1 $1 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rf8 17. Nc5 {is unpleasant for Black.}) 12. a3 ({I believe this simple move is the best try, forcing complications.} 12. Nc5 Qb6 $5 13. N5a4 Qa6 14. Nc5 {is just a draw.}) (12. e4 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 Bg4 14. Rd2 Rad8 {is totally fine for Black too.}) 12... Nc2 13. Rc1 e5 14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Bg5 f6 16. Nc5 $146 ({The best try. A weird move leaving the g5-bishop en prise.} 16. e4 $2 {was played in the only existing game but it allows} Be6 17. Nc5 Bc8 {and Black is clearly better.}) 16... N2d4 17. Be3 b6 18. Nb7 $1 Rd7 19. Bxd4 Nxd4 20. e3 {And White wants Rcd1 next - Black is under pressure.} *

