1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 (7... Nc6 {transposes to the mainline.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nb3 {The only dangerous move. Black has plenty of options and I've tried to find the move tricky answers as White.} (9. Nb5 Be6 10. Nd4 Bc8 {is just a repetition.}) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {with many trades to come.}) 9... e6 10. h4 $5 {This has been played by Peter Svidler. White intends Bg5 and to increase the pressure on the kingside with h5 at some point.} (10. Nc3 {is the most common move, but I like my suggestion more.}) (10. e4 Nb4 11. Nc3 Nd3 12. Qe2 Nxc1 13. Raxc1 Nc6 14. Kh1 $1 {followed by f4 also deserves attention.}) 10... h6 {Should be an improvement for White as the h6-pawn would hang. Here Nc3 is possible but I also like Bd2!?} 11. Bd2 $5 Nc6 (11... Bxb2 12. Bxh6 Re8 13. N1d2 Bxa1 14. Qxa1 Qf6 15. Qb1 {followed by Ne4, with enormous compensation.}) 12. Nc3 Z0 ({White's position is more pleasant, e.g.} 12... Nxc3 13. Bxc3 {is no fun for Black: the strong g7-bishop will be traded while the g2-bishop stays.}) *

