11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Bf4 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 {Here we'll witness the most important difference with a4/...a5 included.} Nc4 {This is no longer that satisfiying. However, I believe this is the most likely to happen, as it is not easy to understand the difference with the regular 10. Nc3 line.} 14. Rdc1 Nxb2 15. Nc5 {Here White has an extra idea of playing Ra2! And this changes everything.} e5 16. Bd2 Nc4 17. Be1 Bh6 $5 (17... Rb8 $6 18. Nb5 {and Black is problems despite his extra pawn.}) (17... e4 18. Bxe4 Re8 19. Rab1 Nd6 20. Bg2 {is clearly nice for White.}) 18. e3 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Bxe3+ 20. Bf2 Bxc1 21. Rxc1 {And here White's bishop pair is really powerful - although Black has three pawns, he's quite dominated and I would pick White every day.} *

