1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 (7... Nc6 {transposes to the mainline.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nb3 {The only dangerous move. Black has plenty of options and I've tried to find the move tricky answers as White.} (9. Nb5 Be6 10. Nd4 Bc8 {is just a repetition.}) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {with many trades to come.}) 9... Nb6 {The most annoying defensive move: Black keeps playing symmetrical. I've found an interesting practical idea here, let's investigate.} (9... Be6 $6 10. Nc5 {is all White wants.}) 10. a4 $146 {We're going to include a4 and ...a5 for good reason.} (10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Bf4 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Nc4 $1 {is known to equalize. And here is the trick, with a4 and ...a5 included you'll see that this move is no longer so good.}) 10... a5 {By far the most natural answer.} 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Bf4 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 {Here we'll witness the most important difference with a4/...a5 included.} Bf5 $1 {The annoying move.} 14. Nc5 Nc4 $1 {Here I've tried two options, but against both of them Black should hold.} 15. Rac1 $5 (15. Nd5 $5 e6 {15...Bxb2 16.Ra2 Rfc8 17.Nd3 Bf6! The best square - otherwise beware to the e7-pawn. 18.Rc1 Nb4 19.N5xb4 axb4 20.Nxb4 This would be slightly unpleasant for Black.} 16. Ne3 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 Bxb2 18. Ra2 Bc3 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Rc1 Bg7 21. f3 h5 {This is no more than equal: White has compensation, nothing more.}) 15... Nxb2 (15... e5 16. Bg5 $1 h6 17. b3 $1 Nb2 18. Rd2 Nxa4 19. bxa4 hxg5 20. Nd5 {is unpleasant for Black.}) 16. Re1 {Black's coordination is doubtful.} Rae8 $1 {This is best! But I really wonder who would play such a move. Basically, it protects e7 and is prophylaxis against Nd5.} 17. Nd5 Nb4 18. Ne3 (18. Nxb4 axb4 19. Bxb7 Bc3 $13) 18... Be6 $5 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Bxb7 Nxa4 21. Bc7 Z0 ({And now unfortunately} 21... Bc3 $1 22. Red1 Na2 $1 23. Rc2 Nb4 {is just a draw.}) *

