1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 {Black plays ...Nf6 and ...g6 just like a King's Indian. No need to say this is a very classical way to play for Black.} 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 {This is my suggestion, allowing Black to transpose into different types of positions, such as the Symmetrical English, the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. I found some interesting ideas in all of these different pawn structures and even some very dangerous novelties in the sharp Grunfeld lines (if Black plays 5... d5).} c5 {The unfortunate point of the KIA move order is that here, White has two options to reach the position we want ( 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.d4 cxd4 8.Nxd4 or 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 ), and both of them give an extra possibility to play for Black. The first move order allows 6... d5 while the second one allows 7... d5), and both of them hold for Black with exact play. You'll have to choose your move order depending on your taste and feeling - in either case the White position is easier to play. 5...c6 in order to play ...d5 is the solid approach. We will cover it in the next chapter. 5...d6 in order to play like a King's Indian will be covered next. And finally, in Chapter 2, we will dive into 5...d5 to play a Grunfeld-type of position.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 $1 (7... Nc6 {transposes to the mainline.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nb3 {The only dangerous move. Black has plenty of options and I've tried to find the move tricky answers as White.} (9. Nb5 Be6 10. Nd4 Bc8 {is just a repetition.}) (9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {with many trades to come.}) 9... Nb6 {The most annoying defensive move: Black keeps playing symmetrical. I've found an interesting practical idea here, let's investigate.} (9... Be6 $6 10. Nc5 {is all White wants.}) 10. a4 $146 {We're going to include a4 and ...a5 for good reason.} (10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Bf4 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Nc4 $1 {is known to equalize. And here is the trick, with a4 and ...a5 included you'll see that this move is no longer so good.}) 10... a5 {By far the most natural answer.} 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Nc5 $5 {This is the only alternative I consider worth investigating.} Nc4 $1 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bf4 Bd4 $1 15. Nb3 Be6 $1 (15... Bg7 $6 16. Rfc1 $1 Nxb2 17. Nc5 {puts Black under immense pressure, while a4/...a5 gives White extra Ra2 ideas and a nice square on b5.}) 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxb7 Ra7 18. Be4 Z0 ({And now after} 18... Rad7 $1 {the engine claims Black has compensation, but giving away the dark-squared bishop, a pawn, to follow up with such a random move seems inhuman to me. And White is safe here - so I believe 12. Nc5 to be a good try!}) *

