1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 c5 8. Nxd5 ({White has two options:} 8. Qa4 {with a playable game where White is not necessarily better, or}) (8. Nxd5 {, going for a position that went well for White in the past, but where recent engines manage to completely egalize with precise moves.}) (8. Qa4 {Here Black has plenty of options, but my problem is that too many of them seem okay for Black.} Nc6 {The most common move - but not the best. • 8...e6!? This kind of prevents Qh4. 9.d3!? Here the two only moves that have been played in official games are 9... Nb6 and 9... Nxc3, which are both dubious. 9.Nxd5 exd5 10.d4 cxd4 11.Nxd4 Bd7 12.Qd1 Nc6 13.Be3 Qf6 seems okay for Black. 9...Nc6 9...b6 $146 seems fine too, with ideas like 10.d4 Qd7!? 11.Qb3 Bb7 12.dxc5 Na6! 13.cxb6 Nc5 14.Qc2 axb6 and very good compensation for Black. 9...Nb6?! 10.Qb5 Na6 11.Bg5 Qe8 12.Qxe8 Rxe8 was unpleasant for Black in Fressinet - Li Chao, 2016, especially had Black played 13.Ne4 $146 with a big hole on f6. 9...Nxc3?! 10.bxc3 Bxc3 11.Rb1 followed by Be3 is unpleasant for Black. While will get his pawn back and a pleasant position as in Feher - Spiriev, Zalakaros 1991, ½-½ ). 10.Ne4 10.Qc4?! no longer makes any sense after 10...b6 $15 10...Qe7 11.Bg5 f6 12.Bd2 Bd7 13.Qb3 b6 14.Nc3 Nc7 followed by ...Kh8, ...e5, and Black is fine. • 8...Nc7 9.d3 Nc6 10.Ne4 10.Qh4 e5 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 seems okay for Black. 10...Ne6 11.Be3 Bd7 $146 11...Ncd4?! 12.Nxd4 cxd4 13.Bd2 and White will soon take over the initiative: 13...Bd7 14.Qa3 Bc6 15.Rfc1 Qd7 16.Rc2 Rfc8 17.Rac1 $14 Laznicka - Efimenko, Russia 2011. 12.Nxc5 Nxc5 13.Bxc5 Nd4 14.Qd1 Nxf3+ 15.Bxf3 Bh3 and Black is fine as Re1 is met with ... Bxb2. Here White's best is 16.Qa4 Bxf1 17.Rxf1 with compensation. • 8...Nb4!? seeems very playable too. • 8...Na6!? as well.} 9. Qc4 Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qb6 $1 {10...b6 11.Ng5 followed by Qh4 is slightly unpleasant for Black.} 11. Qh4 Rd8 {The most frequent and most natural move.} 12. Ng5 $5 h6 13. Nf3 Rd5 $1 {13...Kh7?! 14.e4 would be quite unpleasant for Black, with this permanent tension on the h6-pawn.} 14. Nd2 $5 Rd8 $1 {14...Rh5?! 15.Qa4 and now it's the black rook that is awkward on h5.} 15. Nb3 h5 $1 16. Be3 Qb5 $1 {and somehow Black is just in time to equalize, after finding this series of only moves. 16.Qc4? fails to 16...Be6! 17.Qxc5?? Bxb3 18.Qxb6 axb6-+}) 8... Qxd5 9. d3 Nc6 10. Be3 {This is the second option, which has been played in more than 700 games including many top level ones. However, I believe the two main lines are very forcing and newest engines and closing it to dead equality, although in practice Black never found the accurate way to defend and almost always ended in problems.} Bd7 {The dry option. Despite White obtained good results in the past, the engine proves it to be a total equality.} (10... Bxb2 $5 11. Rb1 Bf6 $1 {At the end of the day you'll understand why protecting e7 does matter!} 12. Qa4 Qd7 13. Bxc5 b6 $1 {13...Nd4 would allow 14.Qd1 $14 and the show must go on.} 14. Bxb6 {14.Be3 Nd4 15.Qd1□ Bb7 16.Nxd4 Bxg2 17.Kxg2 Bxd4 18.Bxd4 Qxd4 is a try equality.} Nd4 $1 {The best sequence according to both theory and practice.} 15. Qd1 axb6 16. Nxd4 Rxa2 17. Nc6 Qd6 18. e3 {18.Rxb6 Bg4! and Black is better.} Bf5 19. Rxb6 Qxd3 {and Black is more than fine.}) 11. Nd4 Qd6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Rc1 Qe6 15. Rxc5 Qxa2 16. Rb5 b6 {As I said, this position gave White good results in practice, but he actually doesn't have even the slightest advantage.} 17. Qb3 (17. Qa1 Qe6 $1 {17...Qxa1?! 18.Rxa1 is no fun for Black as the white rook reaches a6, paralyzing Black's queenside, Then White will bring his king along and Black will suffer.} 18. Qa6 {18.Qa4 Rfc8= So - Mamedyarov, Bucharest 2019.} h5 $5 {One move amongst many. With queens on the board, Black is just fine. He'll put his f-rook on c8 and with kings on the board, White's advantage of paralyzing the queenside the bring his king over is not an existing plan. There is simply zero reason for Black to be worse.} 19. h4 Rfc8 $132 {1-0 Andreikin - Vokhidov, chess.com 2023.}) 17... Qxb3 18. Rxb3 Rfb8 $146 (18... Rfc8 $6 19. Ra1 {has proven a bit annoying to play for Black - his queenside is paralyzed.}) 19. Ra1 a6 $1 {Preventing a paralyzing Ra1-a6. White should allow several pawn trades or ...b5. In both cases, Black is absolutely fine.} *

