1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nc6 8. e4 Nb6 9. d5 Na5 {Now Qe1 is an interesting try, while 10. Nc3 would just transpose to our mainline.} 10. Qe1 $5 {An interesting attempt at taking advantage of Black's move order. White wants to remove the black knight from ...a5 so Black has more difficulties pushing ...c6 (as he won't be able to take back with the knight).} Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 12. Bg5 $1 {Disturbing Black's coordination.} f6 $1 (12... Qd6 $6 13. b3 $1 Ne5 14. Nd4 $1 {and the queen on d6 is quite misplaced. White's next move could be 15. Rd1.}) 13. Bc1 $1 {The bishop had done it's job - for now!} exd5 14. exd5 Bg4 $6 (14... Nd6 $6 15. a4 a5 16. Nd4 {with a huge advantage thanks to the e6-square, again.}) (14... f5 $6 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Qc1 {and again Black's kingside is weakened and it is difficult to find a good square for the c8-bishop.}) 15. h3 {Immediately questioning Black's bishop.} Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Re8 17. Qd1 f5 18. a4 a5 19. Qc2 {This is just bad for Black: Ne2-f4-e6 might come.} *

