1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nc6 8. e4 Nb6 9. d5 Na5 {Now Qe1 is an interesting try, while 10. Nc3 would just transpose to our mainline.} 10. Qe1 $5 {An interesting attempt at taking advantage of Black's move order. White wants to remove the black knight from ...a5 so Black has more difficulties pushing ...c6 (as he won't be able to take back with the knight).} Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 12. Bg5 $1 {Disturbing Black's coordination.} f6 $1 (12... Qd6 $6 13. b3 $1 Ne5 14. Nd4 $1 {and the queen on d6 is quite misplaced. White's next move could be 15. Rd1.}) 13. Bc1 $1 {The bishop had done it's job - for now!} exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 $1 {Black should take the pawn - else he's just worse with no extra material!} 15. Nd4 $1 ({The right away to continue.} 15. Nxd5 $6 Qxd5 16. Nd2 Qe6 $132) 15... c6 $2 (15... Nb4 $4 16. Ne6 {wins right away for White.}) (15... Ndb6 $6 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Bxb7 Re8 19. Qh3 Rb8 20. Bc6 {followed by Rd1, and White is better.}) 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Nxd5 {The previous sequence was forced and now Black can try to complicate matters in order to not just be clearly worse.} Re8 19. Qxe8+ $5 {But this queen sac secures a safe advantage for White.} Qxe8 20. Nc7 Qb8 21. Nxa8 Qxa8 22. Re1 {And Black is in huge trouble: if White manages to double rooks on the e-file or the 7th-rank, consequences could be decisive.} *

