1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nc6 8. e4 Nb6 9. d5 Na5 {Now Qe1 is an interesting try, while 10. Nc3 would just transpose to our mainline.} 10. Qe1 $5 {An interesting attempt at taking advantage of Black's move order. White wants to remove the black knight from ...a5 so Black has more difficulties pushing ...c6 (as he won't be able to take back with the knight).} Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 12. Bg5 $1 {Disturbing Black's coordination.} f6 $1 (12... Qd6 $6 13. b3 $1 Ne5 14. Nd4 $1 {and the queen on d6 is quite misplaced. White's next move could be 15. Rd1.}) 13. Bc1 $1 {The bishop had done it's job - for now!} exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 $1 {Black should take the pawn - else he's just worse with no extra material!} 15. Nd4 $1 ({The right away to continue.} 15. Nxd5 $6 Qxd5 16. Nd2 Qe6 $132) 15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Ne5 $1 ({The best defense.} 16... Nd6 $6 17. Re1 {followed by Bf1, Rad1, and Black's position is awful despite his extra pawn.}) 17. Rd1 ({•} 17. f4 Nf7 18. Re1 {is another way to reach good compensation. After} Re8 19. Be3 c6 20. Bf2 Bf8 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Re1 Qd8 23. Nb3 {followed by Nc5, Black remains solid but I would definitely pick White!}) ({•} 17. Re1 c6 18. f4 Nf7 19. Be3 Re8 20. Bf2 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Bf8 22. Nb3 {transposes to the line above.}) 17... Bg4 $1 {Black should find this move and the following sequence to kind of hold the balance.} (17... Qe7 18. f4 Nf7 19. Re1 {followed by Be3, Rad1, and Black is in huge trouble.}) 18. f3 c5 $1 19. fxg4 cxd4 20. Rxd4 Qe7 21. Kh1 Rad8 22. Be3 b6 23. h3 {And White does have a symbolical advantage thanks to the bishop pair, but the knight on e5 is strong and Black should easily draw this.} *

