1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} c5 $6 {A try to go for a totally symmetrical position, but known as too slow. White has two interesting ways to play.} 8. dxc5 {This is probably the simplest path to an advantage: going for a symmetrical but dynamic position.} Na6 9. Ng5 $1 {Here Black has two options, both of them not being part of the fun.} Ndb4 10. Nc3 Qxd1 (10... h6 11. Nf3 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {transposes to 10... Qxd1.}) (10... Nxc5 11. Be3 Qxd1 12. Rfxd1 Ne6 13. Rac1 {and Black is facing very serious problems.}) 11. Rxd1 h6 12. Nf3 Nc2 $1 ({The engines find this resource as best for Black.} 12... Nxc5 13. Be3 Ne6 14. Rac1) 13. Rb1 Nxc5 14. Bd2 Rd8 15. Rbc1 Nb4 16. Be3 Ne6 17. Ne1 {Followed by a3, and if ...Nc6 most probably Bxc6 and Nd3. Black has a long day ahead!} *

