1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} c5 $6 {A try to go for a totally symmetrical position, but known as too slow. White has two interesting ways to play.} 8. dxc5 {This is probably the simplest path to an advantage: going for a symmetrical but dynamic position.} Na6 9. Ng5 $1 {Here Black has two options, both of them not being part of the fun.} e6 10. Ne4 Bd7 11. Bg5 $1 {The most disturbing move. Again, provoking ...f6 is very weakening for Black, as it weakens e6 and closes the diagonal of the g7-bishop.} (11. Nbd2 $5 {also gives White a bit of pressure:} Qe7 $5 {11...f5 12.Nc3 Bc6 13.Nxd5 Bxd5 14.Nb3 and Black is under pressure.} 12. Nb3 Ba4 13. Bg5 {• 13.Qd3 Nab4 14.Qf3 f5 $132 • 13.Qe1 Rfc8 14.Bg5 Qf8!? 15.Nc3 Bc6! Black should hold this. 16.Nxd5 Bxd5 17.Bxd5 exd5 18.Be3 Bxb2 19.Rb1 Bg7 20.Qd2 d4! Getting rid of the d5-weakness. 21.Bxd4 Bxd4 22.Qxd4 Nxc5 23.Nxc5 Qxc5 24.Qxc5 Rxc5 25.Rxb7 Rc2 $132} f6 14. Bc1 f5 15. Bg5 Qc7 16. Nd6 Bxb3 17. axb3 Nxc5 18. Bxd5 Qxd6 19. Bc4 Qc6 {and Black is only symbolically worse.}) 11... Qc7 (11... f6 12. Bc1 Bc6 13. Nbc3 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxc5 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. Be3 {followed by Rfd1 and a very pleasant endgame for White.}) 12. Nbc3 Nxc3 13. Nxc3 $14 {With Rc1 to come, unless Black is willing to trade his fianchetto bishop on c3.} *

