1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} c5 $6 {A try to go for a totally symmetrical position, but known as too slow. White has two interesting ways to play.} 8. e4 {Logical. Whites takes an edge in the center.} Nf6 $1 {The most resourceful: White needs to do something in the center.} (8... Nb6 $2 9. d5 e6 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. Nc3 {would be awful for Black, who is undeveloped.}) 9. e5 {Now Black has two possibilities, and both should hold with incredibly precise play. Again White has two options, and against both Black will suffer to keep a playable position.} Nd5 {The most natural move.} 10. dxc5 Nc6 $1 (10... Na6 $2 11. Qd4 Ndb4 12. Qh4 $3 Nc2 13. Bg5 Qd7 {13...Nxa1? 14.Bxe7 Qd7 15.Bxf8 Bxf8 16.Nc3 Nc2 17.Nd5!! +- More precise than Ne4 as Rd1 may come next and perhaps some Ne7+ if the dark-squared bishop stands on g7.} 14. Nc3 Nxa1 15. Rxa1 f6 16. Qc4+ $1 {$146 16.Be3?! Qg4 17.Qxg4?! Bxg4 18.a3 Rad8 $132 1/2-1/2 Wojtaszek - Tomczak, Warsaw 2018.} Kh8 {16...Qe6 17.Nd5! is a killer.} 17. Be3 {with tremendous compensation for White.}) 11. Na3 ({The most common try.} 11. a3 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 14. Nc3 Nxe5 15. Qe2 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Rc8 {should be little for White.}) 11... Ndb4 12. Be3 Qa5 (12... Bg4 13. Qa4 Qd7 14. Nc2 a5 15. Rfd1 Qe8 16. Nxb4 axb4 17. Qb3 {is unpleasant for Black, as} Nxe5 $2 {is met with} 18. Nxe5 $1 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 Bxe5 20. Bxb7 {and the c-pawn rocks. The b4-pawn doesn't!}) (12... Qxd1 $6 13. Rfxd1 {would only help White: even if Black recovers his pawn he will have a very passive queenside.}) 13. Nc2 $146 ({White obtains a nice edge thanks to this simple move.} 13. Qe2 Bf5 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 $132 {1-0 Dmitriev - Efimov, Saratov 2008.}) 13... Nxc2 14. Qxc2 {Black will recover his pawn, but will either trade his c6-knight, leaving his queenside undefended, or his c8-bishop, simply granting White the bishop pair.} Rd8 (14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Rfd1 $16) 15. Rfd1 {White will give his pawn back and keep a nice advantage due to his extra space.} Bg4 16. Qb3 {Attacking the b7-pawn.} Qc7 17. Rac1 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Bxe5 19. Be4 $16 {Additionally to his space advantage, White’s bishop pair secures him a nice advantage.} *

