1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Na6 $6 ({Preparing ...c5.} 7... Bf5 $6 {This only makes sense if the b1-knight is already on c3. Now after} 8. Nbd2 {or 8.Re1 Black's last move doesn't make sense.}) (7... c6 $6 8. e4 {grants all the center for free.}) 8. e4 (8. Nc3 c5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Be3 {also gives White an advance: the knight on a6 is out of play.}) 8... Nb6 9. Nc3 Bg4 10. d5 Qd7 11. a4 $1 {Followed by a5, Qe2 (or Qe2 first), and we definitely cannot call this a success for Black!} *

