1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nb6 8. Nc3 ({I've tried to make} 8. Nbd2 $5 {work but didn't end up satisfied, e.g.} Nc6 9. Nb3 $146 a5 $5 10. a4 Be6 $5 {Forcing the events. Of course, this is just a variation out of many possible:} 11. Nc5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Ba6 Nd5 17. Bb5 c6 18. Bxc6 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Bxc1 20. Rbxc1 Rb4 {with a likely draw.}) 8... Nc6 9. d5 $5 (9. e3 {would transpose into the mainstream Grunfeld with g3 - 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nb6! 7.Nc3 Nc6 8.e3 O-O 9.O-O . But with the move order we used, we didn't have to push e3.}) 9... Na5 10. e4 (10. Qc2 {is the alternative but after} c6 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Rd1 Qe8 {I could not find anything for White. The proposed alternative challenges Black a lot, as he has to find lots of strong moves in order to survive.}) 10... c6 11. Bf4 {Again one line of many, but the trickiest one to handle for Black in my opinion.} Nac4 $5 {A rare move, which I believe holds for Black!} 12. Qe2 Bg4 ({This is supposed to be critical, but I believe Black has two ways to equalize:} 12... cxd5 13. exd5 e5 {and 12...e5 followed by a novelty I found for Black on move 16. That means you should choose your 12th move according to your impressions and what you think will work best in practice. A) 12.b3 is definitely a good try: 12...Bxc3 13.bxc4 Bxa1 14.Qxa1 cxd5 Other options are possible too. • 14...f6!? 15.c5 g5!? 16.Bc1 Na4 17.Qd4 b5 and White's compensation is obvious, but Black wants to play ...e5 and the engine thinks the position is unclear. • 14...Nxc4?! 15.dxc6 bxc6 16.Rc1 Nb6 17.Bh6 f6 18.Bxf8 Qxf8 19.e5 definitely looks very pleasant for White. 15.cxd5 f6 16.Bh6 Rf7 and again, White's compensation is better, but it's not like there's a killer idea coming. The assessment is probably around equal, though most people would pick White here. B) 12.dxc6 Qxd1 13.Nxd1 bxc6 14.Rb1 c5 $132 does not give White any advantage: indeed we have weakened the black pawn structure but the black pieces are too active. C) 12.Qb3 cxd5 13.Nxd5 Be6! seems like another critical position. 13...Nxd5 14.exd5 Nxb2 15.Be5! Qb6 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Rfe1!? Qxb3 18.axb3 Rd8 19.Ne5 Bf5 20.g4 Bc2 21.Re2 Rac8 22.h4 is no fun for Black with such a knight on b2. 14.Nc7 Nd2 15.Qb4 Nxf1 16.Bxf1 Bg4 17.Nxa8 Bxf3 18.Nxb6 Qxb6 19.Qxb6 axb6 20.e5 Ra8 21.a3 h6 and Black should hold. 14.Rac1 Nxb2 15.Nd2 N2a4 16.h4 may require attention: the black pieces are awkwardly placed.}) {As often, giving the bishop pair is not the correct solution for Black to equalize.} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 cxd5 15. exd5 $14 {As in the game Carlsen - Topalov, Paris 2017. We have a typical position where Black has two knights for one good square only (d6). White will increase the pressure in the center by centralizing his rooks, and then can decide to disturb the queenside with a4!? or start attacking Black’s king with h4!?. On the long term the bishop pair will also play a role, although for now the d5-pawn blocks the f3-bishop.} *

