y looks very pleasant for White. 15.cxd5 f6 16.Bh6 Rf7 and again, White's compensation is better, but it's not like there's a killer idea coming. The assessment is probably around equal, though most people would pick White here. B) 12.dxc6 Qxd1 13.Nxd1 bxc6 14.Rb1 c5 $132 does not give White any advantage: indeed we have weakened the black pawn structure but the black pieces are too active. C) 12.Qb3 cxd5 13.Nxd5 Be6! seems like another critical position. 13...Nxd5 14.exd5 Nxb2 15.Be5! Qb6 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Rfe1!? Qxb3 18.axb3 Rd8 19.Ne5 Bf5 20.g4 Bc2 21.Re2 Rac8 22.h4 is no fun for Black with such a knight on b2. 14.Nc7 Nd2 15.Qb4 Nxf1 16.Bxf1 Bg4 17.Nxa8 Bxf3 18.Nxb6 Qxb6 19.Qxb6 axb6 20.e5 Ra8 21.a3 h6 and Black should hold. 14.Rac1 Nxb2 15.Nd2 N2a4 16.h4 may require attention: the black pieces are awkwardly placed.}) 13. exd5 {Here Black has plenty of options, but I do not think any of them equalize.} (13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb6 {is easy for Black: White should keep both pairs of knights as somehow Black lacks space to find a good spot for his two knights.}) 13... e5 $1 {This is critical.} 14. Bg5 (14. dxe6 Bxe6 15. Rfd1 Bd7 16. a4 Qe8 17. a5 Qxe2 18. Nxe2 Nxb2 19. axb6 Nxd1 20. Rxd1 Ba4 {followed by ...axb6 Black should be able to draw.}) 14... f6 15. Nd2 $1 Nxb2 $1 (15... Nd6 16. Be3 {followed by a4 looks great for White.}) 16. Be3 f5 (16... N2a4 17. Nxa4 Nxa4 18. d6 $1 {threatening Qc4+ offers White much more than the required compensation.}) 17. Bxb6 (17. Qb5 N2a4 $1 18. Nxa4 Bd7 {seems okay for Black too.}) 17... axb6 18. Rab1 {And now ...e4 seems to miraculously hold for Black.} *

