ly looks very pleasant for White. 15.cxd5 f6 16.Bh6 Rf7 and again, White's compensation is better, but it's not like there's a killer idea coming. The assessment is probably around equal, though most people would pick White here. B) 12.dxc6 Qxd1 13.Nxd1 bxc6 14.Rb1 c5 $132 does not give White any advantage: indeed we have weakened the black pawn structure but the black pieces are too active. C) 12.Qb3 cxd5 13.Nxd5 Be6! seems like another critical position. 13...Nxd5 14.exd5 Nxb2 15.Be5! Qb6 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Rfe1!? Qxb3 18.axb3 Rd8 19.Ne5 Bf5 20.g4 Bc2 21.Re2 Rac8 22.h4 is no fun for Black with such a knight on b2. 14.Nc7 Nd2 15.Qb4 Nxf1 16.Bxf1 Bg4 17.Nxa8 Bxf3 18.Nxb6 Qxb6 19.Qxb6 axb6 20.e5 Ra8 21.a3 h6 and Black should hold. 14.Rac1 Nxb2 15.Nd2 N2a4 16.h4 may require attention: the black pieces are awkwardly placed.}) {This move is known to be bad - but a novelty on move 16 changes its whole assessment in my opinion. I've tried many things and could not find a real advantage for White - but my expertise is that you can enter this position betting on your practical chances, as Black's space is quite limited in several positions.} 13. Bg5 ({The alternative} 13. dxe6 {is analyzed in the next variation. [/variation/31897980]}) 13... f6 14. Bc1 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Be6 16. Rd1 {Till now, the practice has been a disaster for Black in this position.} Nd6 $146 {A powerful novelty in a way. We usually use this word for attacking/dynamic moves, but somehow this simple move powerfully equalizes.} ({•} 16... Bxd5 $2 17. Rxd5 Qc7 18. Rd3 $16 {Jakovljevic - Veleski, 2012.}) ({•} 16... Rf7 $4 17. Nxf6+ $1 Qxf6 18. Bg5 {Kizov -Nedev, Stip 2002.}) ({•} 16... Rc8 17. Nf4 Qe7 18. Nxe6 Qxe6 19. b3 $1 {$16 Jakovljevic - Zugic, Sarajevo 2007.}) 17. Ne3 (17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Be3 Qc7 {is just equal.}) (17. Nc3 Rf7 $1 18. Ne1 Bf8 19. Nd3 {with f4 next - here as well Black is under a slight pressure.}) 17... Rf7 $1 18. h4 $5 Rd7 19. h5 $5 Qe8 (19... Nxe4 20. Rxd7 Qxd7 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. Nh4 f5 23. Nxg6 Nd6 24. Bd2 Bf7 25. Nh4 f4 26. Nf1 {and White's position is a bit more pleasant.}) 20. Ne1 {Followed by b3, and I would pick White but objectively Black is fine, he should just handle a very slight pressure.} *

