1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nb6 8. Nc3 ({I've tried to make} 8. Nbd2 $5 {work but didn't end up satisfied, e.g.} Nc6 9. Nb3 $146 a5 $5 10. a4 Be6 $5 {Forcing the events. Of course, this is just a variation out of many possible:} 11. Nc5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Ba6 Nd5 17. Bb5 c6 18. Bxc6 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Bxc1 20. Rbxc1 Rb4 {with a likely draw.}) 8... Nc6 9. d5 $5 (9. e3 {would transpose into the mainstream Grunfeld with g3 - 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nb6! 7.Nc3 Nc6 8.e3 O-O 9.O-O . But with the move order we used, we didn't have to push e3.}) 9... Na5 10. e4 (10. Qc2 {is the alternative but after} c6 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Rd1 Qe8 {I could not find anything for White. The proposed alternative challenges Black a lot, as he has to find lots of strong moves in order to survive.}) 10... c6 11. Bf4 {Again one line of many, but the trickiest one to handle for Black in my opinion.} Bxc3 $5 {Lately it's been understood that if Black doesn't take the pawn, he is simply worse.} 12. bxc3 cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Nd4 $1 ({I believe this is the most dangerous move.} 14. Qe2 Qc4 {has been played twice by GM Shevchenko (as Black). He scored two wins. The idea is that Qxe7 is always met with ...Nd5.}) (14. Re1 {has been played in a game between Ragger and Cheparinov. It ended in a dry draw between two very well-prepared strong GMs.} Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Re8 {15... Be6!? is possible as well.} 16. Bg5 Nc6 17. Nd4 Bg4 $1 {Both players continue with the first computer line.} 18. Nxc6 Bxd1 19. Nxe7+ Kg7 20. Bxb7 Rad8 21. Bc6 Rf8 22. Nd5 Rd6 23. Be7 Rxc6 24. Bxf8+ Kxf8 25. Rxd1 Nxd5 26. Rxd5 Rxc3 {Ragger - Cheparinov, Aix-les-Bains 2011.}) 14... Qc5 15. Re1 (15. Nb3 {is less threatening.} Nxb3 16. axb3 Qxc3 17. Rc1 Qb4 18. Rc7 Be6 $1 {$146 18...Bf5 is not as precise, as 19.Bh6 Rfe8 20.Qa1 20.Bxb7 Rad8 21.Qa1 f6 $132 Serikbay - Assaubayeva, Warsaw 2021. 20...f6 21.Rxb7 should be unpleasant for Black.} 19. Qa1 {• 19.Rxb7 Rfd8 20.Qa1 Bd5 transposes to 19. Qa1, which is equal. • The same assessment goes for 19.Bh6 Rfe8 20.Rxb7 Qxb3 21.Qa1 f6 and now for example 22.Re1 Kf7 23.Re3 Qa2 24.Qxa2 Bxa2 25.Bc6 Be6 26.Bxe8+ Rxe8 is just a draw.} Rfd8 $1 20. Rxb7 Bd5 {is safe for Black. After} 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. Bh6 f6 {White doesn't have anything better than} 23. Rxa7 Rxa7 24. Qxa7 {with equality.}) 15... Rd8 $6 16. Qe2 e6 17. Nb5 Rd7 18. Nd4 ({Or} 18. h4 $5 {offers White enormous compensation. Unprecise is}) (18. Qe5 Qxe5 19. Bxe5 Nac4 20. Bf4 e5 $1 {= COMP Jonny - COMP Falcon, Beijing 2008.}) *

