1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d5 {Black opens the position, going for a Grunfeld-type pawn structure.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 $1 {We've reached a favorable version of the g3-Grunfeld. After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 it is known that 6...Nb6 (with the idea of 7.Nc3 Nc6 , provoking 8.e3 , and only now 8...O-O ) is more precise than 6... O-O.} Nb6 8. Nc3 ({I've tried to make} 8. Nbd2 $5 {work but didn't end up satisfied, e.g.} Nc6 9. Nb3 $146 a5 $5 10. a4 Be6 $5 {Forcing the events. Of course, this is just a variation out of many possible:} 11. Nc5 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxd4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Ba6 Nd5 17. Bb5 c6 18. Bxc6 Bxb2 19. Rb1 Bxc1 20. Rbxc1 Rb4 {with a likely draw.}) 8... Nc6 9. d5 $5 (9. e3 {would transpose into the mainstream Grunfeld with g3 - 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 Bg7 4.Bg2 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nb6! 7.Nc3 Nc6 8.e3 O-O 9.O-O . But with the move order we used, we didn't have to push e3.}) 9... Na5 10. e4 (10. Qc2 {is the alternative but after} c6 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Rd1 Qe8 {I could not find anything for White. The proposed alternative challenges Black a lot, as he has to find lots of strong moves in order to survive.}) 10... c6 11. Bf4 {Again one line of many, but the trickiest one to handle for Black in my opinion.} Bxc3 $5 {Lately it's been understood that if Black doesn't take the pawn, he is simply worse.} 12. bxc3 cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Nd4 $1 ({I believe this is the most dangerous move.} 14. Qe2 Qc4 {has been played twice by GM Shevchenko (as Black). He scored two wins. The idea is that Qxe7 is always met with ...Nd5.}) (14. Re1 {has been played in a game between Ragger and Cheparinov. It ended in a dry draw between two very well-prepared strong GMs.} Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Re8 {15... Be6!? is possible as well.} 16. Bg5 Nc6 17. Nd4 Bg4 $1 {Both players continue with the first computer line.} 18. Nxc6 Bxd1 19. Nxe7+ Kg7 20. Bxb7 Rad8 21. Bc6 Rf8 22. Nd5 Rd6 23. Be7 Rxc6 24. Bxf8+ Kxf8 25. Rxd1 Nxd5 26. Rxd5 Rxc3 {Ragger - Cheparinov, Aix-les-Bains 2011.}) 14... Qc5 15. Re1 (15. Nb3 {is less threatening.} Nxb3 16. axb3 Qxc3 17. Rc1 Qb4 18. Rc7 Be6 $1 {$146 18...Bf5 is not as precise, as 19.Bh6 Rfe8 20.Qa1 20.Bxb7 Rad8 21.Qa1 f6 $132 Serikbay - Assaubayeva, Warsaw 2021. 20...f6 21.Rxb7 should be unpleasant for Black.} 19. Qa1 {• 19.Rxb7 Rfd8 20.Qa1 Bd5 transposes to 19. Qa1, which is equal. • The same assessment goes for 19.Bh6 Rfe8 20.Rxb7 Qxb3 21.Qa1 f6 and now for example 22.Re1 Kf7 23.Re3 Qa2 24.Qxa2 Bxa2 25.Bc6 Be6 26.Bxe8+ Rxe8 is just a draw.} Rfd8 $1 20. Rxb7 Bd5 {is safe for Black. After} 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. Bh6 f6 {White doesn't have anything better than} 23. Rxa7 Rxa7 24. Qxa7 {with equality.}) 15... Bd7 $1 {For concrete reasons, this move is best. It is probably related to the fact that it develops Black's last undeveloped piece!} 16. Re5 Qa3 17. Bc1 $146 {An interesting new idea in a position that, so far, is known to be a forced draw.} (17. Qc1 Qxc1+ 18. Rxc1 Nc6 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Rxe7 Nd5 {with total equality: Abdusattorov - Erigaisi, chess24.com 2022.}) (17. Qe1 {is playable too, but after Nac4! 18.Rxe7 Rfe8 19.Rxe8+ Rxe8 20.Qc1 Qxc1+ 21.Rxc1 Na4! $146 21... Bc8 was less precise in Smirnov - Shevchenko, lichess. org 2021. 22.Bxb7 Nc5 followed by ...Nd3, Black should get an easy draw.}) 17... Qxc3 18. Bh6 {Here Black has different ways to equalize, but you should focus on how many moves he has and how many possibilities he has to blunder. My personal bet is that this position is an excellent practical choice.} Nac4 19. Rxe7 Rfe8 {Here White has two interesting options, against which Black should be careful.} 20. Rxe8+ (20. Rc1 Nb2 $1 {20...Qb4 21.Rxe8+ Rxe8 22.Bxb7 and White enjoys the bishop pair advantage.} 21. Qb3 Qxb3 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. axb3 Nd3 24. Ra1 Nc5 25. b4 Nd3 26. Bxb7 Nxb4 27. Rxa7 Bh3 28. Ra1 {and unfortunately, although White is a bit better, a draw seems difficult to avoid...}) 20... Rxe8 21. Bxb7 Qb2 $1 ({•} 21... Ne5 22. Rc1 Qa3 23. Qb3 {and White is only a little better, but facing the bishop pair is definitely unpleasant.}) ({•} 21... Ba4 22. Rc1 Qb2 23. Nb3 Qxa2 24. Qd4 Qb2 25. Qxb2 Nxb2 26. Nc5 Rd8 27. Nxa4 N2xa4 28. Rc2 {and despite the extra pawn, it is Black who has to be careful. White's bishops are so much stronger than Black's knights!}) ({•} 21... Nb2 22. Qd2 Qxd2 23. Bxd2 N2c4 24. Bb4 {is just an advantage for White.}) 22. Nb3 Z0 ({Black seems active enough to equalize, though here as well I would definitely pick White. A sample line (where Black has many opportunities to go wrong!)} 22... Bh3 23. Bc6 Rc8 24. Rc1 Qe5 25. Bh1 Re8 26. Nd4 $5 Rd8 27. Nc6 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Qf6 29. Rd8+ Qxd8 30. Nxd8 Bf5 31. Nc6 Bb1 32. Nxa7 Bxa2 {with a likely draw.}) *

