1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 Ne4 {It may look tempting, but it just forces d2-d4 that White was gonna play anyway.} 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 {Here Black has many moves but I believe after any of them, White gets an easier position. I do not see ...Ne4 as an improvement of Black's position either.} Bf5 {Kind of the most natural move: though here as well you may ask about the usefulness of having played ...Ne4.} 9. Nh4 $5 ({This move has been played by Gukesh and supercomputer Ethereal! It must make sense! Instead,} 9. e3 {and}) (9. Nbd2 {make perfect sense as well.}) 9... Be6 10. Qc2 {Concretely asking Black what he wants to do with his knight on e4.} Nf6 (10... Nd6 11. Nd2 {with the idea of pushing e4 just seems pleasant for White. 11.cxd5?! cxd5 12.Nc3 Nc6 13.e3 g5 Black wants the f5-square back for his bishop. 14.Nf3 Bf5 15.Qe2 e6 16.Ba3 Bf6 17.Rac1 Re8 18.Rfd1 Bg6 It seems Black sort of equalized in that weird computer game. 0-1 Ethereal 12.43 - LCZero v0.26.2-rc1_J92-100, tcec-chess.com 2020.}) ({Again,} 10... f5 {would mostly be weakening, and after} 11. e3 {followed by Nc3 (if 11... a5) or Nf3, White is slightly better.}) 11. Nd2 a5 12. e4 {This seems very easy to play for White.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nd7 15. Rfe1 Nf6 16. Bg2 a4 17. Bc3 $16 {White got a better position in Gukesh - Sethuraman, Kolkata 2022, 1-0.} *

