1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 Ne4 {It may look tempting, but it just forces d2-d4 that White was gonna play anyway.} 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 {Here Black has many moves but I believe after any of them, White gets an easier position. I do not see ...Ne4 as an improvement of Black's position either.} Be6 $6 {This dubious move has been played almost a hundred times.} 9. Nbd2 Nxd2 (9... f5 {justifies the knight on e4, but also makes more holes. After} 10. e3 {followed Rc1, Qc2 White will start pushing his queenside pawns, perhaps remove his f3-knight to d3, and it's hard to understand what Black will come up with, as pushing more kingside pawns would only weaken him more.}) 10. Qxd2 {This is just good for White.} dxc4 11. Ng5 $1 {Black is in big trouble.} Bh6 {With this move, Black forces a long sequence of move which results in a worse endgame for him.} 12. Nxe6 Bxd2 13. Nxd8 c3 14. Nxb7 cxb2 15. Rab1 Bc3 16. Nc5 Bxd4 17. Nd3 $16 {White wins the b2-pawn and stays with a better pawn structure. It won't be easy for Black to deal with the b2-pawn.} *

