1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 Ne4 {It may look tempting, but it just forces d2-d4 that White was gonna play anyway.} 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 {Here Black has many moves but I believe after any of them, White gets an easier position. I do not see ...Ne4 as an improvement of Black's position either.} Nd7 {Black wants to support his e4-knight with ...Ndf6, or replace it if it gets exchanged. Although it looks a bit weird to temporarily leave the bishop on c8, and although I really love White there, this move has been played the most often in OTB games!} 9. Nc3 Nxc3 (9... Ndf6 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Ne5 {just transposes.}) 10. Bxc3 Nf6 {And here I like the Ne5 idea.} 11. Ne5 $5 Ne4 12. Bb2 a5 13. a4 $1 {And now there's no black piece able to take advantage of the b4-square. I believe it is quite difficult for Black to find something to do.} Bf5 14. Rc1 {Next could very well be e3, f3 and then either play for e4 or g4 to push all black pieces backward. 1-0 Rasulov - Yashmetov, chess.com 2020.} *

