1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 Ne4 {It may look tempting, but it just forces d2-d4 that White was gonna play anyway.} 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 {Here Black has many moves but I believe after any of them, White gets an easier position. I do not see ...Ne4 as an improvement of Black's position either.} a5 {The most fashionable move lately, and perhaps the most sensible one as well, is going for quick counterplay. Black wants to gain space and, if possible, disturb White's pieces with ...a4.} 9. Ne5 $5 {A completely new idea (together with the next move), which I find very interesting for White. The reason why I looked for this kind of idea is that the main lines were leading straight into boring positions.} (9. e3 {The most classical way to play (or}) (9. Nc3 {which transposes after} Bf5 10. e3 {Nxe3 ) . My problem here is that after the main moves 9...Bf5 10.Nc3 Nxc3 11.Bxc3 Be4 12.Bh3! 12.Qe2 is probably better but it again slows down White's play. At some point, Black will take on f3 when he has to (e.g. after Rfc1 and Bh3) and his position will be extremely solid. Instead, 12.Bh3 is supposed to accelerate the process but I believe it faces a concrete problem. 12...c5! followed by ...Nc6 or ... cxd4 and there is absolutely zero advantage for White.}) 9... a4 $1 10. Na3 $5 {And basically White wants to play f3 and if ...Nd6, push c5 and have b5 under control.} axb3 (10... Bf5 11. f3 Nf6 12. Nd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Na6 14. Nc2 {is just nice for White: we got the bishop pair and good coordination.}) 11. axb3 Bf5 {This bishop sortie allows White to advance the kingside pawns.} 12. f3 $1 Nf6 13. g4 $1 Be6 14. h3 Z0 ({With the idea of f4, and after} 14... h5 15. e3 Nbd7 16. Nd3 hxg4 17. hxg4 {the knight is coming to f4! Something like Kf2, Rh1, Qg1, Qh2, is not a plan to exclude either!}) *

