1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 Ne4 {It may look tempting, but it just forces d2-d4 that White was gonna play anyway.} 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 {Here Black has many moves but I believe after any of them, White gets an easier position. I do not see ...Ne4 as an improvement of Black's position either.} a5 {The most fashionable move lately, and perhaps the most sensible one as well, is going for quick counterplay. Black wants to gain space and, if possible, disturb White's pieces with ...a4.} 9. Ne5 $5 {A completely new idea (together with the next move), which I find very interesting for White. The reason why I looked for this kind of idea is that the main lines were leading straight into boring positions.} (9. e3 {The most classical way to play (or}) (9. Nc3 {which transposes after} Bf5 10. e3 {Nxe3 ) . My problem here is that after the main moves 9...Bf5 10.Nc3 Nxc3 11.Bxc3 Be4 12.Bh3! 12.Qe2 is probably better but it again slows down White's play. At some point, Black will take on f3 when he has to (e.g. after Rfc1 and Bh3) and his position will be extremely solid. Instead, 12.Bh3 is supposed to accelerate the process but I believe it faces a concrete problem. 12...c5! followed by ...Nc6 or ... cxd4 and there is absolutely zero advantage for White.}) 9... a4 $1 10. Na3 $5 {And basically White wants to play f3 and if ...Nd6, push c5 and have b5 under control.} Be6 11. f3 (11. Nd3 Bf5 12. e3 {is interesting as well - again I like that knight on d3!}) 11... Nd6 12. c5 Nb5 13. Nxb5 cxb5 {Here we get a critical position where White has several options.} 14. b4 ({This is like the most natural move.} 14. e3 $5 {deserves attention too.}) (14. Nd3 $5 {is possible as well.}) (14. f4 $5 {might be kind of enjoyable too.}) 14... Nc6 (14... a3 15. Bc3 Nc6 16. f4 {looks great for White - b4 is already protected.}) 15. a3 Bxe5 $1 16. dxe5 d4 17. f4 {And White seems to have a small but stable advantage thanks to the long-term weakness on b5, and possibly on d4.} *

