1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} a5 {Here White has two very reliable options: playing it simple, ignoring a5, or playing 8. Nc3 which is a typical reaction to ...a5.} 8. d3 $5 Bg4 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. a3 (10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Re8 12. e3 e5 13. Qc2 {also seems like a simple way to be slightly better.}) 10... Re8 (10... Ne8 {was played by Magnus in an online game, but would I would say} 11. Bxg7 Nxg7 12. d4 {should simply be nice for White, as there is no 'bad bishop on b2' facing a wall on d4.}) 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Nxf3 e5 13. cxd5 Nxd5 (13... cxd5 14. e3 {is also a small plus for White: the d7-knight would do much better placed on c6, but for now, it can't move due to the e5-pawn. Bruzon Batista - Zherebukh, Saint Louis 2017.}) 14. Qc2 Qe7 15. e3 $14 {White is better and easily won in the game Carlsen - Gukesh, chess.com 2022.} *

