1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Nbd7 8. d4 $5 {A natural move now that playing ...Bf5 will require extra maneuvers.} Ne4 {Black should act fast - otherwise after Nc3 you may already wonder what Black can do.} 9. Nbd2 Ndf6 (9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Nf6 11. Ne5 {is an easy plus for White, as when a black piece comes to e4 we're able to push f3: 1-0 Vadasz - Dembo, Budapest 1999.}) 10. Ne5 {Having played Ne5, White is doing great. At some point, he'll be able to push f3 if it helps.} Bf5 11. e3 Qa5 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. f3 Nf6 14. g4 $16 {Black pieces are moving away and White has a very dynamic position. Black's pieces also lack good squares. Spoelman - Donchenko, Lingen 2020.} *

