1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Re8 8. Qc2 $5 ({Of course} 8. d4 {or}) (8. d3 {are possible as well, but I like to keep some mystery :)}) 8... Nbd7 9. d4 {Logical - now that ... Bf5 will need some time to be played.} Nb6 $5 (9... b5 10. Nbd2 bxc4 11. bxc4 Nb6 12. Ne5 Bf5 13. Qb3 Rc8 14. Rac1 {is nice for White, who's the one pressuring on the queenside and has a dangerous knight on e5.}) 10. Rc1 $5 {A very cool maneuver, together with the coming move.} (10. Nh4 {to prevent ... Bf5 was my first idea, but after} a5 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Nd2 Nb8 $1 {followed by ...Na6-b4, I wasn't entirely satisfied, e.g.} 13. e4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Qxe4 Qb6 16. Qe3 Na6 {and I think Black is doing okay.}) 10... Bf5 11. Qd1 {Now the c4-pawn is defended and White has kept flexibility in his position.} Ne4 $5 (11... a5 12. a4 {may not help Black, as his b6-knight is so far away from the b4-square.}) 12. cxd5 $1 (12. Nh4 dxc4 13. Nxf5 gxf5 14. bxc4 e5 $1 {would not be so clear.}) 12... Nxd5 {Here White should be careful with ...Bh6 and ....Nxf2 ideas. A new cool maneuver comes, now that our goal is clear: pushing the black central pieces away and gaining all the center.} (12... cxd5 13. Nc3 $14 {and the knight on b6 is highly misplaced.}) 13. Qe1 $1 (13. Nfd2 Ndf6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bh3 Bd5 16. Nc3 Ne4 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. e3 {would be a safe bet, but White's advantage is very limited...}) 13... Bh6 $1 {Otherwise Ne5 comes and the black pieces will soon have to move back, with disastrous consequences. 13. ..Be6 ( 14.Ne5 f5 15.Nd3 a5 16.e3 Bf7 17.Nd2 Nxd2 18.Qxd2 is definitely great for White, as Black will never be able to push ...e5. 13...Nd6 14.Nbd2 Ne4 15.Nh4 gives White a clear advantage at once.} 14. Rd1 $1 {Rc1 Qd1 followed by Qe1 Rd1, how funny!} a5 $3 {The only move! You'll understand why within a few moves...} (14... Qb6 $2 15. Ne5 Ne3 $1 {fails to} 16. fxe3 Bxe3+ 17. Kf1 Bf2 18. Nc4 $1 {+-}) 15. Bc1 $5 {15. Ne5?! Ne3! 16. fxe3 Bxe3+ 17. Kf1 Bf2 This is the whole point of 14... a5: the white queen is trapped! 18.Qxf2 Nxf2 19.Kxf2 a4 $132 Now we have a double-edged position which I do not recommend, Black is a little too active and ...f6 is coming. The tempting 15.Nh4 a4 16.Nxf5 gxf5 is just unclear.} Bxc1 16. Rxc1 {And now White will try to push the black pieces back slowly and enjoy a superior center.} a4 {The most natural move.} 17. b4 Ndf6 18. h3 $5 a3 19. e3 {Followed by Ne5, Nbd2/Nc3, and I definitely prefer White.} *

