1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bf5 8. d3 {Limiting the f5-bishop.} Qc8 {The only try to do something different than in other lines: trade bishops with ...Bh3.} 9. Re1 {White wants to keep his light-squared bishop.} (9. Nbd2 {is also slightly better for White, e.g.} Bh3 10. Rc1 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qd7 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Rd8 14. Qe2 Qd3 15. Qxd3 Rxd3 16. e5 Ne8 17. Ne4 $14 {as in the game Artemiev - Shirov, Moscow 2017.}) 9... Bh3 10. Bh1 h6 11. Nbd2 Z0 ({Again, White's position is a pleasure to play. Let's see some examples about how the game may continue. •} 11... Re8 12. Rc1 Qd8 13. Rc2 {13.d4!? with the idea of e4 or Ne5 makes sense as well.} Nbd7 14. Qa1 e5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nc4 Qe7 17. a3 N5b6 18. Na5 {$14 1-0 Howell - Hamdouchi, Doha 2015. • 11...Na6 12.Rc1 Qg4 12...Qd8 13.a3 Rc8 14.b4 $16 Vazquez - Costachi, chess.com 2023. 13.Nf1 Rfd8 14.Ne3 Qe6 15.Qd2 $14 Black's pieces are awkwardly placed, again. Wei Yi - Costachim, chess.com 2023.}) *

