1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. e3 {We have a long game full of small maneuvers ahead, but we're a bit better, sitting on the safe side of the board.} Qa5 ({•} 13... Qb6 14. Rc1 Rad8 15. Qc2 {Owing the c-file can't hurt.} Qa6 16. a3 e4 $2 {Weakening that pawn is rarely a good idea.} 17. dxe4 dxe4 18. Nd2 $16 {Jumabayev - Sanal, Novi Sad 2022.}) ({• The following game went easy for Grischuk:} 13... Rc8 14. Rc1 Rxc1 15. Qxc1 Qb8 16. Qb1 Rc8 17. Rc1 Rc6 18. Rxc6 {Without queens, that structure is difficult to break. With queens, the c6-pawn is just an extra weakness as our queen can disturb Black in different ways.} bxc6 19. Qc2 {19.Qa1!? Ne8 20.h4 with the idea of Bh3 and if ...f5 then e4 seemed even stronger.} Qd6 20. a3 Ne8 21. e4 d4 22. b4 Bh6 23. h4 $16 {Grischuk - Lin, China 2019.}) 14. Re1 $5 (14. Qd2 Qa6 15. Rfc1 e4 16. Ne1 {also looked easier for White in: Oparin - Artemiev, chess.com 2020.}) 14... Rac8 15. Re2 {A typical maneuver.} h6 16. Rc2 Nh7 17. Rac1 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 Nhf8 19. Nd2 Nb6 {Now White had to do something unusual, making a hole on b4 and then self-pinning his bishop.} 20. a4 $1 (20. a3 $6 Rc8 21. Qd1 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Qb5 23. Qc2 Ne6 24. a4 Qc6 $132 {Nihal - Paehtz, Toledo 2021.}) 20... Rc8 21. Bc3 $1 Z0 ({And the game might continue with} 21... Qc5 22. a5 Nbd7 23. b4 Qd6 24. Qb3 {with a large advantage for White.}) *

