1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 Nbd7 10. Nd2 e5 {This is less logical without the light-squared bishop, as explained above.} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Rc1 $5 Z0 ({Now for example} 12... Rc8 13. Rxc8 Qxc8 14. Qa1 Qb8 15. Bg2 Re8 16. e3 Qd6 17. Nf3 h6 18. Rc1 {was nice for White in Moiseenko - Zakaryan, Gelendzhik 2022. It is difficult for Black to do something and at some point, White will either push a3-b4, double on the c-file, or push a central pawn if Black is not ready to face it well.}) *

