1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. Nd2 Re8 11. Bg2 (11. e3 $5 {is possible as well, but anyhow Bg2 will be played at some point.}) 11... Nbd7 12. e3 a5 13. a3 Qe7 14. Qc2 Red8 15. Rfd1 Ne8 16. Bxg7 (16. d4 h5 17. Bc3 {Even keeping dark-squared bishops (after all the g7-bishop isn't great either) White got a great position.} Nd6 18. b4 a4 19. b5 $1 cxb5 20. cxd5 exd5 21. Bxd5 Rac8 22. Qd3 $16 {Oparin - Ali Marandi, lichess.org 2020.}) 16... Kxg7 17. d4 {White has the bishop pair and more space. Black’s position is very solid, nevertheless White’s queenside expansion is going to continue.} *

