1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. Nd2 Nbd7 {Here White's move order doesn't change much. Just try to remember plans!} 11. Bg2 Qe7 12. Qc2 $5 Rfe8 13. Rfe1 Nh5 {Black tries to trade some pieces to deprive White of the bishop pair.} 14. d4 {But White doesn’t agree! Here as well, White is slowly getting everything he wants.} Nhf6 15. e3 a6 16. a4 Qb4 17. Bc3 Qe7 18. b4 $14 {As we’ve seen in other variations, with the bishop pair, extra space, and ongoing queenside expansion, White’s position is favorable. White won in the game Dubov - Sargissian, Khanty-Mansiysk 2013.} *

