1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. Nd2 Nbd7 {Here White's move order doesn't change much. Just try to remember plans!} 11. Bg2 Qe7 12. d4 {Usually, we first wait for the f6-knight to move in order to push d4, but there's nothing wrong with doing it here.} Rfe8 13. e3 a5 (13... Nb6 14. a4 a5 15. Ba3 Qd8 16. Qc2 Nc8 17. b4 $1 {White takes an edge on the b-file. Things are going smoothly!} axb4 18. Bxb4 Nd6 19. Rfb1 $16 {Artemiev - Dubov, Sochi 2016.}) 14. a3 h5 15. Qe2 Red8 16. Rfd1 Ne8 17. e4 {Here as well, things are going perfectly for White.} dxe4 18. Nxe4 $16 {And White had the advantage and went on to win in the game Oparin - Vazquez, lichess.org 2021.} *

