1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. Nd2 Nbd7 {Here White's move order doesn't change much. Just try to remember plans!} 11. Qc2 {This seems to be Grischuk's favorite.} a5 (11... Ne8 12. d4 Nd6 13. e4 $1 {White opens the position and has a slight edge due to the bishop pair.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Qb6 16. Rfd1 $14 {Jones - Ovchinnikov, chess.com 2022.}) 12. a3 Qe7 13. Bg2 Rfd8 (13... Ne8 14. d4 $5 Nef6 15. e3 Rfe8 16. Rfd1 h5 17. Nf3 Ne4 18. Ne1 $5 {White maneuvers his knight to d3 - s square I love for the white knight as I've already said earlier in that course, as it controls the center even better than on f3, and makes f2-f3 possible to get rid off the e4-knight.} Nd6 19. a4 Nf5 20. Nd3 Qd8 21. Rab1 Nf6 22. Nc5 Nd6 23. Bc3 Bf8 24. Be1 h4 25. Nd3 Nde4 26. f3 $1 {It's time!} Nd6 27. g4 Nd7 28. e4 $16 {1-0 Grischuk - Ghaem Maghami, St Petersburg 2018.}) 14. e3 Ne8 15. d4 $5 {Let's see another game by Grischuk - who definitely likes to keep the dark-squared bishop, meaning the bishop pair.} b5 16. a4 b4 17. Rac1 (17. e4 $1 {seemed to be like an easy plus for White.}) 17... Nd6 18. Rfd1 Rac8 19. Qd3 Nf6 20. Rc2 Rc7 21. Rdc1 Rdc8 {Now it looks like Grischuk is dominating but the position isn't simple. Closing it with c5 limits White's possibilities, and otherwise Black may play ...c5 himself.} 22. Nf3 dxc4 $1 23. bxc4 c5 $1 24. Nd2 Nd7 25. Nb3 e5 {Black as doing fine: ½-½ Grischuk - Kamsky, St Petersburg 2018.} *

