1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. Nd2 a5 (10... Qe7 11. e3 a5 12. a3 Nbd7 13. Qc2 Ne8 14. Bg2 Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Qf6 16. d4 {looks like an easy game for White:} Nd6 17. Rfc1 Rfd8 18. Rab1 $14 {Pert - Nguyen, Turkey 2012. Remember pushing d4 always makes a lot of sense when the b2-bishop is gone, as otherwise it would be considered a 'bad' (passive) bishop. Or, to say it otherwise (as the g7-bishop wouldn't be great either after d4 by White), once these bishops are traded there is o reason not to push d4.}) 11. a3 (11. Qc2 {is another possible move order, but White likes to make sure that the a5-pawn won't reach a3.}) 11... Na6 12. Qc2 ({Here's another game that went perfectly for White:} 12. Bg2 Qb6 13. d4 Rfd8 14. e3 Nb8 15. Qc2 Nbd7 16. Rfc1 {(improving the pieces and keeping two possible plans: a queenside expansion or pushing e4)} Ne8 17. Bc3 Qc7 18. Rab1 Qb8 19. e4 $16 {Oparin - Kamsky, chess.com 2021.}) 12... Qb6 ({Another kind of model game went} 12... Nd7 13. d4 f5 14. Bg2 Kh8 15. e3 Nc7 {when White went for my favorite maneuver.} 16. Nf3 Ne8 17. Ne5 Nd6 18. Nd3 {The knight on d3 I like so much! 18.a4 first looked stronger to me, though.} Re8 {18...a4! 19.cxd5 axb3 20.Qxb3 exd5 21.Bc3 $14 would have limited the damage.} 19. Rab1 Ra7 20. a4 Ne4 21. Ba3 $16 {At some point White got f3 and e4 played: Oparin - Wang, Russia 2016.}) 13. e3 ({Another high-level game went} 13. Bg2 Rfd8 14. Rab1 Ne8 15. Bxg7 Nxg7 16. e3 Nc5 17. d4 {and here there's no reason to doubt White's advantage either:} Nd7 18. Rfc1 Nf5 19. Nf3 $14 {Malakhov - Kamsky, Sochi 2015.}) 13... Rfd8 14. d4 $14 {We've been there already and seen that this kind of position was good for White, who is likely to push e3-e4 soon.} (14. Bd4 {A weird move. Qc7 15.Qc3 Ne8 16.Bxg7 Nxg7 17.b4 17. d4 still looked good for White anyway. 17...Nf5 18.d4 axb4 19.axb4 Qe7 20.c5 Nc7 21.Be2 Rxa1 22.Rxa1 e5 $132 Jones - Kamsky, chess.com 2022.}) *

