1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O (4... d5 5. c4 c6 6. b3 {would transpose to the mainline.}) 5. c4 c6 {A solid approach: consolidating the center before pushing ...d5.} 6. b3 d5 7. Bb2 {We are at a crossroads where Black has many possible moves, though White's plans do not change that much anyhow.} Bg4 8. d3 $5 {The most natural move when Black develops his light-squared bishop. If it stays alive, it will make it useless as the light-squares are solidly consolidated, and if it gets traded, we have a bishop pair so as per rule we should keep the position as open as possible.} (8. d4 {remains a very possible option, though.}) 8... Bxf3 {Black can try to keep the bishop pair a little longer, but as a result, White will be able to recapture on f3 with his knight.} 9. Bxf3 e6 {Having 'lost' (traded) his light-squared bishop, putting his pawns on light squares and keeping a solid/ closed center is logical from Black's point of view. Now White has a choice to play with or without e3. It has advantages (control of the whole center, no more ...d4 ideas (almost) ever and disadvantages (loses a tempo, weakens the d3-pawn). A matter of choice!} 10. e3 Nbd7 (10... a5 11. Qc2 Na6 12. a3 Nd7 13. d4 f5 14. Nc3 Nf6 {and here in the game Jones - Kamsky, chess.com 2022, White decided to go for} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. b4 {after which the game was a mess. I do not think this sacrifice was necessary. I believe after Ne2-Nf4 and Bg2 (to enable f3 after ...Ne4) White was better, and could have taken his time to improve his queenside domination.}) 11. Qc2 h5 12. Nd2 Re8 13. b4 a6 14. a4 Rc8 15. Qb3 {White is also better here.} (15. a5 $5 Nh7 16. Bg2 h4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. e4 {looked good for White to me as well. Of course, if ...h4 and not ...Nh7, my idea was to take on h4 as White could have done in the game - see just below.}) 15... h4 16. Rfd1 (16. gxh4 $5 {with the idea of} Nh7 17. h5 $1 {followed by Kh1 seemed great for White to me.}) 16... Nh7 17. d4 Qg5 18. b5 Ndf6 {Black goes for an attack - why not, it's a blitz game! Here he is enough counterplay, but we've seen how White could have improved his play before. 0-1 Grischuk - Dubov, chess24.com 2022.} *

