1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} c6 8. Rb1 {Now Black has a dilemma: to include ...a5 and ...a3 or not. At first, you would say, why not to open the a-file when White pushes b4. But ...a5 has a downside: when Black plays ... d5, after an exchange on d5 the b5-square is weak.} Re8 {Black protects the e5-pawn to make ...d5 possible next.} 9. e4 $5 {I like this setup once ...c6 has been played, as long as ...d5 is not a good move. Indeed, Black cannot take advantage of the d4-square so easily.} h6 (9... d5 $6 10. exd5 cxd5 11. Bg5 $1 {would be great for White - and this fully justifies 9. e4!?.}) 10. Re1 {Now that Bg5 is impossible, White puts his rook on e1 so that after ...d5 exd5 cxd5 the e5-pawn will hang. Now, again Black should decide if he wants to include ...a5 or not.} Be6 11. b4 Nbd7 {May Black play 11...d4 or 11...dxc4, the g2-bishop's diagonal will open and the c3-knight will soon jump to d5, with excellent prospects.} 12. a4 {This is more pleasant for White compared with 10... a5.} d5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nd2 $14 {We are happy that the diagonal of the g2-bishop is open again.} *

