1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} c5 {Black wants to play some strange Botvinnik system (...c5 + ...e5), but there the knnight would be better on e7 so it doesn't block the f-pawn.} 8. a3 Nc6 9. Rb1 a5 {White was trying to push b4: so Black prevents it.} 10. Bg5 {White wants to trade the f6-knight (something he cannot do in Botvinnik systems when the knight is on e7, due to …f6) in order to increase his control of the d5-square.} h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 Be6 13. Nd2 Bg7 14. Ne4 $146 {A pretty forcing move. Black has a choice: exchanging on d5 and get a worse position or allow Nec3 which is a perfect relocation of the white knight.} Bxd5 (14... f5 15. Nec3 $14) 15. cxd5 Ne7 16. Qb3 Rb8 17. a4 $14 {White controls the light squares and has more space - he's definitely better.} *

