1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nh5 $6 {Black aims at playing ...c5.} 8. d4 $5 {This isn't forced, but I believe it is a good reaction to the black knight going to the side of the board.} Nc6 (8... Nd7 9. e4 {is a great version of the King's Indian with g3: here the black knight has nothing to do on h5.}) 9. Bg5 Qd7 (9... Nf6 $2 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Nd5 {wins material.}) 10. d5 Na5 11. Qd3 b6 12. e4 {With the black knight on a5, White is definitely doing great. When Black plays ...f5 White will take and answer ...gxf5 with Nh4.} *

