1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nh5 $6 {Black aims at playing ...c5.} 8. d4 $5 {This isn't forced, but I believe it is a good reaction to the black knight going to the side of the board.} Nc6 (8... Nd7 9. e4 {is a great version of the King's Indian with g3: here the black knight has nothing to do on h5.}) 9. Bg5 f6 10. Be3 f5 11. dxe5 dxe5 (11... Nxe5 $6 {is met with} 12. c5 $1 f4 13. Bd4 Bg4 14. Qb3+ Kh8 15. Rad1 Bxf3 16. exf3 {1-0 Forster - Maier, Switzerland 2018.}) 12. Qb3 Nd4 {Black needs to play actively before White centralizes his rooks and get a full control of the position.} 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. c5+ Kh8 15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Nd5 $146 {A simple improvement to a cool game in which White was nevertheless better as well. 16. Nxd4 ( Qxc5 17.Na4 Qa5 18.Nc6! What a cool move! 18...Qa6 19.Ne7 Be6 20.Bd5 Bxd5 21.Nxd5 $14 1-0 Wirig - Pytel, France 2009.} Qxc5 17. Rc1 {And Black is in big trouble.} *

