1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nc6 ({•} 7... Re8 8. Rb1 {and we are going to transpose in one line or another. The ideas remain the same: queenside expansion and sometimes e2-e4. 8.e4 Bg4 is a different story with the pawn on c7 and not c6, and the b8-knight will be able to come to d4.}) ({•} 7... h6 {Black wants to control g5 before he goes ...Be6. Nevertheless, after} 8. b4 {Black can choose how to place his pieces but we'll end up in similar positions as above.}) ({•} 7... Nbd7 8. Rb1 {is again very similar to the lines above: but the c8-bishop being blocked should favor White. 8.b4!? is possible as well.}) 8. Rb1 {Again the same thing: Black can play many different moves, but White's plans remain the same. Here I'll give different possible follow-ups, but the list is non-exhaustive. Basically, you're gonna push your queenside pawns whatever Black does.} Re8 9. b4 e4 {Trying to justify ...Re8.} (9... Nd4 10. Be3 $5 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 a6 12. a4 $14 {White has a pleasant edge with extra space.}) 10. dxe4 {The start of a more or less forced sequence.} Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Rxe4 12. b5 Nd4 13. Nxd4 Rxd4 14. Qb3 Be6 15. Bxb7 Bxc4 16. Qc2 {With big problems for Black: 1-0 Ivic - Matinian, chess.com 2022.} *

