1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nc6 ({•} 7... Re8 8. Rb1 {and we are going to transpose in one line or another. The ideas remain the same: queenside expansion and sometimes e2-e4. 8.e4 Bg4 is a different story with the pawn on c7 and not c6, and the b8-knight will be able to come to d4.}) ({•} 7... h6 {Black wants to control g5 before he goes ...Be6. Nevertheless, after} 8. b4 {Black can choose how to place his pieces but we'll end up in similar positions as above.}) ({•} 7... Nbd7 8. Rb1 {is again very similar to the lines above: but the c8-bishop being blocked should favor White. 8.b4!? is possible as well.}) 8. Rb1 {Again the same thing: Black can play many different moves, but White's plans remain the same. Here I'll give different possible follow-ups, but the list is non-exhaustive. Basically, you're gonna push your queenside pawns whatever Black does.} Be6 (8... Nd4 9. b4 c6 10. b5 {is pleasant for White, who's pressuring for free on the queenside.}) 9. b4 h6 {Black might prevent Bg5 which would create some annoying pressure on the kingside but White now turns to the queenside and grabs the initiative on the opposite side of the board.} 10. b5 Ne7 11. a4 {Intending Ba3 and c5.} Qd7 12. Ba3 Bh3 13. c5 $14 {And White has a slight advantage.} *

