1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nc6 ({•} 7... Re8 8. Rb1 {and we are going to transpose in one line or another. The ideas remain the same: queenside expansion and sometimes e2-e4. 8.e4 Bg4 is a different story with the pawn on c7 and not c6, and the b8-knight will be able to come to d4.}) ({•} 7... h6 {Black wants to control g5 before he goes ...Be6. Nevertheless, after} 8. b4 {Black can choose how to place his pieces but we'll end up in similar positions as above.}) ({•} 7... Nbd7 8. Rb1 {is again very similar to the lines above: but the c8-bishop being blocked should favor White. 8.b4!? is possible as well.}) 8. Rb1 {Again the same thing: Black can play many different moves, but White's plans remain the same. Here I'll give different possible follow-ups, but the list is non-exhaustive. Basically, you're gonna push your queenside pawns whatever Black does.} a5 9. b3 $5 ({Here there is nothing wrong with the move} 9. a3 {, but opening the a-file will indeed help Black if White plays classical. Instead, I've decided to propose you a totally brand-new idea.}) {White changes his plan and will try to obtain some advantage in the center or kingside, instead of focusing on the queenside. One thing that makes this idea possible is that Rb1 (avoiding problems on the h8-a1 diagonal) is more useful than …a5 if suddenly the critical aspects of the position move to our right (center and kingside).} 9... h6 10. Bb2 {After trying several things, this move came as my favorite by far. To start with, it prevents an immediate ...d5.} Be6 (10... d5 $2 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nxe5) 11. Re1 $5 {A great prophylactical move against ...d5 - not as concrete as 10. Bb2 but anyway, let's see...} (11. Qd2 $5 {with the idea of} d5 12. Nb5 d4 13. e3 dxe3 14. fxe3 {deserves attention too.}) 11... Qd7 12. d4 $146 exd4 (12... e4 $6 13. d5 exf3 14. dxe6 {with tempo on the black queen is the reason why we awaited ...Qd7 to push d4.}) 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Z0 ({White is clearly better, and for example} 14... Bf5 {fails nicely to} 15. Nd5 Ne8 16. Qxg7+ $1 Nxg7 17. Nf6+ Kh8 18. Nxd7 Bxd7 19. Bxb7 {winning for White. While after 14...Nd5 White simply plays 15.Qd2 $16}) *

