rying several things, this move came as my favorite by far. To start with, it prevents an immediate ...d5.} Be6 (10... d5 $2 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nxe5) 11. Re1 $5 {A great prophylactical move against ...d5 - not as concrete as 10. Bb2 but anyway, let's see...} (11. Qd2 $5 {with the idea of} d5 12. Nb5 d4 13. e3 dxe3 14. fxe3 {deserves attention too.}) 11... d5 {Other moves will not improve Black's position.} (11... Re8 12. Qd2 $5 d5 13. Nb5 $1 {is a better version for White than our main line.}) 12. Nb5 $1 (12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Nd4 {would be very decent for Black.}) 12... e4 $6 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bg4 15. cxd5 e3 16. fxe3 Nxd5 17. Qd2 Z0 ({And Black does not have compensation. If} 17... Qg5 {then} 18. h4 {is a simple solution:} Qxe3+ 19. Qxe3 Nxe3 20. Bxb7 {with an extra pawn.}) *

