1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 d6 {The King's Indian Defense against the King's Indian attack!} (5... Nc6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Rb1 {would soon transpose. 7.d4 would transpose into a regular King's Indian.}) 6. Nc3 e5 {Other orders would transpose as well - as Black will end up playing ...e5 anyway. Note that against any move, 7. d4 will transpose into a regular g3 King's Indian.} (6... Nc6 7. Rb1 e5 {transposes.}) (6... c6 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {as well.}) ({So does} 6... Nbd7 7. Rb1 e5 8. d3 {although ...Nc6 lines are more popular.}) 7. d3 {Black has tried tons of different moves here.} Nc6 ({•} 7... Re8 8. Rb1 {and we are going to transpose in one line or another. The ideas remain the same: queenside expansion and sometimes e2-e4. 8.e4 Bg4 is a different story with the pawn on c7 and not c6, and the b8-knight will be able to come to d4.}) ({•} 7... h6 {Black wants to control g5 before he goes ...Be6. Nevertheless, after} 8. b4 {Black can choose how to place his pieces but we'll end up in similar positions as above.}) ({•} 7... Nbd7 8. Rb1 {is again very similar to the lines above: but the c8-bishop being blocked should favor White. 8.b4!? is possible as well.}) 8. Rb1 {Again the same thing: Black can play many different moves, but White's plans remain the same. Here I'll give different possible follow-ups, but the list is non-exhaustive. Basically, you're gonna push your queenside pawns whatever Black does.} a5 9. b3 $5 ({Here there is nothing wrong with the move} 9. a3 {, but opening the a-file will indeed help Black if White plays classical. Instead, I've decided to propose you a totally brand-new idea.}) {White changes his plan and will try to obtain some advantage in the center or kingside, instead of focusing on the queenside. One thing that makes this idea possible is that Rb1 (avoiding problems on the h8-a1 diagonal) is more useful than …a5 if suddenly the critical aspects of the position move to our right (center and kingside).} 9... h6 10. Bb2 {After trying several things, this move came as my favorite by far. To start with, it prevents an immediate ...d5.} Be6 (10... d5 $2 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Nxe5) 11. Re1 $5 {A great prophylactical move against ...d5 - not as concrete as 10. Bb2 but anyway, let's see...} (11. Qd2 $5 {with the idea of} d5 12. Nb5 d4 13. e3 dxe3 14. fxe3 {deserves attention too.}) 11... d5 {Other moves will not improve Black's position.} (11... Re8 12. Qd2 $5 d5 13. Nb5 $1 {is a better version for White than our main line.}) 12. Nb5 $1 (12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Nd4 {would be very decent for Black.}) 12... d4 13. e3 $1 {Here we understand why we put our rook on e1!} dxe3 14. Rxe3 {Of course we take with the rook, adding pressure on Black's e5-pawn.} Ng4 15. Re2 $1 {A cute maneuver.} Bf5 (15... Nb4 16. Rd2 c6 17. Nc3 {is just bad for Black: his knights are a bit awkward on g4 and b4! Next could be a3, Ne4, and d4 at some point.}) 16. h3 $1 Qxd3 (16... Nf6 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Qxd3 19. Rc1 $16) 17. Ra1 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Nf6 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 {And White is much better.} *

