1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. c4 h5 $5 {A rare continuation.} (7... O-O 8. Nc3 {would transpose to Chapter 1 [/course/200248/1] 1... Nf6 lines with 2... g6 and 5... c5.}) 8. h3 O-O (8... h4 $2 9. g4 {does not help Black: the h4-pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 9. Nc3 Nxd4 ({After} 9... d6 10. Be3 $1 Bd7 11. b3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Qd2 $14 {White simply gets a dream position as we were trying to get in ...Nf6/...g6/... c5 chapters.}) 10. Qxd4 d6 11. Rd1 $146 {A logical move, but also a novelty. It is anyway hard to imagine that including ...h5 and h3 can be good for Black when both sides castled kingside.} Be6 (11... Bd7 12. c5 $1 {creates concrete problems for Black.}) 12. Qh4 Rc8 13. b3 Ng4 {Attacking the undefended knight on c3.} 14. hxg4 Bxc3 15. Bg5 $1 {A crucial move.} Bxa1 ({After} 15... f6 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Rac1 {or 15...Bf6 16.gxh5 Bxg5 17.Qxg5 Kg7 18.hxg6 White is winning.}) 16. Bxe7 Qc7 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. Rxa1 Bxg4 19. Qf6 Z0 ({This is just good for White, as} 19... Bxe2 $2 20. Bd5 {Threatening Qxg6.} Kh7 21. Re1 {just loses for Black.}) *

