1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qb6 $5 {Not a bad line at all. In fact, White is able to put pressure, but with exact play Black should manage to hold.} 6. Nb3 g6 7. Be3 $5 (7. O-O Bg7 8. c4 d6 9. Nc3 O-O {and I'm not so happy with the knight on b3, and now if} 10. Be3 {Black can deviate from our line with} Qa6 {which is why I prefer the 7. Be3 move order.}) 7... Qd8 8. c4 Bg7 9. Nc3 d6 10. Nd4 {As black spent two tempi for Qd8-b6-d8, we can improve our knight too.} O-O 11. h3 {Preventing ...Ng4. We're back into some sort of normal setup.} Bd7 12. Qd2 a6 13. O-O Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qc8 (14... Rc8 15. Qd3 Bc6 16. Rfd1 {is good for White as well.}) 15. Bxf6 $1 {Not a move you do every day - but if you achieve something by force...} Bxf6 16. Nd5 Bxh3 (16... Rb8 17. Nxf6+ exf6 18. Qxd6 Bxh3 19. Bxh3 Qxh3 20. Qxf6 {is just an extra pawn for White.}) 17. Nb6 {And White wins an exchange and gets some advantage.} *

