1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qb6 $5 {Not a bad line at all. In fact, White is able to put pressure, but with exact play Black should manage to hold.} 6. Nb3 e6 7. e4 $5 {Now I like the idea to transpose into some sort of favorable Sicilian, where the queen is misplaced on b6, and the white knight is still on b1, offering White options pushing his c-pawn.} Qc7 (7... Be7 8. O-O Qc7 9. c4 Ne5 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Nc3 d6 {transposes to 7... Qc7.}) 8. O-O Be7 9. c4 ({After} 9. Nc3 {we would be in regular Sicilian Defence, that its why we use opportunity to transpose to Hedgehog structures.}) 9... Ne5 10. Bf4 O-O (10... d6 11. Na3 $1 O-O 12. Rc1 {with c5 ideas could be pretty annoying for Black.}) 11. Nc3 d6 12. Nd2 Bd7 (12... Nxc4 13. Nxc4 Qxc4 14. Bxd6 {is clearly better for White, with e5 to come.}) 13. Qe2 $14 {White has a pleasant Maroczy kind of position.} *

