1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qb6 $5 {Not a bad line at all. In fact, White is able to put pressure, but with exact play Black should manage to hold.} 6. Nb3 d6 7. Nc3 e6 8. a4 {Again, White's plan is to advance the a-pawn.} Be7 ({Of course, Black can't play} 8... a5 {because of} 9. Nb5 $1) 9. a5 Qd8 10. e4 {Followed by O-O is another Scheveningen Sicilian where the white pawn went from a2 to a5 for free, which makes a massive difference as Black is unable to put ...a6 and ...b5 or even ...b6 in good conditions.} *

