1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qb6 $5 {Not a bad line at all. In fact, White is able to put pressure, but with exact play Black should manage to hold.} 6. Nb3 d5 {This is definitely critical. Black should try to take the center.} 7. O-O e6 8. Nc3 {I've tried several things and came to the conclusion that this was the best practical try. Black really struggles to equalize.} Be7 9. a4 $1 O-O 10. a5 {Gaining space before breaking the center.} Qd8 11. e4 $5 {It is time to open the center and the long diagonal for our g2 bishop.} d4 12. e5 $1 dxc3 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. bxc3 {The last sequence of moves was forced, and now Black has a choice. This is something we like: the more choices, the more time your opponent will spend and the more chances he has to go wrong!} Qc7 $5 (14... Bxc3 15. Ra4 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 {transposes to 14... Qxd1.}) 15. Qh5 $1 Bxc3 16. Ra4 Bf6 ({Black cannot exchange queens with} 16... Qe5 $2 17. Qxe5 Bxe5 18. a6 $1 {and Black is in trouble.}) 17. Rc4 Qe5 $1 {Now it is different!} 18. Qxe5 Nxe5 19. Rc7 Rb8 20. Re1 Ng6 21. h4 {With nice compensation, but Black should be able to equalize.} *

