1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. c4 {Now Black has two options: ...e6 transposing into some Catalan type of position, or ...e5 transposing in a reversed Grunfeld.} e6 7. O-O Qb6 $6 {This is too slow, as the queen is not the piece Black should develop early.} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nc3 {The best line for White.} Bb7 10. cxd5 {A very strong move! We are not only opening the c-file and the a4-e8 diagonal, but we remove the defender from the b5 square as well.} cxd5 11. Be3 Qa5 12. a3 {Time to grab some space on the queenside.} Bd6 13. b4 {White is improving all of his pieces and pawns with tempo.} Qd8 14. Nb5 Bb8 ({Not an easy decision, but after} 14... Be7 {the pawn on a7 falls after the simple} 15. Bxa7) 15. Bc5 $16 {And White won in the game Panchanathan - Morozov, Calgary 2022.} *

