1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. c4 {Now Black has two options: ...e6 transposing into some Catalan type of position, or ...e5 transposing in a reversed Grunfeld.} e5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. O-O ({My recommendation.} 8. Bg5 $5 {deserves attention too but it allows} Bb4+ {.}) (8. Nc3 {would be a great move order if only Black did not have} d4 $1 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 10. Bxa8 Qxa8 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 Qxd5 13. f3 Bc5 {with full compensation for the exchange.}) 8... Be7 $6 9. Nc3 Be6 10. Bg5 e4 {A move you don't wanna play! But you have to...} 11. Qa4 O-O 12. Rad1 $1 (12. Qxc6 $6 Rc8 {would just be fine for Black.}) 12... Qe8 (12... Qb6 $2 {has been played the most often, but} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Qxb2 17. e3 {is just winning for White, who is more active and wins the e4-pawn: Sjugirov - Goltsev, chess.com 2022.}) 13. e3 {And Black's position is terribly unpleasant.} *

