1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {The best line for Black in my opinion.} 6. Nb3 (6. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1 {would just be more than fine for Black.}) 6... d5 7. Bg5 Be6 8. O-O {Here Black has a decent position if he understands that he should push ...e4 at some point and grant the d4-square.} Qd7 $5 9. Nc3 O-O-O $1 10. e3 $5 ({Now} 10. e4 {isn't precise, as after} dxe4 11. Qe2 Bg4 $1 {is okay for Black.}) 10... Be7 11. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 12. Nc5 Qe7 $1 (12... Qd6 $6 13. N3a4 {and the queen is misplaced on d6 as} e4 14. c4 $1 {would be problematic.}) 13. N3a4 e4 $1 ({Black must firstly block the long diagonal, as after} 13... Kb8 $2 14. c4 $1 dxc4 15. Qe2 {and Black is in huge trouble.}) 14. c4 {A typical idea for White, opening the position and removing the support of the e4 pawn.} dxc4 15. Qe2 Bd5 16. Rad1 ({White must choose the right rook, because after} 16. Rfd1 Ne5 17. Nxe4 {Black has the unpleasant} Nd3 $1) 16... Ne5 17. Nxe4 Bc6 $1 18. Nac3 {And White will play Rd4 or b3 next, and sits on the pleasant side of the board, even if objectively Black might be okay. Again, see how many opportunities Black had to go wrong!} *

