1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) ({Another possible line is} 4. c4 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nc7 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Be7 9. Nd2 {but I do not really like it for White. A possible follow-up would be} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd5 11. Qb3 Nd4 $1 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 14. Qb7 {with a draw.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 {The best line for Black in my opinion.} 6. Nb3 (6. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1 {would just be more than fine for Black.}) 6... d5 7. Bg5 Be6 8. O-O {Here Black has a decent position if he understands that he should push ...e4 at some point and grant the d4-square.} Be7 9. Bxf6 ({White needs react quickly, as after} 9. Nc3 d4 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Ne4 Qb6 {followed by ...f5 is problematic for White.}) 9... gxf6 10. e3 h5 $1 {Black avoids Qh5 which could be disturbing, and plays a useful attacking move. Against almost anything else, White would play Nc3 followed by Qh5 and Rad1, with a pleasant position.} ({For example} 10... Qd7 $2 11. Nc3 O-O-O 12. Qh5 $1 Kb8 13. h3 {followed by Rfd1.}) 11. Nc3 e4 $1 12. h4 Qd7 13. Qe2 (13. Nd4 Ne5 {would be unclear too.}) 13... Bb4 $5 (13... O-O-O 14. Rfd1 Qc7 {is not very natural for Black, but after} 15. Nb5 Qb6 {there doesn't seem to be a killer, e.g.} 16. c4 Bg4 17. Qf1 Bxd1 18. Rxd1 dxc4 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Qxc4 Kb8 21. Bxe4 {and Black has compensation for equality, no more.}) 14. Rfd1 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7 16. c4 ({Trying to force things.} 16. Qf1 $5 O-O-O 17. Rab1 Ne5 18. Nd4 Bg4 19. Bh3 a6 {is also unclear.}) 16... dxc4 17. Nd4 (17. Nc5 f5 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qxc4 Kf7 {is around equal.}) 17... Bg4 {Black should take the exchange or he's just worse.} 18. Qxc4 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 O-O-O 20. Bxe4 {White must save the rook to attack Black's weak pawns, otherwise the endgame without a rook can be dangerous.} Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Qxc4 (21... Rxd4 {is favorable to White, after} 22. Qxd4 {(attacking the a7- and f6-pawns)} Qb6 23. Qd5 {with the initiative.}) 22. Rxc4+ {Again, White has compensation for equality, but not more. What to do, if Black plays perfectly the position ends equal!} *

