1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. e4 $5 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) {The most serious try here. Now Black should just develop normally.} 5... g6 ({This is a little bit slow, though also playable.} 5... d6 {followed by ...Be7 would likely transpose to 5... Be7, as after} 6. c3 Be7 $5 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 9. Be3 d5 $1 {I do not see any advantage for White.}) 6. c3 Bg7 {This is definitely too slow.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 exd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Nb5 {Black will never manage to get rid of his isolated d-pawn.} Ne8 11. N1c3 $16 {White has a big advantage, but in blitz games anything can happen, and White resigned after forty moves in the Kramnik - Tsydypov game, lichess.org 2020.} *

