1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. c4 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) 5... d5 ({•} 5... d6 $6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. d3 O-O 8. a3 h6 9. Rb1 {White wants to play b4 after what his position would be excellent.} a5 10. Ne1 Be6 11. f4 $1 exf4 12. gxf4 {with the idea of f5, e4, or Nc2-e3 is excellent for White.}) ({•} 5... Be7 $6 6. Nc3 O-O 7. d3 d5 {7...d6 transposes to 5... d6.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxe5 $1 Nxc3 10. Nxc6 {and White wins a pawn.}) 6. Qa4 $5 (6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 Nc7 {is discussed under 4. c4 - where I explain this is not something I want for White.}) 6... Bd6 (6... Bd7 $2 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 9. Qe4 {is a nice trick that wins a pawn for White, without compensation, e.g.} Bd6 10. Qxd5 Bc6 11. Qb3 $16 {1-0 Izoria - Hilby, chess.com 2019.}) 7. d4 $5 {An old try by Kramnik - but recent engines have no problem meeting it.} (7. Ng5 {- the only knight move that prevents ...Be6 - could have been a good move, but after} O-O {!} 8. cxd5 Nd4 $1 {Black has full compensation.}) 7... cxd4 (7... exd4 {A very annoying option.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Bxd5 O-O {!? White wins a pawn but the position is very drawish. It was played in two high level games:} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxd4 Bh3 {12...Qe7 13.Nc3 Be5 14.Qe4 Re8 15.Be3 Rb8 16.Qc2 h5= $13 Black enjoys nice compensation - enough for a draw. Caruana - Nepomniachtchi, Saint Louis 2017.} 13. Re1 Rb8 14. Nc3 Qe7 15. Bg5 Qe6 16. Bf4 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Rxb2 {Black has a weakness on c6, but the strong h3-bishop compensates. 0-1 Nepomniachtchi - Carlsen, Zagreb 2022.}) 8. cxd5 Qa5 9. Qxa5 Nxa5 10. Na3 {This was Kramnik's idea, but here as well the engine is able to solve Black's problems.} Bxa3 $146 (10... Bd7 $2 11. b4 Bxb4 12. Nxe5 Bc3 {was Kramnik - Karjakin, Russia 2016, but after} 13. Nxd7 $146 Bxa1 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Bf4 Bc3 17. Bc7 {followed by d6 White is completely winning.}) 11. bxa3 Nc4 12. Nd2 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Bf5 {Black wants ... Be4 (or sometimes ...Ne4) and he's doing fine. So, it seems the whole Kramnik's idea with 6. Qa4 was a one-game try.} *

