1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. e4 $5 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) {The most serious try here. Now Black should just develop normally.} 5... g6 ({This is a little bit slow, though also playable.} 5... d6 {followed by ...Be7 would likely transpose to 5... Be7, as after} 6. c3 Be7 $5 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 9. Be3 d5 $1 {I do not see any advantage for White.}) 6. c3 d6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 9. dxe5 $1 ({Weaker is} 9. d5 $6 {because of} Nd4 $132 {with strong knight in the centre, as happened in the game Afanasiev - Tregubov, Sochi 2021.}) 9... dxe5 10. Qa4 $5 {A possible try, disturbing Black's coordination before it is too late.} (10. Nc3 Bg7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxd8+ Rxd8 13. Bxf3 O-O 14. Kg2 Nd4 15. Bg5 $6 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 {With total equality. Firouzja - Carlsen, Stavanger 2020.}) 10... Nd7 (10... Qe7 11. Nc3 {and Black should watch out for Nd5 as well.}) 11. Be3 Rc8 12. Rc1 Bg7 13. Nc3 O-O 14. Nd5 {And White got a small but stable advantage thanks to the strong knight on d5 and pressure on the queenside.} *

