1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. e4 $5 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) {The most serious try here. Now Black should just develop normally.} 5... Nxe4 $6 {This would be a bad idea.} 6. Re1 ({After the more or less forced line} 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. Bxe4 d5 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. Nc3 d4 10. Re1+ Be6 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Qh5 $1 {I do not think Black equalizes either.}) 6... Nf6 (6... d5 $2 {is just a blunder:} 7. c4 $1 Be6 8. Qa4 $1 Bd6 9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Rxe4 b5 11. Qxb5 $1 Bxe4 12. Qa4 {And if} Bd5 {then} 13. Nc3 {. 1-0 Rodshtein - Donchenko, Sweden 2016.}) 7. Nxe5 Be7 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 {Here in the two existing games, Black took on e5, but we firstly check the alternatives.} Re8 {Might be a better defense than ...Nxe5, but White is a bit better.} 10. d3 Bd6 11. Nf3 Rxe1+ 12. Qxe1 Bf8 13. b3 $5 {It is important to always be able to meet ...d5 in good conditions. So far so good.} Nb4 (13... d5 14. Bg5 $14) (13... h6 14. Bb2 d5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17. Ne5 $16 {White's bishop are superior and the White queen may arrive to e8.}) 14. Qe2 d5 15. a3 Nc6 16. Bg5 dxc4 17. dxc4 h6 18. Rd1 Z0 ({White wins as many tempi as possible, and after} 18... Qe7 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Nd5 $14 {he enjoys a better position.}) *

