1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. e4 $5 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) {The most serious try here. Now Black should just develop normally.} 5... Nxe4 $6 {This would be a bad idea.} 6. Re1 ({After the more or less forced line} 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. Bxe4 d5 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. Nc3 d4 10. Re1+ Be6 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Qh5 $1 {I do not think Black equalizes either.}) 6... Nf6 (6... d5 $2 {is just a blunder:} 7. c4 $1 Be6 8. Qa4 $1 Bd6 9. cxd5 Bxd5 10. Rxe4 b5 11. Qxb5 $1 Bxe4 12. Qa4 {And if} Bd5 {then} 13. Nc3 {. 1-0 Rodshtein - Donchenko, Sweden 2016.}) 7. Nxe5 Be7 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 {Here in the two existing games, Black took on e5, but we firstly check the alternatives.} Nxe5 10. Rxe5 d6 (10... Bd6 $6 {makes Black's position is even worse:} 11. Re1 Re8 12. d4 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 cxd4 14. Nb5 {and White gets his pawn back:} Bc5 15. b4 Bf8 16. Bf4 d6 17. Nxd4 $16 {Anton Guijarro - Deuer, Viernheim 2023.}) 11. Re1 {Both existing games went pretty bad for Black.} Be6 12. b3 ({After} 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Bxc4 14. d4 Be6 15. b3 {White won in the game Ding Liren - Nepomniachtchi, chess24.com 2020. Here I see no reason not to just improve White's position with 12. b3 as ...d5 is not possible.}) 12... Qd7 13. d4 {And White has a large advantage.} *

