1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. O-O ({This is a good line for Black, with precise play. Besides the main line (} 4. d4 {), I tried to analyze other things (}) (4. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. c4 {,}) (4. O-O e5 5. e4 {) but discarded all these options (except the last one, which I offer as an alternative at the end of the chapter) although you can find a summary of them below.}) 4... e5 5. e4 $5 ({Here I did not like} 5. d3 d5 {, getting into a completely reversed King's Indian. However I found two interesting tries after which Black should be precise in order to equalize.}) {The most serious try here. Now Black should just develop normally.} 5... Be7 $1 {This is the most sensible move. Now plans with c3-d4 are just too slow to get an advantage.} 6. Re1 (6. d3 {allows extra options like} d5 {.}) (6. c3 Nxe4 $1 {is a dry equality:} 7. Re1 d5 8. d3 Nf6 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Rxe5 O-O {= (½-½ Jumabayev - Erdos, Dubai 2021.}) 6... d6 7. c3 O-O 8. h3 ({We need to stop ...Bg4, as} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 10. d5 Nd4 {is not what we want.}) 8... Be6 9. d4 ({And here other moves than} 9. d4 {have been tried, like}) (9. Na3 {(Amin). But they're definitely fine for Black, so I don't believe in this line at all for White.}) 9... exd4 10. cxd4 d5 $5 11. exd5 Z0 ({And after} 11... Nxd5 {Black had no problems in the game Gukesh - Karthikeyan, Abu Dhabi 2018. Nevertheless, I would say 4. O-O followed by 5. e4 can be tried in a one-shot game.}) *

