1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} e6 5. e4 {Don't ask twice!} c5 6. e5 (6. O-O {is possible as well, but we've got a Sicilian kind of position and generally, it is good to push e5 there when it forces the f6-knight away. Just a win of time!}) 6... Nd5 7. O-O Nc6 8. Re1 Be7 9. c4 {A logical move to keep the center under control.} Nc7 10. Nc3 {With d4 to come, White can claim the advantage.} *

