1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} e6 5. e4 {Don't ask twice!} d6 6. O-O c5 {In the chapter about 2...b5 we'll see this position with the pawn on b5 and not b6. Both have pros and cons.} 7. c4 Be7 8. Nc3 {White will play Re1 shortly followed by d4, with a good Maroczy structure. If Black goes ...e5, White will play Nh4 (taking advantage of the weakened f5-square) followed by f4 at some point. Compared to a normal Hedgehog, White has lost a tempo playing d3 followed by d4. This tempo is meaningless as White has a serious space advantage and an harmonious position. There's one last detail to be careful of in order to be precise, let's see!} O-O 9. Re1 a6 ({The most critical move order. If} 9... Nc6 {or}) (9... Nbd7 {, White just pushes} 10. d4 {and gets a fine version of the positions we're gonna see.}) ({For example} 9... Nc6 10. d4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Qc7 13. b3 Rfd8 14. Bb2 Rac8 15. Rad1 {was just good for White in Oparin - Kramnik, chess.com 2023.}) 10. b3 $5 {A clever more order. It turns out that after playing d4 cxd4 Nxd4, White's bishop will be better on b2, eying a long diagonal, than e3.} (10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qc7 {White does not have time for 12. b3 due to 12...b5. Nevertheless,} 12. Be3 {remains interesting for White, as after} Qxc4 $2 13. Rc1 {the black queen turns out to be in hugetrouble, e.g.} Qb4 14. a3 Qa5 15. Nd5 $1 exd5 16. Bd2 {winning. But my expertise of the position is that White's bishop is better placed on b2.}) 10... Nbd7 {The knight is generally better placed on d7 than c6 in the Hedgehog, otherwise we'll see something like Oparin-Kramnik above.} 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qc7 13. Bb2 {White has a great position as he enjoys a great space advantage without counterplay.} Rfe8 ({Let's first see a masterpiece by Nigel Short.} 13... Rac8 14. Qd2 g6 15. Bh3 Nc5 16. b4 Rcd8 {A typical pattern.} 17. Rac1 Bc8 18. Bg2 Ncd7 19. Nd5 $1 {Boom!} exd5 20. cxd5 Qb7 21. Nc6 Rfe8 22. f4 Nh5 23. e5 {Black is just getting smashed, let's see the rest of the game as White deserves it to be shown!} Nb8 24. Nxd8 Rxd8 25. e6 Nf6 26. f5 b5 27. Bd4 Rf8 28. Qh6 fxe6 29. dxe6 d5 30. fxg6 Nc6 31. Rxc6 {Black never got a chance! 1-0 Short - Ghaem Maghami, Iran 2016.}) 14. h3 (14. Rc1 Rac8 15. h3 Qb8 16. Qe2 Bf8 17. Rcd1 {was very much similar in Dubov - Grischuk, Moscow 2018, although White pushed too hard and eventually lost.}) 14... Rac8 15. Qe2 Qb8 16. Rad1 $14 {Soon White will start pushing his kingside pawns, and Black is without counterplay.} *

