1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c4 e6 (6... dxc4 7. dxc4 e6 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. Qc2 {followed by b3, Bb2, is pleasant for White. Romanishin - Beliavsky, Vilnius 1980.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 Be7 9. e4 $1 {A typical move for our setup!} dxe4 10. dxe4 Nc5 ({Our pawn is safe; after} 10... Nxe4 $2 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Qe2 Nf6 13. Rd1 $1 Qc8 14. Bg5 {and Black is busted.}) 11. Nd4 $16 {The knight is coming to f5 and White is almost winning. 1-0 Amin - Rozentalis, Sweden 2018.} *

