1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O c5 6. e4 $1 {Here White can play this move right away!} dxe4 7. Nfd2 $5 (7. dxe4 $5 {would be an interesting pawn sac as well, according to the engine.}) 7... e6 8. dxe4 {White recovers his pawn and gets a slightly better pawn structure. After this trade on e4, Black’s pawn has nothing to do on c5, a square that could be, for example, occupied by the bishop (with the help of …a5 to prevent b4).} Nc6 9. c3 Be7 10. e5 $1 {White clears the g4-square for his queen.} Nd5 11. Re1 O-O 12. Qg4 {Followed by Nc4, and White has a very nice position. Black will also have to take measures about Bh6 and the kingside pressure in general.} *

