1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O e6 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 {is possible as well, but I wasn't entirely satisfied after} dxc4 7. Qa4+ {7.dxc4 Qxd1 8.Rxd1 Bd6 9.Nc3 a6 is solid for Black too.} Nbd7 {after what Black has a harmonious position, which I could not break.}) 6... Be7 (6... Nbd7 7. Re1 {followed by e4 is gonna be very similar to the main lines below, except the knight on d7 is not very well placed, as in the event of e4-e5 the f6-knight won't have a good square to go to.}) (6... c5 7. e4 $1 {Here we don't even need to prepare e2-e4.} Nc6 {7...dxe4?! 8.dxe4 Nxe4? 9.Ne5! Nd6 10.Bxb7 Nxb7 11.Qf3 Qc7 12.Ne4! followed by Bf4 with a win.} 8. h4 $5 Be7 {and we have transposed into our mainline.}) 7. e4 c5 8. h4 $146 {I like this move order, waiting for Black to castle shortside before pushing e5. White could also play 8. Re1 with a similar idea.} (8. e5 $6 Nfd7 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Nf1 Qc7 11. Bf4 h6 12. h4 O-O-O {is the kind of stuff to avoid.}) 8... Nc6 9. Re1 {Black should make a decision at some point.} Qc7 (9... dxe4 10. dxe4 {followed by e5, c3, is a good pawn structure for White.}) 10. c3 O-O-O {Without waiting for e4-e5 is too risky.} 11. exd5 exd5 (11... Nxd5 12. Nc4 Kb8 13. a4 {is great for White too.}) 12. a3 {With b4 to come White's attack will be faster.} *

