1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O e6 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 {is possible as well, but I wasn't entirely satisfied after} dxc4 7. Qa4+ {7.dxc4 Qxd1 8.Rxd1 Bd6 9.Nc3 a6 is solid for Black too.} Nbd7 {after what Black has a harmonious position, which I could not break.}) 6... Be7 (6... Nbd7 7. Re1 {followed by e4 is gonna be very similar to the main lines below, except the knight on d7 is not very well placed, as in the event of e4-e5 the f6-knight won't have a good square to go to.}) (6... c5 7. e4 $1 {Here we don't even need to prepare e2-e4.} Nc6 {7...dxe4?! 8.dxe4 Nxe4? 9.Ne5! Nd6 10.Bxb7 Nxb7 11.Qf3 Qc7 12.Ne4! followed by Bf4 with a win.} 8. h4 $5 Be7 {and we have transposed into our mainline.}) 7. e4 c5 8. h4 $146 {I like this move order, waiting for Black to castle shortside before pushing e5. White could also play 8. Re1 with a similar idea.} (8. e5 $6 Nfd7 9. Re1 Nc6 10. Nf1 Qc7 11. Bf4 h6 12. h4 O-O-O {is the kind of stuff to avoid.}) 8... O-O 9. e5 Nfd7 10. Re1 {And we get a great version of ...d5, ...Nf6, ... e6 lines, where Black in the exact same position usually quickly goes ...b5, ...a5, ...Ba6, when here he's just gone ...b6 and ...Bb7. Our plan is simple: Nd2-f1 and then h2-g4 or e3, Bc1-f4, Nf3-g5 etc.} *

