1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O e6 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 {is possible as well, but I wasn't entirely satisfied after} dxc4 7. Qa4+ {7.dxc4 Qxd1 8.Rxd1 Bd6 9.Nc3 a6 is solid for Black too.} Nbd7 {after what Black has a harmonious position, which I could not break.}) 6... Be7 (6... Nbd7 7. Re1 {followed by e4 is gonna be very similar to the main lines below, except the knight on d7 is not very well placed, as in the event of e4-e5 the f6-knight won't have a good square to go to.}) (6... c5 7. e4 $1 {Here we don't even need to prepare e2-e4.} Nc6 {7...dxe4?! 8.dxe4 Nxe4? 9.Ne5! Nd6 10.Bxb7 Nxb7 11.Qf3 Qc7 12.Ne4! followed by Bf4 with a win.} 8. h4 $5 Be7 {and we have transposed into our mainline.}) 7. e4 dxe4 {Black wants to avoid the pawn structure we've seen above.} 8. dxe4 Nc6 (8... Nxe4 $4 {just loses to} 9. Ne5) 9. Qe2 Nd4 {This is in no way an improvement of Black's position.} 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Re1 Nd7 12. Nf3 Qc5 13. Be3 {And what is the black queen doing there? White is just better, 14. Rad1 will follow, with space advantage. Hera - Vovk, Hungary 2018.} *

