1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 $5 {The most obvious way to play against ...b6 and ...Bb7: White will close the black bishop diagonal with e2-e4 or Black will close it himself with ...d7-d5.} d5 5. O-O e6 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 {is possible as well, but I wasn't entirely satisfied after} dxc4 7. Qa4+ {7.dxc4 Qxd1 8.Rxd1 Bd6 9.Nc3 a6 is solid for Black too.} Nbd7 {after what Black has a harmonious position, which I could not break.}) 6... Be7 (6... Nbd7 7. Re1 {followed by e4 is gonna be very similar to the main lines below, except the knight on d7 is not very well placed, as in the event of e4-e5 the f6-knight won't have a good square to go to.}) (6... c5 7. e4 $1 {Here we don't even need to prepare e2-e4.} Nc6 {7...dxe4?! 8.dxe4 Nxe4? 9.Ne5! Nd6 10.Bxb7 Nxb7 11.Qf3 Qc7 12.Ne4! followed by Bf4 with a win.} 8. h4 $5 Be7 {and we have transposed into our mainline.}) 7. e4 dxe4 {Black wants to avoid the pawn structure we've seen above.} 8. dxe4 O-O 9. Qe2 $5 (9. e5 {would allow} Ne4 {with some trades, even if White should be slightly better here as well.}) 9... Nc6 10. e5 Nd7 11. Nb3 $5 {I like this move. With the d-pawns traded, White still has an edge on the kingside, but he should not focus exclusively on this half of the board as the position is quite open.} a5 12. Rd1 {A very unpleasant pin on the d7- knight, since Black doesn't get the time to free the e7 square for the queen.} Qc8 13. Bf4 a4 14. Nbd4 {Black can trade some pieces, but White has a space advantage.} Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qb7+ 17. Qf3 Qxf3+ 18. Kxf3 {This would definitely be a great endgame for White. Not only can we claim a space advantage, but Black's whole queenside is very weak.} *

