1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b5 {A move Black sometimes plays when it's kind of clear that White's light-squared bishop will move to g2, thus not attacking the b5-pawn. Black gains spaces on the queenside and allows a vis-à-vis with the g2-bishop, more actively than with 1... b6.} (2... d6 3. Bg2 e5 4. O-O {followed by c4, Nc3, will be a good version for White of lines we've seen earlier or will see later.}) (2... e6 {will be followed by ...b6 or ...d5 and transpose into other chapters too.}) 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 {As against ...b6 ideas we've seen, this seems to be the most logical to face ...Bb7. White will close the bishop's diagonal with e2-e4 unless Black closes it himself with ...d7-d5.} ({I remember a brilliant victory by Magnus over MVL after} 4. Na3 {when after} a6 5. c4 {Black played} b4 {. However, after 5...e6 ( 5...e5!? also makes sense.) 6.b3 bxc4 7.Nxc4 a5 8.O-O d5!? it looks to me like Black is somehow okay: 9.Nfxe5 c6 10.Nb2 Nfd7 11.Nxd7 Nxd7 with relatively easy play for Black.}) 4... e6 (4... d5 $6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 b5 4.O-O Bb7 5.d3 e6 6.c4 .}) 5. e4 d5 6. exd5 $5 {A fresh idea instead of the usual 6. e5, as White can try to exploit the weaknesses of Black's queenside.} Nxd5 7. O-O {With the idea of Nd4, attacking the b5-pawn and threatening c4, just seems good for White. If the black pawn was on b6 it would be a different story.} *

