1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b5 {A move Black sometimes plays when it's kind of clear that White's light-squared bishop will move to g2, thus not attacking the b5-pawn. Black gains spaces on the queenside and allows a vis-à-vis with the g2-bishop, more actively than with 1... b6.} (2... d6 3. Bg2 e5 4. O-O {followed by c4, Nc3, will be a good version for White of lines we've seen earlier or will see later.}) (2... e6 {will be followed by ...b6 or ...d5 and transpose into other chapters too.}) 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 {As against ...b6 ideas we've seen, this seems to be the most logical to face ...Bb7. White will close the bishop's diagonal with e2-e4 unless Black closes it himself with ...d7-d5.} ({I remember a brilliant victory by Magnus over MVL after} 4. Na3 {when after} a6 5. c4 {Black played} b4 {. However, after 5...e6 ( 5...e5!? also makes sense.) 6.b3 bxc4 7.Nxc4 a5 8.O-O d5!? it looks to me like Black is somehow okay: 9.Nfxe5 c6 10.Nb2 Nfd7 11.Nxd7 Nxd7 with relatively easy play for Black.}) 4... e6 (4... d5 $6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 b5 4.O-O Bb7 5.d3 e6 6.c4 .}) 5. e4 d6 (5... Be7 {will soon transpose as ... d6 is probably next.}) 6. O-O c5 {The most logical move, fighting for the center.} 7. d4 $5 {One of the two best and most challenging moves.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxe4 (8... a6 $6 9. Re1 {is annoying for Black: ...Be7 is met with e5, and otherwise a4, ...b4, c3 will be annoying for Black.}) 9. Bxe4 Nxe4 10. Nxb5 a6 11. Nd4 {Here White will play c4 against almost anything and due to his late development, Black has some problems to solve.} Be7 12. c4 O-O 13. Qf3 d5 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 {This is unpleasant for Black, who cannot move his b8-knight and the d5-pawn is pinned.} *

