1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 b5 {A move Black sometimes plays when it's kind of clear that White's light-squared bishop will move to g2, thus not attacking the b5-pawn. Black gains spaces on the queenside and allows a vis-à-vis with the g2-bishop, more actively than with 1... b6.} (2... d6 3. Bg2 e5 4. O-O {followed by c4, Nc3, will be a good version for White of lines we've seen earlier or will see later.}) (2... e6 {will be followed by ...b6 or ...d5 and transpose into other chapters too.}) 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. d3 {As against ...b6 ideas we've seen, this seems to be the most logical to face ...Bb7. White will close the bishop's diagonal with e2-e4 unless Black closes it himself with ...d7-d5.} ({I remember a brilliant victory by Magnus over MVL after} 4. Na3 {when after} a6 5. c4 {Black played} b4 {. However, after 5...e6 ( 5...e5!? also makes sense.) 6.b3 bxc4 7.Nxc4 a5 8.O-O d5!? it looks to me like Black is somehow okay: 9.Nfxe5 c6 10.Nb2 Nfd7 11.Nxd7 Nxd7 with relatively easy play for Black.}) 4... e6 (4... d5 $6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 b5 4.O-O Bb7 5.d3 e6 6.c4 .}) 5. e4 d6 (5... Be7 {will soon transpose as ... d6 is probably next.}) 6. O-O c5 {The most logical move, fighting for the center.} 7. a4 {This is an interesting alternative to our main move 7. d4.} a6 (7... b4 8. a5 Be7 9. c3 bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Re1 {followed by Nbd2, Nc4, or sometimes d4, and White has a pleasant position.}) 8. d4 $5 {This should be an improved version of 7. d4, but actually leads to an incredible mess.} Nxe4 (8... cxd4 $6 9. Nxd4 {transposes here [/variation/31887656/#/8/w].}) 9. Ng5 (9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. b4 Ncd7 13. Bb2 Nf6 14. Qe2 {should be a simpler option, with a slight advantage for White after regaining the b5-pawn. But 9. Ng5 is a super challenging move!}) 9... d5 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nc3 f5 (11... cxd4 12. Nxe4 Be7 13. Qg4 {and Black has problems.}) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Nxe4 $5 {A very interesting try.} Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Qxd4 (15... fxe4 $2 16. Qh5+ {is bad for Black:} g6 {is met by} 17. Qe5 {, while 16...Kd7 18.dxc5 is killing for White, as Black badly misses his dark-squared bishop to defend.}) 16. Bg2 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 {Even after the queens exchange, White, thanks to the bishop pair, has a dangerous initiative and Black's queenside pawns are weak.} Be7 18. Bf1 $1 c4 19. Re1 $1 Kf7 20. Re5 {White regains the pawn and is better thanks to the bishop pair.} *

