1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 e6 (3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 {followed by Bb2, c4, and the black knight has nothing to do on c6.}) 4. Bg2 Bd6 5. Nbd2 Nf6 6. b3 {Followed by Bb2, c4, O-O, and again the black knight has nothing to do on c6.} O-O 7. Bb2 b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. c4 Ne7 10. Rc1 $16 {Black’s setup is weird, and White has a direct threat of pushing c5. Things are not so simple for Black, as opening long diagonal a1-h8 (e.g. if Black plays…c5) can be very dangerous. From the game Meier - Hefter, Germany 2001.} *

