1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bg4 4. Bg2 Qd7 {The only way to (try to) justify Black's setup.} (4... e6 5. O-O {and after} Nf6 {or 5...Bd6 , White will just play c4 and once again, White has developed perfectly and the knight has nothing to do on c6.}) (4... Nf6 $6 {allows} 5. Ne5 {which is immediately a clear advantage for White:} Bf5 6. c4 e6 7. Qa4 $16) 5. h3 $5 {So that there is no ...Bh3. The following lines are non-exhaustive, as in such a position Black can come up with a weird move at any moment, but they give a good idea of why White is better.} Bf5 6. c4 e6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. g4 {The extra move h3 is useful for White!} Be4 9. g5 {White wants to take the bishop pair, but by including this move he creates extra problems for Black.} Ng8 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Ne5 $1 {Black has concrete problems} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 14. Kc2 {White has a nice advantage thanks to the bishop pair and the falling e4-pawn.} *

