1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bg4 4. Bg2 Qd7 {The only way to (try to) justify Black's setup.} (4... e6 5. O-O {and after} Nf6 {or 5...Bd6 , White will just play c4 and once again, White has developed perfectly and the knight has nothing to do on c6.}) (4... Nf6 $6 {allows} 5. Ne5 {which is immediately a clear advantage for White:} Bf5 6. c4 e6 7. Qa4 $16) 5. h3 $5 {So that there is no ...Bh3. The following lines are non-exhaustive, as in such a position Black can come up with a weird move at any moment, but they give a good idea of why White is better.} Bxf3 6. exf3 $1 (6. Bxf3 O-O-O 7. Bg2 e5 {is unclear.}) 6... e6 7. f4 {The point of the previous move - White has set up a strong pawn structure in the center.} Bd6 8. c3 Nf6 9. Nd2 Ne7 10. Nf3 {With Ne5 to come, White has a good setup: Svane - Horvath, chess.com 2022.} *

