1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bf5 ({Apart from} 3... Bg4 {, or}) (3... Nf6 {to transpose to ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 afterwards, other third moves don't really make sense.}) 4. Bg2 Nb4 {Unlike in the main line you'll see below, here White can't sacrifice an exchange, as ...Nc2 would come with check.} 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O $5 ({A good alternative, together with} 6. Nh4 $5 {which you may explore. If Black retracts his knight to c6, then after Nb1 we are back into the main line. 6.c3 Nc6 would be less dynamic.}) 6... Nf6 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qb3 $14 {With Nh4 to come, winning the bishop pair.} *

