1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bf5 ({Apart from} 3... Bg4 {, or}) (3... Nf6 {to transpose to ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 afterwards, other third moves don't really make sense.}) 4. Bg2 Nb4 {Unlike in the main line you'll see below, here White can't sacrifice an exchange, as ...Nc2 would come with check.} 5. Na3 e6 6. O-O $5 ({A good alternative, together with} 6. Nh4 $5 {which you may explore. If Black retracts his knight to c6, then after Nb1 we are back into the main line. 6.c3 Nc6 would be less dynamic.}) 6... Be7 7. c3 Nc6 8. Qa4 $5 {I found this move very attractive for White and preferred it over the classical 8. Qb3.} Qd7 9. Nb5 $1 {The point of the previous move; the threats of 10. c4 and 10. Bf4 are in the air.} Rc8 (9... a6 $6 10. Ne5 $1 {creates problems, as} Nxe5 $2 {loses to} 11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Qxd7+ Nxd7 13. Nxa8) 10. c4 Nf6 {Now White can enter a fun line.} 11. Ne5 $5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ne4 13. Qxa7 $5 (13. Rd1 {is possible as well.}) 13... c6 14. cxd5 cxd5 (14... cxb5 15. d6 Bd8 16. Be3 {with huge compensation.}) 15. a4 Nc5 16. Nd4 Qd8 {A cute way to trap the white queen.} 17. b4 {Starting a long forced sequence.} Ra8 18. Qxa8 Qxa8 19. bxc5 Bxc5 20. Nxf5 exf5 21. Bxd5 {And White has more than enough compensation for the queen. Remember, if you don't like it, you can just play 13. Rd1.} *

