1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bf5 ({Apart from} 3... Bg4 {, or}) (3... Nf6 {to transpose to ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 afterwards, other third moves don't really make sense.}) 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O {White takes his time before playing the logical c4 so that the move ...Nb4 becomes less threatening.} e6 6. c4 Be7 7. Ne5 $5 {White goes for favorable trades.} O-O 8. Nc3 {The c6-knight is misplaced, as it blocks the c7-pawn. Black can decide to play a worse position with no plan, or trade on e5 and get a worse position as follows.} Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ne4 {Black enters a forcing line which is gonna end badly for him.} 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 exd5 12. Qb3 {And White will win a pawn.} *

