1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bf5 ({Apart from} 3... Bg4 {, or}) (3... Nf6 {to transpose to ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 afterwards, other third moves don't really make sense.}) 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Nb4 6. c4 $5 ({White can also play} 6. Na3 {or}) (6. Ne1 {, but this forcing line is by far the most dangerous for Black. Black holds with precise play - but it is too tempting to play this position as White.}) 6... Nc2 7. cxd5 $1 (7. Nh4 {followed by Nxf5 and cxd5 or Nc3 is another possible exchange sacrifice, but it is by far easier to handle as Black than the one I suggest.}) 7... Nxa1 8. e4 $1 (8. dxe6 fxe6 9. e4 Bxe4 {would be a transposition to the mainline, except it would give Black the extra option to play 8... Bxe6.}) 8... Bxe4 9. dxe6 fxe6 (9... f6 $2 10. Nc3 Bc2 11. Qe2 c6 12. d5 $1 Ne7 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. Bf4 {is a total nightmare for Black: 1-0 Matlakov - Dzhumagaliev, Tallinn 2016.}) 10. Nc3 {White has sacrificed an exchange, but Black faces real problems, since he is underdeveloped, his center is weak, and White's material deficit is not so great, since the a1 knight is unlikely to escape.} Bc6 $2 {he wrong square for the bishop, as the following variations prove.} 11. Re1 Be7 12. d5 $1 {Boom! Black has huge concrete problems now.} Bxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Nd4 Qd7 15. Bxb7 Z0 ({And after} 15... Rd8 {the position was just winning for White in Andreikin - Vokhidov, Almaty 2022, when} 16. Qf3 {would have been even more precise than the game continuation.}) *

