1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nc6 {Black wants to push ...e5. Of course, allowing it wouldn't necessarily be bad, it would be no less than some sort of reversed Pirc with an extra tempo. Nevertheless, with the black knight on c6 blocking Black's c-pawn, pushing d4 to prevent ...e5 is by far the most logical.} 3. d4 Bf5 ({Apart from} 3... Bg4 {, or}) (3... Nf6 {to transpose to ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 afterwards, other third moves don't really make sense.}) 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O Nb4 6. c4 $5 ({White can also play} 6. Na3 {or}) (6. Ne1 {, but this forcing line is by far the most dangerous for Black. Black holds with precise play - but it is too tempting to play this position as White.}) 6... Nc2 7. cxd5 $1 (7. Nh4 {followed by Nxf5 and cxd5 or Nc3 is another possible exchange sacrifice, but it is by far easier to handle as Black than the one I suggest.}) 7... Nxa1 8. e4 $1 (8. dxe6 fxe6 9. e4 Bxe4 {would be a transposition to the mainline, except it would give Black the extra option to play 8... Bxe6.}) 8... Bxe4 9. dxe6 fxe6 (9... f6 $2 10. Nc3 Bc2 11. Qe2 c6 12. d5 $1 Ne7 13. Nd4 Bg6 14. Bf4 {is a total nightmare for Black: 1-0 Matlakov - Dzhumagaliev, Tallinn 2016.}) 10. Nc3 {White has sacrificed an exchange, but Black faces real problems, since he is underdeveloped, his center is weak, and White's material deficit is not so great, since the a1 knight is unlikely to escape.} Bxf3 $1 {By far the best move - played by Caruana! Here both recaptures are interesting, but kind of hold for Black with absolutely perfect play.} 11. Qxf3 (11. Bxf3 Qd7 $1 {11...Nf6? 12.Bxb7 Rb8 13.Bc6+ Kf7 14.Be3 looks disgusting for Black.} 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Nf6 14. Qe2 {14.Bh3 Be7 15.Qe2 Rb6 16.Bf4 O-O 17.Rxa1 Nd5 18.Nxd5 Qxd5 is also kind of okay for Black, who will go ...Rxf4 at some point if necessary.} Be7 15. Bf4 {15.Bh3 Rb6 $132} O-O 16. Rxa1 Nd5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rc1 {and here in Ding Liren - Caruana, chess24.com 2020, Black should have gone} Rxf4 $1 19. gxf4 Rf8 {and he is very close to equality.}) 11... Nf6 12. Qe2 $5 (12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Be7 {and Black sort of survives.}) 12... Be7 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Bc6+ Kf7 15. Bf4 $1 {The best try, controlling the important d6-square.} (15. Be3 {is analyzed in the next informational [/variation/31976971].}) 15... Nc2 $5 (15... Qxd4 16. Re1 $1 {is definitely problematic for Black.}) 16. Qxc2 Qxd4 17. Re1 {And White definitely has enough compensation and sits on the more comfortable side of the board.} *

