1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Nf6 5. Bg2 c6 6. O-O h6 {Black’s only logical square to develop his c8-bishop is f5, and Black plays ...h6 as prophylactic measure against Nh4.} 7. a4 a5 {White has decided to play a4 and provoke ...a5. It is good for him to have these moves included as when the position opens, Black’s queenside pawn structure will be less flexible.} 8. Re1 {White wants to play e4, gaining space and semi-opening the diagonal of his g2-bishop.} Bf5 9. Ne5 {Improving the position of the knight while enabling e2-e4 again.} e6 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Be7 12. c3 {Now that White has opened the position, he is definitely sitting on the more pleasant side of the board thanks to his extra space and strong e5-knight.} *

