1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Nf6 5. Bg2 g6 6. a4 {A typical move against the b6-knight; including a4 and forcing Black to play ...a5 is in White's favour.} a5 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 {The plans are always similar.} Bf5 9. Nh4 {Attacking the f5 bishop and at the same time preparing the e4 advance.} Be6 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {With a small edge for White, nevermind if Black trades b7 for d4 or not.} *

