1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Nf6 5. Bg2 Bf5 {The logical follow-up.} 6. Nh4 e6 7. Nxf5 exf5 8. Qd3 g6 (8... Ne4 $6 {makes it worse for Black:} 9. f3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qf6 11. e4 $16 {Lorparizangeneh - Romanov, Sousse 2021.}) 9. a4 a5 10. f3 $146 {By including a4 and ...a5, White has weakened the b5-square. And now it is time to strike in the center! This was still a novelty while I was working on the course. But not anymore. It was played in August 2023 in the game Beydullayeva - Swayams.} Bg7 11. e4 $1 fxe4 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 O-O 14. Bg5 {White completes his development as he wants to castle longside and start an attack.} h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. O-O-O $1 {White goes “all-in”. Having included a4 and ...a5 costs you a pawn, you might say, but the position is very concrete now.} Nxa4 17. h4 {And the attack is coming fast!} *

