1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Bf5 5. Nh4 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qd3 e6 8. e4 {This position has been played three times: all by GM Svane!} Be7 9. Ng2 (9. exd5 exd5 10. Nf5 Bf6 11. Bf4 {was played in Svane - Lopez Gracia, chess.com 2022, but after} Ne7 {Black's position looks fine.}) 9... Bg6 10. Nf4 {We go for the bishop pair.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Bf5 12. g4 {We want that bishop!} Bxe4 13. Qxe4 c6 14. c3 {A Caro-Kann-like position arises, where we get the bishop pair and control all important central squares.} Nf6 15. Qe2 Nfd5 16. Nd3 {With Bg2 next and White has a typical slight advantage. The idea behind Nd3 is that the knight controls e5 and c5 while Black has two knights and only one good square for them: d5.} (16. Bg2 $14 {is not bad either.}) *

