1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Bf5 5. Nh4 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qd3 e6 8. e4 {This position has been played three times: all by GM Svane!} c6 (8... dxe4 $4 {falls into a beginner trick, though such things can always accidentally happen:} 9. Qb5+ c6 10. Qxh5) 9. exd5 $146 {An interesting novelty forcing Black to make a decision: weaken either the b5 or d5 square. The natural way to play is to try to get a symmetrical position, but White is more dynamic and obtains a good position as we will see.} exd5 10. Bg2 Be7 11. Nf5 Bf6 12. O-O Ne7 {Black manages to trade the dangerous f5-knight.} 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. f4 $1 {But now White expands on the kingside and threatens to trap the h5-bishop with g4 and f5.} f6 15. g4 Bf7 16. b3 $5 {Just reducing the b6-knight’s potential even more.} O-O 17. Ne2 {Followed by f5, Nf4, and White has a pleasant position.} *

