1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 {The most natural way to play when Black clearly shows his intentions to push ...e5.} Nb6 {This is Black's idea: stopping c4. Other moves are of no interest: they'll just, at the very best, transpose into another chapter.} 4. Nc3 $1 {The best setup. White wants to play e4.} Bf5 5. Nh4 Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 7. Qd3 e6 8. e4 {This position has been played three times: all by GM Svane!} c6 (8... dxe4 $4 {falls into a beginner trick, though such things can always accidentally happen:} 9. Qb5+ c6 10. Qxh5) 9. Ng2 $5 {This is possible as well.} Bg6 ({The novelty} 9... Bb4 $1 {is the reason why 9.Ng2 is probably not the best continuation.} 10. Nf4 dxe4 11. Qxe4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 {folllowed by ...Nf6 and ...Qd5, or ...Bxc3+ and ...Qd5 right away in the event of 13. Bg2.}) 10. Nf4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nf6 (11... Bf5 12. c3 Nf6 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Qe2 Bd6 15. Nh5 Qg6 16. g4 {and Black has problems with his bishop, as Nxg7 is next.}) 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bg2 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Be7 15. h4 Nd5 16. Bd2 $14 {With a typical slight advantage due to the extra space and bishop pair: Svane - Kovalenko, chess.com 2023.} *

