1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... e6 5. O-O Qb6 $6 ({A)} 5... Nf6 {transposes to 4...Nf6 5.O-O e6}) ({B)} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 7. Nb3 Be7 {7...Bb6 8.c4 Nf6 transposes into 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6 7.O-O Bc5 8.Nb3 Bb6 • 8...Nge7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 transposes to 8...Nf6 9.cxd5 Nxd5 • 8...dxc4? 9.Qxd8+ Bxd8 10.N3d2 $16 with an awful endgame for Black.} 8. c4 Nf6 {transposes into 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6 7.O-O Bc5 8.Nb3 Be7}) 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nc3 $5 {Threatening both Na4 and e4 is also good for White. White is simply better right away.} *

