1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... e6 5. O-O cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5 7. Nb3 Bb6 (7... Be7 8. c4 Nf6 {transposes here [/variation/31872484/#/8/w].}) 8. c4 Nge7 (8... dxc4 $2 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 $16 {Ned2 with an awful endgame for Black.}) (8... Nf6 {transposes here [/variation/31872484/#/8/w].}) 9. cxd5 exd5 ({An interesting option, played by Jorden van Voreest amongst others.} 9... Nxd5 {transposes.}) 10. Nc3 O-O $1 (10... d4 11. Na4 {would likely transpose as} Bc7 $2 12. e3 $1 {is definitely bad for Black: White's pieces are powerful.}) 11. Na4 (11. Nxd5 $6 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxd5 Bg4 {with compensation for Black.}) 11... d4 12. Bd2 $5 ({I believe White should play calmly and not hurry to take the bishop pair. After} 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. e3 d3 $1 {Black was dynamic enough in Amin - Van Foreest, Almaty 2022, 1-0.}) 12... Re8 13. Nxb6 {An excellent practical try.} Qxb6 (13... axb6 14. e3 $1 d3 {is now too slow due to} 15. Bc3 $1 {and the d4-pawn will be a serious weakness.}) 14. e3 Nf5 $1 {The only move not to get immediately worse according to the engine!} 15. exd4 Ncxd4 16. Re1 $1 Be6 (16... Rxe1+ 17. Bxe1 Be6 18. Bc3 {with a wonderful bishop pair.}) 17. Bc3 $1 {The start of a long forced line.} Bxb3 18. axb3 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 (19. Bxe1 Nxb3 20. Ra3 {and the position is equal.}) 19... Nc2 20. Qe4 Nxa1 21. Qxf5 Nxb3 (21... Qe6 22. Qg5 Qg6 23. Qd5 Re8 24. h4 {would be pleasant for White.}) 22. Bd5 Z0 ({And now after} 22... Kh8 {(forced)} 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Qxf7+ Kh8 25. Be4 Qh6 {Again a forced move.} 26. Qxb7 Rf8 27. Qxb3 Qd2 28. Bf3 Qd4 {Black holds some sort of equality as the f3-bishop can hardly move.}) *

