1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are} 7. Ne5 {and}) (7. Qa4 {, but they're known to be fine for Black.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {We've transposed into a main line of the Catalan.} 9. Nfd2 $5 ({This move has become popular some years ago, instead of the traditional} 9. Nbd2 c3 {line. However, since then, solutions have been found for Black to make a draw. Nevertheless, I would like to suggest that line which is really not easy to play for Black over the board, especially if he has transposed into this line somehow accidentally.}) 9... Nd4 {This move seems to be a surprising equalizer as well.} 10. Nc3 Nd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bxd5 O-O $1 ({You really get to know that!} 12... Nxe2+ $6 13. Kg2 $1 {It is important not to allow ...Bh3+ later. Here White will be better thanks to his space advantage.}) 13. Ne4 $5 (13. Bxc4 Rd8 14. Bd3 Bg4 15. Kf1 Bh3+ 16. Kg1 Bg4 {and White has nothing better than repeating moves: Turov - Fridman, Tallinn 2020.}) 13... Rd8 14. Nxc5 Rxd5 15. Be3 Nxe2+ 16. Kg2 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 Bf5 {Forced.} 18. Rd5 ({And there's somehow no way to trap the black knight, e.g. Bb1 19.Kf1 b6□ 20.Kxe2 bxc5 and Black will suffer a little bit, especially if White can put his bishop on c3, a dream square, but the position should be a draw. Kourkoulos Arditis - Bharath, Kavala 2022. •} 18. Kf1 Bg4 $132) ({•} 18. Kf3 b6 $1 {$132 Kourkoulos Arditis - Bharath, Kavala 2022.}) *

