1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are} 7. Ne5 {and}) (7. Qa4 {, but they're known to be fine for Black.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {We've transposed into a main line of the Catalan.} 9. Nfd2 $5 ({This move has become popular some years ago, instead of the traditional} 9. Nbd2 c3 {line. However, since then, solutions have been found for Black to make a draw. Nevertheless, I would like to suggest that line which is really not easy to play for Black over the board, especially if he has transposed into this line somehow accidentally.}) 9... Na5 $1 {The best move.} 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. bxa3 {It took quite a while for even the best GMs to find equality for Black here, but it seems that few solutions exist if the Black's play is extremely accurate. But also remember that Black also has many ways to go wrong!} Bd7 12. Bb2 Bc6 $5 13. Bxc6+ (13. Bc3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Nc6 15. Nxc4 O-O {is somehow similar.}) 13... Nxc6 14. Nxc4 O-O 15. Nd6 (15. Rac1 {is even easier for Black:} Rfd8 16. a4 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Rd8 {Fressinet - Burg, Bremen 2023.}) 15... Rab8 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Ne4 Kg7 18. Rd7 Rfd8 19. Rad1 {Here White can push a little bit, but with good play by Black this is also a draw: Kazakouski - Van Wely, Tornelo 2021.} *

