1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are} 7. Ne5 {and}) (7. Qa4 {, but they're known to be fine for Black.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {We've transposed into a main line of the Catalan.} 9. Nfd2 $5 ({This move has become popular some years ago, instead of the traditional} 9. Nbd2 c3 {line. However, since then, solutions have been found for Black to make a draw. Nevertheless, I would like to suggest that line which is really not easy to play for Black over the board, especially if he has transposed into this line somehow accidentally.}) 9... Na5 $1 {The best move.} 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. bxa3 {It took quite a while for even the best GMs to find equality for Black here, but it seems that few solutions exist if the Black's play is extremely accurate. But also remember that Black also has many ways to go wrong!} Bd7 12. Bb2 Rc8 13. Bc3 b6 14. Rdc1 Rc7 $1 {Another important move, though not as forcing as others we will see.} (14... O-O 15. Bxa5 bxa5 16. Nxc4 {and Black has problems: Prohaszka - Fridman, Saint Louis 2018.}) 15. Rab1 {This seems to be like the best try, to provoke ...O-O as ...Ke7 would be met by Bb4+, and allowing Bxa5 and Rb8+ would be too much.} ({• After} 15. Bxa5 bxa5 {the main difference is that Black hasn't castled and will equalize with ...Ke7:} 16. Rxc4 {16.Nxc4 Ke7 17.Nxa5 Rhc8 18.Nb3 Rc2 with enough compensation: Fridman - Yilmaz, chess.com 2020.} Rxc4 17. Nxc4 Ke7 18. Nxa5 Rc8 $13 {With ...Rc2 coming, and Black is totally fine. Dominguez Perez - Anand, Saint Louis 2018.}) ({•} 15. Bb4 $146 Nd5 16. e4 Nxb4 17. axb4 Nc6 18. Rxc4 {looks tempting but after} Kd8 $1 19. Rac1 Rc8 20. a3 g5 {followed by ...f6, ... Ke7, White has no way to breakthrough.}) ({•} 15. Be5 Rc8 $1 {and with or without including Rab1, Bc3 and ...Rc7 will be repeated.}) 15... O-O 16. Bxa5 bxa5 17. Nxc4 $1 (17. Rxc4 Rfc8 $1 18. Rxc7 Rxc7 19. Rb8+ Be8 {is just equal: Fedoseev - Nihal, St Petersburg 2018.}) 17... g5 $1 {Black gains space on the kingside and makes room for his king.} 18. Bb7 $146 ({The best try.} 18. Nd6 {doesn't give any advantage:} Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Rb8 20. Nb7 Nd5 21. Nxa5 {Studer - Haug, Gibraltar 2020.}) (18. Nxa5 Rfc8 {gives Black enough compensation for a draw.}) 18... a4 19. Ba6 Bc8 20. Bb5 Bd7 21. Bxd7 Rxd7 22. Kf1 {White sits on the easier side of the board, even if the position should be a draw.} *

