1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are} 7. Ne5 {and}) (7. Qa4 {, but they're known to be fine for Black.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {We've transposed into a main line of the Catalan.} 9. Nfd2 $5 ({This move has become popular some years ago, instead of the traditional} 9. Nbd2 c3 {line. However, since then, solutions have been found for Black to make a draw. Nevertheless, I would like to suggest that line which is really not easy to play for Black over the board, especially if he has transposed into this line somehow accidentally.}) 9... Na5 $1 {The best move.} 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. bxa3 {It took quite a while for even the best GMs to find equality for Black here, but it seems that few solutions exist if the Black's play is extremely accurate. But also remember that Black also has many ways to go wrong!} O-O (11... Nd5 12. Ne4 O-O {transposes.}) 12. Ne4 (12. Bb2 Nd5 13. Rac1 b5 14. Ne4 Bb7 {Tricky. 14...a6!? $146 with the idea of meeting Nd6 or Nc5 with ...Nb7 should be fine as well. Anyway, after the following more or less forced sequence, Black seemed fine as well.} 15. Nd6 Bc6 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 Nb7 18. Nf5 Rfe8 $1 19. Nxg7 Rxe2 20. Nf5 Re6 21. Nd4 Nc5 $1 {= $13 Vidit - Aronian, chess24.com 2021. Black's knight (and central pawns after a capture on e6 ) give him enough compensation.}) 12... Nd5 $1 {One of the paths to equality.} 13. Bd2 Nc6 14. Rac1 $1 (14. Nc3 Rd8 15. Rab1 f6 16. Be1 Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Kf7 {was fine for Black in Fressinet - Edouard, Nimes 2018.}) 14... b6 15. Rxc4 Nce7 16. Rcc1 Ba6 17. e3 {This isn't much, but White sits on the easier side of the board. The bishop pair is slightly more important than the doubled pawns, especially since a4-a5 could come soon: Ivanchuk - Adams, Batumi 2019.} *

