1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc5 ({The alternatives are} 7. Ne5 {and}) (7. Qa4 {, but they're known to be fine for Black.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {We've transposed into a main line of the Catalan.} 9. Nfd2 $5 ({This move has become popular some years ago, instead of the traditional} 9. Nbd2 c3 {line. However, since then, solutions have been found for Black to make a draw. Nevertheless, I would like to suggest that line which is really not easy to play for Black over the board, especially if he has transposed into this line somehow accidentally.}) 9... Na5 $1 {The best move.} 10. Na3 Bxa3 11. bxa3 {It took quite a while for even the best GMs to find equality for Black here, but it seems that few solutions exist if the Black's play is extremely accurate. But also remember that Black also has many ways to go wrong!} O-O (11... Nd5 12. Ne4 O-O {transposes.}) 12. Ne4 (12. Bb2 Nd5 13. Rac1 b5 14. Ne4 Bb7 {Tricky. 14...a6!? $146 with the idea of meeting Nd6 or Nc5 with ...Nb7 should be fine as well. Anyway, after the following more or less forced sequence, Black seemed fine as well.} 15. Nd6 Bc6 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 Nb7 18. Nf5 Rfe8 $1 19. Nxg7 Rxe2 20. Nf5 Re6 21. Nd4 Nc5 $1 {= $13 Vidit - Aronian, chess24.com 2021. Black's knight (and central pawns after a capture on e6 ) give him enough compensation.}) 12... Nd5 $1 {One of the paths to equality.} 13. Bd2 b6 $1 {The most precise.} 14. Rac1 (14. Nc3 {trades too many pieces as well:} Bb7 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bxa5 bxa5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 Rfc8 {followed by ...Rab8 with a highly likely draw: Vitiugov - Esipenko, Moscow 2021.}) 14... Rb8 $1 {An important discovery.} 15. Nd6 (15. Bb4 $146 Rd8 16. Bxa5 bxa5 17. Nc5 Re8 {or 17...Rf8 doesn't lead to anything either.}) 15... Rd8 16. e4 Rxd6 17. exd5 f6 {The somehow 'simple' move that equalizes, in order to meet Bf4 with ...e5.} 18. Re1 (18. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 $17) (18. Bb4 $6 Rd8 19. d6 Bd7 20. Bxa5 bxa5 21. Rxc4 Rb6 $15) 18... Bb7 {White has no choice but to trade everything and make a draw.} 19. Bxa5 (19. Rxe6 Rxe6 20. dxe6 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rc8 22. f4 f5) 19... bxa5 20. dxe6 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 {And the game ended in a draw in Bluebaum - Buhmann, Austria 2017. Of course, we would have preferred the 9. Nfd2 line to bring some advantage, but the most important is how precise Black should be if he doesn't want to be under huge pressure. There are many ways to go wrong and very few to equalize or almost equalize.} *

