1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 ({We go for a reversed Grunfeld.} 4. O-O e5 5. d3 {would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.}) 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {6...e6 7.c4 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e6} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.d4 cxd4 5.Nxd4 d5 6.c4 e5 etc.}) 6. b3 $5 {This is the only interesting alternative to challenge Black.} Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. c4 dxc4 $1 (9... Qe7 $6 10. cxd5 Rd8 11. Nc3 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Rxd5 13. Qc2 {and Black has coordination problems.}) 10. Qc1 Qe7 $1 {This move leads to equality. Nevertheless, practically speaking, it is not easy to take the natural retreat square of the black bishop.} (10... Bd7 $6 11. Qxc4 Be7 12. Rd1 {would be unpleasant for Black.}) 11. Qxc4 e5 {The easiest.} 12. Rc1 b6 $1 ({Precise.} 12... Bb6 $4 13. Ba3) (12... Bd6 13. Nbd2 {would be easier to play as White, with ideas like Qh4 followed by Nc4.}) 13. Nbd2 Be6 $5 14. Qh4 Rad8 15. e3 Bf5 $1 {A forced path to equality.} 16. Nc4 e4 17. Nfe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qe6 $1 19. h3 {Black is fine here. Anyway, I consider 6.b3 as an interesting alternative, to get Black out of theory. You may decide depending if your opponent seems confident or not - if he isn't, he's probably transposed into a Catalan ( 6.c4 ) he's not especially happy about. If he is, he probably knows what he is doing, and you can test him with 6. b3!} *

