1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We go for a reversed Grunfeld. 4.O-O e5 5.d3 would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.} Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch Opening.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. dxc5 ({We aim for a good Catalan type of position. The other option is} 8. Nc3 $5 {.}) 8... Bxc5 9. a3 O-O 10. Qc2 {White will get a more pleasant positions. Here some examples.} Z0 ({•} 10... Bb6 11. Nbd2 Bd7 12. Qd3 Rc8 13. Nc4 $14 {• 10...Be7 11.Rd1 Bd7 12.e4 Nb6 13.Nc3 Rc8 14.Bf4 $14 • 10...Qe7 11.b4 Bb6 12.Bb2 Rd8 13.Nbd2 e5 14.Nc4 $14 White has a good coordination and is threatening to win the bishop pair. 10.b4 is considered good, but after 10...Be7 11.Bb2 Bf6 12.Qb3 Bxb2 13.Qxb2 Qf6 14.Qxf6 gxf6 the endgame does not seem that easy.}) *

