1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We go for a reversed Grunfeld. 4.O-O e5 5.d3 would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.} Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch Opening.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5 ({The classical approach, though} 9. Bg5 {has been played more often.}) 9... d4 $6 {This is just a dubious line.} 10. Na4 Bf5 11. b4 $1 {Probably not the only move to take an advantage - but my favourite one!} d3 $1 {Trying to get rid of the d4-weakness.} 12. e3 $1 Nxb4 13. Rb1 $146 ({Till now everyone's been playing} 13. Nd4 {, but I like this simple move more. It has never been played but is recommended by GM Adrien Demuth in his book on the Reti.}) 13... Nxa2 (13... Nc2 14. Rxb7 Be4 15. Rb3 $1 Rc8 16. Bb2 $16 {with Nd4/h4/e5 to follow, and Black's position won't remain harmonious for long.}) 14. Nd4 Bd7 {Black threatens ...Bxa4 followed by ...Nc3.} 15. Bd2 $1 {Covering the c3-square.} Qe8 16. Rxb7 $1 Bxa4 17. Rxe7 $1 {Forcing the exchange of queens.} Bxd1 (17... Qxe7 $2 18. Qxa4 {and the a2-knight gets trapped.}) 18. Rxe8 Raxe8 19. Rxd1 $16 {With an overwhelming advantage for White, to quote GM Adrien Demuth, who is fully right.} *

