1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We go for a reversed Grunfeld. 4.O-O e5 5.d3 would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.} Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch Opening.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5 ({The classical approach, though} 9. Bg5 {has been played more often.}) 9... Bxc5 10. Na4 $5 (10. a3 $5 {is suggested by GM Adrien Demuth, but I believe Black equalizes by force and 'cleans' the position too much compared to my suggestion.} Ne4 $1 11. Nxd5 $5 {11.Qc2!? Nxc3 12.Qxc3 Bb6 13.b4 Bf5!? 14.Bb2 d4 15.Qd2 Be4 is pretty dry with accurate play by Black.} Be6 12. Nc3 Qxd1 $5 13. Nxd1 Na5 $1 {Black gets enough compensation.} 14. b4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Be7 $1 16. Rxb3 $5 {The beginning of a long forced line.} Bxb3 17. Nd4 Bxd1 18. Bxe4 Ba4 19. Bxb7 Rab8 $1 {Avoiding Nc6.} 20. Bc6 Bxc6 21. Nxc6 Rb7 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Be3 Rc8 {With a dry equality as the black rooks are too active.}) 10... Be7 11. Be3 {An old and quite primitive idea: reinforcing the control of the d4-square.} Ne4 12. Nd4 (12. Rc1 $5 {is possible as well.}) 12... Nxd4 (12... Ne5 $6 13. Rc1 {prevents ...Nc4 and makes ...Ne5 pointless.}) 13. Bxd4 Bf5 14. Nc3 Qd7 15. e3 $14 {White will centralize his rooks and get a small but stable advantage.} *

