1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We go for a reversed Grunfeld. 4.O-O e5 5.d3 would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.} Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch Opening.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5 ({The classical approach, though} 9. Bg5 {has been played more often.}) 9... Bxc5 10. Na4 $5 (10. a3 $5 {is suggested by GM Adrien Demuth, but I believe Black equalizes by force and 'cleans' the position too much compared to my suggestion.} Ne4 $1 11. Nxd5 $5 {11.Qc2!? Nxc3 12.Qxc3 Bb6 13.b4 Bf5!? 14.Bb2 d4 15.Qd2 Be4 is pretty dry with accurate play by Black.} Be6 12. Nc3 Qxd1 $5 13. Nxd1 Na5 $1 {Black gets enough compensation.} 14. b4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Be7 $1 16. Rxb3 $5 {The beginning of a long forced line.} Bxb3 17. Nd4 Bxd1 18. Bxe4 Ba4 19. Bxb7 Rab8 $1 {Avoiding Nc6.} 20. Bc6 Bxc6 21. Nxc6 Rb7 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Be3 Rc8 {With a dry equality as the black rooks are too active.}) 10... Be7 11. Be3 {An old and quite primitive idea: reinforcing the control of the d4-square.} Re8 12. Rc1 Ne4 13. Nd4 (13. Nc3 {is a good try, but after} Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Bf6 15. Rd3 Qe7 $1 {the position is quite unclear.}) 13... Bd7 ({Defending the pawn.} 13... Bf6 14. Nc5 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 {is great for White. This is likely to finish with a strong g2-bishop vs a poor bishop on e6 defending the d5-weakness.}) 14. Nc3 $1 {White wants to clear knights from the board in order to exploit the d5-weakness.} Bf6 ({An interesting practical try.} 14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 {just helps White.}) (14... Nxc3 {isn't any better.} 15. Rxc3 Bf6 16. Rc5 $16) 15. Nxd5 Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Be6 17. Bxe4 Bxd5 18. Bf6 ({This is probably more precise than} 18. Bb6 Qxb6 19. Bxd5 Rad8 20. e4 Nb4 21. Qf3 Nxd5 22. exd5 Qxb2 23. Rc7 {and Black suffered big time in Le Quang Liem -Boros, Burlingame 2019.}) 18... Qxf6 19. Bxd5 Rad8 20. e4 Nb4 21. Qb3 {And the b-file is ours.} *

