1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 {This is the start of one of the best lines for Black.} 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 {We go for a reversed Grunfeld. 4.O-O e5 5.d3 would be a reversed King's Indian, but I simply did not like it from the White side. Only having to equalize (while White tries to be better against the King's Indian) gives Black too many possibilities to play and obtain a reasonable position.} Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 Be7 {Black wants to transpose to a Tarrasch Opening.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. dxc5 ({The classical approach, though} 9. Bg5 {has been played more often.}) 9... Bxc5 10. Na4 $5 (10. a3 $5 {is suggested by GM Adrien Demuth, but I believe Black equalizes by force and 'cleans' the position too much compared to my suggestion.} Ne4 $1 11. Nxd5 $5 {11.Qc2!? Nxc3 12.Qxc3 Bb6 13.b4 Bf5!? 14.Bb2 d4 15.Qd2 Be4 is pretty dry with accurate play by Black.} Be6 12. Nc3 Qxd1 $5 13. Nxd1 Na5 $1 {Black gets enough compensation.} 14. b4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Be7 $1 16. Rxb3 $5 {The beginning of a long forced line.} Bxb3 17. Nd4 Bxd1 18. Bxe4 Ba4 19. Bxb7 Rab8 $1 {Avoiding Nc6.} 20. Bc6 Bxc6 21. Nxc6 Rb7 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Be3 Rc8 {With a dry equality as the black rooks are too active.}) 10... Be7 11. Be3 {An old and quite primitive idea: reinforcing the control of the d4-square.} Re8 12. Rc1 Bg4 (12... Bf8 13. Nd4 {does not help Black.}) 13. h3 {Again, I like to play this move before Black prevents it with ...Qd7.} Bh5 14. Nc3 {The knight has done its job: removing the bishop from c5. Now it's time to target the d5-pawn again.} (14. Nc5 {isn't convincing:} Bxc5 15. Bxc5 Qd7 16. Kh2 Rad8 {with an unclear position in Georgiev -Seitaj, Prishtina 2021.}) 14... Bb4 $1 ({The best defense.} 14... Qd7 $2 15. g4 Bg6 16. g5 {followed with Qxd5 is just an extra pawn for White.}) 15. Qb3 $5 {Going for a positional advantage instead of forced complications.} (15. Bg5 {is a good try as well. A long more or less forced line would be} Bxc3 16. Rxc3 d4 17. Rd3 h6 18. Nxd4 $1 {and now after} Nxd4 19. Rxd4 Qb6 20. Rd6 $1 Bxe2 $1 21. Qd2 Qxd6 $1 22. Qxd6 Bxf1 {we are heading to a position where Black is sitting on the hard site of the board, but should be able to escape, e.g.} 23. Bxf1 $1 {23.Bxf6 Bxg2 24.Kxg2 Re6 25.Qc7 gxf6 26.Qxb7 Ree8 should hold for Black.} hxg5 24. Qc7 Rac8 25. Qxb7 Rc2 {and Black should have enough counterplay for a draw, the main point being that} 26. b3 $2 {fails to} Re1 27. Kg2 Ne4 {and Black is better. Back to move 25, if White is unable to get his bishop to c4, Black should be able to keep his rooks active.}) 15... Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Na5 17. Qd1 Nc4 (17... Nc6 18. Rc1 h6 19. Qa4 {followed by Rfd1 gives White a small and stable advantage.}) 18. Bg5 Nxb2 19. Qb3 Nc4 20. Rd1 {Black is facing concrete problems, and can't solve them all.} *

