. Rd6 $1 Bxe2 $1 21. Qd2 Qxd6 $1 22. Qxd6 Bxf1 {we are heading to a position where Black is sitting on the hard site of the board, but should be able to escape, e.g.} 23. Bxf1 $1 {23.Bxf6 Bxg2 24.Kxg2 Re6 25.Qc7 gxf6 26.Qxb7 Ree8 should hold for Black.} hxg5 24. Qc7 Rac8 25. Qxb7 Rc2 {and Black should have enough counterplay for a draw, the main point being that} 26. b3 $2 {fails to} Re1 27. Kg2 Ne4 {and Black is better. Back to move 25, if White is unable to get his bishop to c4, Black should be able to keep his rooks active.}) 15... Bxc3 16. Rxc3 Na5 17. Qd1 h6 {Preventing Bg5, the f6-knight being an important defender of the d5-pawn.} 18. Nd4 Ne4 19. Bxe4 $1 {An unusual move, after which White will consolidate his kingside and increase his advantage on the dark squares.} Rxe4 20. f3 Re8 21. b3 Z0 ({Preventing ...Nc4. After} 21... Rc8 22. Qd2 Rxc3 23. Qxc3 Nc6 24. Nxc6 bxc6 25. Kf2 {Black is going to suffer: White will play g4 soon, completely consolidating the light squares, while we dominate on the dark-squares and have targets on c6 and a7.}) *

