$1 17. Rfd1 Nd5 $1 {doesn't lead to anything for White after} 18. Bd2 Ne5 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. Qxc5 Nxf3 21. exf3 d3 $1 {with a likely ...Rc8 or ...Re2 next.}) ({•} 16. Bc5 b6 {or 16...h5!? doesn't give White any advantage.}) 16... d4 17. Bg5 $146 (17. Rfd1 {has been played in the only existing OTB game.} Nd5 $1 {$146 17...Qf5?! 18.Bf4 g5? 19.Bc7! Rd7 20.g4! Qg6 21.Qxb7+- went very wrong for Black in Michiels - Tomov, Belgium 2019.} 18. Bd2 {18.Nc5 Nxe3+ 19.fxe3 Bxc5 20.Rxc5 Qe7 is just fine for Black.} Ne5 {And I am not even convinced White is even able to 'push' here, e.g.} 19. Ba5 b6 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. Be1 Rd7 {with equality.}) 17... Ne5 $1 18. Rfd1 {After this move White is able to press.} (18. Bxf6 {is very tempting, but after the weird} gxf6 $1 {18...Bxf6?! 19.Nc5 just wins a pawn. Black just seems fine due to the misplaced knight on a4, e.g.} 19. Rfd1 b6 20. Nc3 Nxf3 21. exf3 Qe6 {with equality.}) 18... b6 19. Nc3 Nxf3 20. exf3 Qf5 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Ne4 Qd5 23. Qd3 {White's control of the light squares make his position easier to play, although Black has played all the best moves up to this point. Of course, the pawn structure means that even if things go well for White the road to victory won't be short, but we do have an enjoyable position.} *

