1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... c5 {This is also an interesting option for Black.} 5. d4 {This is my suggestion as I don't believe KIA plans like d3, Nbd2, e4, are of any danger for Black.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nb3 $5 ({A challenging option.} 7. c4 O-O 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 4.O-O O-O 5.c4 c5 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 d5 8.cxd5 Nxd5 , and is another possible try.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nc3 e6 9. e4 d4 (9... O-O {transposes here [/variation/31955664/#/9/b].}) 10. e5 $1 {Here Black was already inaccurate.} dxc3 11. exf6 (11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bg5 h6 $1 14. exf6 hxg5 15. Rad1+ Kc7 16. fxg7 Rg8 17. bxc3 Rxg7 {was around equal in Matlakov - Vidit, Budva 2019.}) 11... Bxf6 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Qf3 Bg7 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Rfd1 $146 (15. Rab1 {was played in Carlsen - Erigaisi, chess24.com 2022; but after} e5 $1 {I think Black is totally fine.}) 15... Qf6 16. Qxf6 Bxf6 17. Rab1 Bxc3 18. Nc5 {And Black has problems.} *

