1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... e5 {Black takes the center for himself - the downside of the King's Indian.} (4... Nf6 5. c4 {transposes.}) 5. d3 (5. c4 {is another line, but after} dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 {6...c6 7.Qxc4 Ne7 is also playable.} 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe4 f6 11. f4 Bf5 12. Qc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4 Bf5 {White's best is to repeat a draw, as} 14. Qe3 Bh3 15. Rf3 Ne7 $1 16. fxe5 Nf5 {could be dangerous for him.  7.Qxc4 Nge7 is good for Black.}) 5... Ne7 {I initially thought this move order was unprecise, but after analyzing it, it has its advantages as well.} 6. c4 {The alternative 6. e4 is analyzed in detail in the next variation.} c6 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 {This seems to be a worse endgame for Black: the d4-square is available but the c6-pawn prevents Black's knight from using it.} Bg4 (9... c5 10. Nc3 Nbc6 11. Nd5 $14 {The white knight arrives on d5 early enough.}) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nd7 12. Be3 $14 {White has the bishop pair and a safe position: Amin - Erdos, Warsaw 2021.} *

