1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... e5 {Black takes the center for himself - the downside of the King's Indian.} (4... Nf6 5. c4 {transposes.}) 5. d3 (5. c4 {is another line, but after} dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 {6...c6 7.Qxc4 Ne7 is also playable.} 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe4 f6 11. f4 Bf5 12. Qc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4 Bf5 {White's best is to repeat a draw, as} 14. Qe3 Bh3 15. Rf3 Ne7 $1 16. fxe5 Nf5 {could be dangerous for him.  7.Qxc4 Nge7 is good for Black.}) 5... Ne7 {I initially thought this move order was unprecise, but after analyzing it, it has its advantages as well.} 6. e4 O-O $1 ({•} 6... c6 7. Re1 {creates problems with the e5-pawn. Trading pawns on e4 would lead to a worse endgame due to the misplaced knight on e7 which has nowhere to go.} d4 8. a4 O-O 9. Na3 {Now we just play like a reversed King's Indian. We are really in what we call the King's Indian Attack!} c5 10. Nc4 Nbc6 11. Rf1 h6 12. Nh4 Be6 13. b3 Qd7 14. f4 {White was doing excellent in Vidit - Sokolovsky, chess.com 2022.}) ({•} 6... dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nbc6 9. Nc3 {tranposes into 5...Nc6 6.Nc3 Nge7 7.e4 dxe4 8.dxe4 Qxd1 9.Rxd1 .}) 7. Nc3 (7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nc3 {doesn't lead anywhere for example after} Ne7 $5 9. Re1 Nbc6 10. Rb1 a5 $132 {Hansen - Izoria, chess.com 2021.}) 7... c6 $1 8. Re1 d4 9. Nb1 c5 {And I must say I do not like this version of the reversed King's Indian as contrarily to Vidit's game after 6... c6, we've lost two tempi with our knight. Of course, the position remains playable, but Black should be at least fine. Ianov - Mirzoev, Lutsk 2018.} *

