1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... e5 {Black takes the center for himself - the downside of the King's Indian.} (4... Nf6 5. c4 {transposes.}) 5. d3 (5. c4 {is another line, but after} dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 {6...c6 7.Qxc4 Ne7 is also playable.} 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe4 f6 11. f4 Bf5 12. Qc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4 Bf5 {White's best is to repeat a draw, as} 14. Qe3 Bh3 15. Rf3 Ne7 $1 16. fxe5 Nf5 {could be dangerous for him.  7.Qxc4 Nge7 is good for Black.}) 5... Ne7 {I initially thought this move order was unprecise, but after analyzing it, it has its advantages as well.} 6. c4 {The alternative 6. e4 is analyzed in detail in the next variation.} c6 7. e4 O-O (7... d4 {would be a favorable reversed King's Indian: our pawn on c4 limits Black's expansion on the queenside, our rook is on f1 and not e1 (helpful when your goal is to play f4) and we lost no tempo/tempi with our b1-knight.}) 8. b4 {White starts to expand on the queenside.} d4 (8... Nd7 9. Nbd2 b6 10. a4 Bb7 11. a5 $14 {Grischuk - Riazantsev, Almaty 2022.}) 9. a4 c5 {This position occurred in Oparin - Aronian, chess.com 2022.} 10. b5 {And here, in the aforementioned game, White should have played b5, in order to get a similar game as Amin Bassem (see 8... h6, here [/variation/31955672]).} *

