1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 (3... c5 4. O-O {is covered under 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 g6 4.O-O}) 4. O-O (4. d4 {would transpose into very classical positions - which might be recommendable if you aren't satisfied with the lines that follow. Indeed, Black equalizes, but he should be smart and play precise moves.}) 4... e5 {Black takes the center for himself - the downside of the King's Indian.} (4... Nf6 5. c4 {transposes.}) 5. d3 (5. c4 {is another line, but after} dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nc6 {6...c6 7.Qxc4 Ne7 is also playable.} 7. Nxe5 Bxe5 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qe4 f6 11. f4 Bf5 12. Qc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4 Bf5 {White's best is to repeat a draw, as} 14. Qe3 Bh3 15. Rf3 Ne7 $1 16. fxe5 Nf5 {could be dangerous for him.  7.Qxc4 Nge7 is good for Black.}) 5... Nc6 {Black can decide to start with this move, which keeps the kingside flexible (the g8-knight won't necessarily go to e7) or with 5... Ne7 keeping the queenside flexible (the b8-knight won't necessarily go to c6).} 6. Nc3 ({After failing to find anything with both} 6. e4 {and}) (6. Nbd2 {, I've tried a few more things, and concluded this was the best try, However, with perfect play, Black is able to equalize. But this is chess! Trust me, if you know more than your opponent he'll be under psychological pressure and will most of the time fail to find the best moves!}) (6. Nbd2 Nge7 7. e4 {first looked to me like what I should propose as it's a KIA LTR, but after the main line} O-O 8. c3 a5 9. a4 h6 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nc4 Re8 12. Re1 Bf5 $1 {I could not find a single decent idea for White.}) (6. e4 dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bg4 {is a position I got once against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave as Black. I went to e7 with my knight, which made no sense at all, and slowly lost the game. Instead, after} 9. c3 Nf6 {or even 9... f6!? followed by ... Nh6.} 10. Nbd2 O-O {again I could not find any serious try for White.}) 6... Nge7 7. e4 O-O 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Re1 Qd8 (10... Qd6 11. Nd2 Re8 12. Ne4 Qd8 13. c3 $14 {With Nc5 pending all the time, White's position is very pleasant, although he lost in Rapport - Amin, Warsaw 2021.}) 11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 $146 {Followed by c3 and d4 or Nd2, with a pleasant position for White.} *

