1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Black can go ...Bg4 straight away or start with the solid ...c6, as we'll examine later. First, let's see what happens if Black tries to take advantage of delaying ...c6.} 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {doesn't bring White much success.}) 3... c6 {Black solidifies the center and the h1-a8 diagonal before continuing his development. Here I'll suggest two more orders, leading to very similar positions.} 4. c4 (4. O-O Nd7 {This is somehow similar to our main line.} 5. h3 Bh5 {5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 will shortly transpose into 4... Bxf3 as a deviation to our main line.} 6. c4 e6 7. cxd5 {and we have transposed into 4. c4 below, except that h3 and ...Bh5 has been included, which can't be bad for White.}) (4. O-O Nf6 {would transpose into 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 c5 4.O-O Bg4}) 4... e6 {Black kept his knight on b8 so in the event of cxd5 he can take back with the c-pawn and develop his knight to c6.} 5. O-O Nd7 (5... Nf6 {transposes into lines [/course/200248/13] starting with 2... Nf6.}) 6. cxd5 {We take on d5 now that Black played ...Nd7.} cxd5 (6... exd5 7. h3 Bh5 8. Nc3 Ngf6 {and we have transposed into the mainline.}) 7. Nc3 Ngf6 8. d3 Be7 9. Be3 $5 O-O 10. Qb3 Bc5 11. Bf4 $14 {The b7-pawn is hanging, and after Rac1 White will have a more pleasant position thanks to the misplaced knight on d7. White won in the game Malakhov - Kobalia, Russia 2015.} *

