1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Black can go ...Bg4 straight away or start with the solid ...c6, as we'll examine later. First, let's see what happens if Black tries to take advantage of delaying ...c6.} 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {doesn't bring White much success.}) 3... Nd7 (3... e6 4. h3 Bh5 {4... Bxf3 will be very similar to 4... Bxf3 in our main line.} 5. c4 c6 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes into lines [/course/200248/13] starting 2... Nf6.}) (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 Bg4 .}) 4. h3 {Of course delaying this move, that gives Black between a clear choice of keeping the bishop pair or not, is possible as well. But my choice was to play this little move right away.} Bxf3 5. Bxf3 c6 6. d3 {This gives White a nice game with the bishop pair.} Ngf6 7. O-O e5 {Without a light-squared bishop, it is more logical for Black to play solid with ...e6.} 8. e4 dxe4 9. dxe4 Bc5 10. Nd2 O-O 11. Qe2 Qe7 12. a4 a5 13. Nc4 $14 {White enjoys a nice position. He has the bishop pair, a solid queenside, an equal center and is going to act on the kingside, most likely by playing Kh2, Bg2, and pushing his pawns.} *

