1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Black can go ...Bg4 straight away or start with the solid ...c6, as we'll examine later. First, let's see what happens if Black tries to take advantage of delaying ...c6.} 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {doesn't bring White much success.}) 3... Nd7 (3... e6 4. h3 Bh5 {4... Bxf3 will be very similar to 4... Bxf3 in our main line.} 5. c4 c6 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes into lines [/course/200248/13] starting 2... Nf6.}) (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 Bg4 .}) 4. h3 {Of course delaying this move, that gives Black between a clear choice of keeping the bishop pair or not, is possible as well. But my choice was to play this little move right away.} Bxf3 5. Bxf3 c6 6. d3 {This gives White a nice game with the bishop pair.} e6 7. O-O Ngf6 (7... Bd6 8. Bg2 Ngf6 {transposes to 7... Ngf6 followed by 8... Bd6.}) 8. e4 Ne5 9. Bg2 dxe4 10. dxe4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 {This is an excellent endgame for White.} Bc5 (11... Rg8 12. f4 Bc5+ 13. Kf1 Ned7 14. Nd2 Nh5 15. Bf3 $1 {$16 A nice trick, with the idea to trap the knight on g3! This was seen in the game Svane - Petrov, Almaty 2022.}) 12. Nc3 Rg8 13. Na4 Be7 14. f4 $14 {White enjoys the bishop pair, a space advantage, and after e5, c4, Be3, Black will start to suffocate. Howell - Gajewski, Warsaw 2021.} *

