1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Black can go ...Bg4 straight away or start with the solid ...c6, as we'll examine later. First, let's see what happens if Black tries to take advantage of delaying ...c6.} 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {doesn't bring White much success.}) 3... Nd7 (3... e6 4. h3 Bh5 {4... Bxf3 will be very similar to 4... Bxf3 in our main line.} 5. c4 c6 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes into lines [/course/200248/13] starting 2... Nf6.}) (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 Bg4 .}) 4. h3 {Of course delaying this move, that gives Black between a clear choice of keeping the bishop pair or not, is possible as well. But my choice was to play this little move right away.} Bh5 5. c4 e6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nc3 c6 8. O-O (8. d4 $5 {is another approach, but I prefer my suggestion.}) 8... Ngf6 9. d3 {Against …Bg4 setups I like d3 plans more than d4. White plays for e2-e4 and is more likely to activate his g2-bishop. Having the white pawns on light squares also limits Black’s light-squared bishop.} Bd6 10. e4 O-O 11. exd5 $1 {This is very similar to 9... Be7 lines.} (11. g4 $6 Bg6 12. Nh4 Nxe4 $1 {was fine for Black in Oparin - Shirov, Moscow 2016.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Qb3 $1 {White's position is a delight.} Nb6 14. a4 (14. Be3 Re8 15. Rfe1 h6 16. a4 $16 {is very much similar: Meier - Xu, chess.com 2022.}) 14... a5 15. Be3 (15. Bd2 $5 {to prevent ...Bb4 also hurts.}) 15... Bb4 16. Nd4 $16 {White has a superb knight on d4 and a target on d5, while Black has a very badly placed knight on b6 and also a relatively useless bishop on h5. Martirosyan - Subelj, Batumi 2019.} *

