1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Black can go ...Bg4 straight away or start with the solid ...c6, as we'll examine later. First, let's see what happens if Black tries to take advantage of delaying ...c6.} 3. Bg2 (3. Ne5 Bf5 {doesn't bring White much success.}) 3... Nd7 (3... e6 4. h3 Bh5 {4... Bxf3 will be very similar to 4... Bxf3 in our main line.} 5. c4 c6 6. O-O Nf6 {transposes into lines [/course/200248/13] starting 2... Nf6.}) (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 Bg4 .}) 4. h3 {Of course delaying this move, that gives Black between a clear choice of keeping the bishop pair or not, is possible as well. But my choice was to play this little move right away.} Bh5 5. c4 e6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nc3 c6 8. O-O (8. d4 $5 {is another approach, but I prefer my suggestion.}) 8... Ngf6 9. d3 {Against …Bg4 setups I like d3 plans more than d4. White plays for e2-e4 and is more likely to activate his g2-bishop. Having the white pawns on light squares also limits Black’s light-squared bishop.} Bc5 10. Qb3 Bb6 (10... Qb6 11. Qc2 {threatens Na4, while} Qd8 {would now be met by} 12. b4 $1 Bxb4 13. Rb1 {and White is doing more than fine.}) 11. Na4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 O-O 13. e3 $146 {I like this slow move, not hurrying to take the other bishop.} (13. Nxb6 Nc5 $5 14. Qc2 axb6 15. b4 Na4 $146 {is quite solid for Black.}) 13... Re8 14. Nxb6 Qxb6 (14... Nc5 15. Qc2 axb6 16. Bg2 $14) 15. Qc2 $14 {White has an easy game with the bishop pair, although of course Black is very solid and it may take some time to gain the necessary space to convert.} *

