1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} Nbd7 7. cxd5 {The typical reaction when the knight leaves b8, and cannot develop to c6 at once.} cxd5 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Nc3 e6 {The position looks pretty symmetrical but it is definitely not as dry as it might look at first sight.} 10. Qxb6 Nxb6 11. d3 {Black has serious problems in this endgame.} Bd6 (11... Be7 12. Nd4 $146 O-O 13. f4 {followed by Be3, Rac1, g4...}) 12. Nb5 Bb8 13. Be3 {A rook is coming to c1 and Black’s position could collapse soon.} a6 14. Nc3 (14. Bxb6 axb5 15. Rfc1 {with the idea of Rc5 (apart from Rc8+) should be very good as well.}) 14... Nbd7 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nh4 Ke7 17. f4 $16 {Black is being suffocated. White has a lot more space and it looks like none of the black pieces has a future. Bacrot - Malyi, chess.com 2022.} *

