1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Be7 8. Nc3 {Now in the case of ...dxc4 we can play Ne5, unlike after 7... Nbd7.} O-O 9. Ne5 Nfd7 $6 10. Nd3 $1 ({Black wants to meet} 10. g4 {with} Nxe5 {and after} 11. dxe5 {there will be no knight hanging on f6.}) {This powerful move was only played twice. Not only the knight is heading to f4, in order to eliminate Black's bishop pair, but it also leaves the black knights on b8 and d7 limiting each other.} 10... dxc4 11. Nf4 Bg6 12. h4 $1 e5 {Black is lucky not to lose at once!} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Bh3 $1 {The h1-a8 being closed, the bishop switches to another diagonal!} Qxd1 15. Rxd1 h5 16. Be3 Na6 17. Bd4 $16 {Black has an extra-pawn, but White will get it back with benefits. It is already hard to find a decent move for Black here. Svane - Korobov, chess.com 2021.} *

