1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 cxd5 {This is a typical slight advantage for White as the b8-knight has gone to d7 and will need time if it wants to go back to its best square, c6.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Nc3 Be7 (10... Qxb3 11. axb3 a6 12. Nh4 $5 {$146 followed by g4, winning the bishop pair with a small advantage.}) 11. Ne5 $146 Qxd4 $2 (11... O-O {?} 12. g4 Bg6 13. g5 {wins material.}) 12. Qxb7 Rb8 13. Qc6 $1 Z0 ({This is problematic for Black due to} 13... Qxe5 $2 14. Bf4) *

