1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 $1 ({The most challenging move.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {was popular at some point but after} Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 {with the idea of ... Ne6, it turns out Black is too solid.}) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nc3 $1 ({Black already has a difficult decision to make.} 11. f4 $2 {would be strong if it wasn't met by} g5 $3 12. g4 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Bxg4 $1 14. hxg4 h5 {with huge problems for White.}) 11... Bc5 $6 12. Na4 $1 Be7 (12... Qe7 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Be3 {The dark-squared bishop is too important. Here White has a clear advantage.} Nd7 {14...O-O 15.Rc1 Nd7 16.g4 Bg6 17.f4 f5 18.g5 $16 Warmerdam - Slagboom, Maastricht 2022.} 15. f4 f6 16. Qb3 $16 {Svane - Le Tuan Minh, lichess.org 2021.}) 13. f4 $1 {White threatens g4 and f5, winning a piece.} (13. g4 $2 Bg6 14. f4 h5 $1 15. f5 $6 Bh7 {is problematic for White.}) 13... h6 14. Be3 Bg6 {And here I would improve on the game Svane - Daggupati, chess.com 2022, with Rc1.} 15. Rc1 {Just to paralyze the queenside. Next could be Qb3 or simply Bf2.} *

