1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 $1 ({The most challenging move.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {was popular at some point but after} Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 {with the idea of ... Ne6, it turns out Black is too solid.}) 9... Ne4 10. Bxe4 (10. Nd2 {was Grischuk's try, but after the simple} Nxd2 {(instead of 10... f5)} 11. Bxd2 Be7 {I am not sure why White should be better.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nc3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 (12... Bg6 13. Be3 Qc8 14. Kh2 Be7 15. Qd4 O-O 16. Nxe4 Rd8 17. Nd6 Qe6 18. Rfd1 f6 {occurred in Donchenko - Prilleltensky, Pardubice 2022, and here after} 19. Qg4 $1 {$146 Qxg4 20.hxg4 Black would have been under serious pressure.}) 13. Rxd1 Bg6 14. Be3 Be7 15. Rac1 {This was unpleasant for Black in Svane - Lashkin, chess.com 2022.} *

