1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {transposes to the mainline, while 3...Bg4 transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Bg4 3.Bg2 c6 .}) (2... e6 3. Bg2 Nf6 {is a transposition to systems with ...e6. Side third moves will, at best, transpose into another chapter.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. h3 {Asking Black to make a decision right away.} Bh5 (5... Bxf3 6. Bxf3 {doesn't make much difference (if any) with 2... Bg4 followed by 3... Nd7 and 4... Bxf3. White has an easier game.}) 6. c4 {We play similarly as against 2... Bg4 (and 3... Nd7), but with the pawn on c6 and knight on b8, Black wants to take back on d5 with the c-pawn if we give him that chance.} e6 7. d4 {Black could also play with the pawn on d3, but I believe this is the most challenging setup.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Ne5 $1 ({The most challenging move.} 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nh4 {was popular at some point but after} Bg6 12. Nc3 Nf8 $1 {with the idea of ... Ne6, it turns out Black is too solid.}) 9... Ne4 10. Bxe4 (10. Nd2 {was Grischuk's try, but after the simple} Nxd2 {(instead of 10... f5)} 11. Bxd2 Be7 {I am not sure why White should be better.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nc3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bb4 13. Nxe4 Qxd1 (13... O-O {? occurred in another game of Svane (perhaps the 100th in this course?), Svane - Rasulov, chess.com 2023, and here after} 14. g4 $1 Bg6 15. Ng3 {White would have had a huge advantage.}) 14. Rxd1 Bxe2 15. Rd4 Be7 $1 (15... a5 $2 16. Bd2 Be7 17. Re1 {was much better for White in Svane - Krysa, chess.com 2023.}) 16. Bg5 Bf3 $1 17. Bxe7 $146 (17. Nd6+ Bxd6 18. exd6 $6 {occurred in Grandelius - Akobian, chess.com 2022, but after} Kd7 $1 19. Re1 Rhe8 20. Re7+ Rxe7 {followed by ...Bd5 it is Black who would have pushed for a win!}) 17... Kxe7 (17... Bxe4 $6 18. Bf6 $1 gxf6 19. Rxe4 {is nasty for Black.}) 18. Nd6 Rhd8 19. g4 {And White wants Kh2, Kg3, f4, and can apply some pressure even if Black's position is extremely solid with the bishop on d5.} *

