1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... Bf5 3. Bg2 {will transpose.}) 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bf5 (4... h6 {This prepares ...Bf5, making sure the bishop can hide on h7 if necessary.} 5. c4 Bf5 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. d3 {We are going to transpose into similar positions as the main line, where ...h6 has cost a tempo and hasn't been particularly useful.}) 5. c4 e6 6. Qb3 Qb6 7. d3 {Playing with d3 makes perfect sense against ...Bf5 setups, so the black bishop is limited.} Nbd7 8. cxd5 {As usual, we wait for ...Nbd7 before taking on d5.} exd5 9. Qc2 {Here we keep queens!} Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bg6 (12... Bg4 $6 {is even worse:} 13. Be3 Qa6 14. Nd4 $16 {Svane - Pultinevicius, chess.com 2022.}) 13. Nh4 ({White wins the bishop pair and gets a good advantage.} 13. Be3 {followed by Nh4 is possible as well.}) 13... Rad8 14. h3 Rfe8 15. Kh2 Bb4 (15... Nh5 16. Be3 Qa5 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. a3 $16 {Svane - Yanchenko, chess.com 2023.}) 16. Be3 Qa5 17. f3 $146 {White will take his time to take the bishop on g6, perhaps playing a3 or Ne2 next, while now ...Qh5 would make no sese after a move like Rfd1.} (17. Nxg6 $6 {somehow gave Black fine counterplay after} hxg6 18. f3 Qh5 19. Rad1 Ne5 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 {and the game ended quickly after} 21. Ne2 $4 Neg4+ 22. fxg4 Nxg4+ 23. Kh1 Nxe3 24. Qd1 Rxd1 {Svane - Koustav, chess.com 2023.}) *

