1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Nbd7 {This is not a line to worry about.} 5. d4 e6 6. Nbd2 Be7 $1 7. c4 (7. Re1 O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 b6 {would no longer be convincing for White: Black is in time to play ...Bb7 and ...c5.}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 {We got an advantageous Catalan as Black has played …Nbd7 too early, and we will be able to push e2-e4 in wonderful conditions.} b6 9. e4 dxc4 {The critical move.} 10. Nxc4 Bb7 11. Rd1 $5 {I believe this is the best try for White.} c5 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nd6 $5 ({I've tried to make the same idea work with} 13. Qe4 {first, but after} b5 $5 {Black seems to be fine. • 13...cxd4 14.Qg4 Kh8 15.Nxd4 Rc8 16.b3 a6 17.a4 would typically be annoying for Black: he cannot move much and White will play Bb2, Rac1, and slowly increase the pressure. • 13...Nc3? falls into a nice trap: 14.Qxb7 Nxd1 15.d5! and after 15...Rb8 16.Qxa7 exd5 it is very important that White has 17.Bf4! with a clear advantage, as 17...dxc4? loses straight away to 18.Rxd1+-} 14. Nd6 Bxd6 15. Ng5 g6 16. exd6 N7f6 17. Qh4 Qxd6 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Nf3 Rfc8 {White has enough compensation, but probably nothing more.}) 13... Bxd6 14. Ng5 g6 15. exd6 {In the database, White scored 4/4 in this position! A serious threat is Qe2 with the idea of Nxe6, and then it will be difficult to get rid of the pressure White is applying.} cxd4 {The only move according to the engine!} 16. Rxd4 N7f6 $1 17. b4 (17. Bf4 Nxf4 18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Rxf4 Rxb7 20. Qc6 Qd7 21. Qxd7 Nxd7 22. Rc1 Nc5 {Unfortunately we get no time for b4 due to ...Nd3.} 23. Rd4 a5 $1 {and Black should hold that.}) 17... Qxd6 18. Bb2 {And here White has very, very serious compensation on the dark squares. Moves like Qd2/Rh4 are likely to follow!} *

