{This is stronger, getting rid of the black knight without weakening the white king. If Black plays …f5, his bishop on g7 will remain passive forever, while after …Nh6 we would just trade on f6, followed by Re1, Bf4, Rc1 with a good position.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O c5 5. d3 ({•} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Nc3 Be7 {and now} 9. f4 {or 9.Bg5 are playable lines for White, but I decided to stick to the same plan throughout this chapter.}) ({•} 5. c4 d4 {is not what we want.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. c3 O-O 9. e5 Ng4 {A weird continuation.} 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qb6 12. Nb3 f6 13. Bh3 $1 ({This position occured in Dardha - Lagarde, Cap d'Agde 2022, when after} 13. h3 Nxf2 {followed by} 14. Z0 fxe5 {Black got interesting compensation.}) *

