1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O c5 5. d3 ({•} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Nc3 Be7 {and now} 9. f4 {or 9.Bg5 are playable lines for White, but I decided to stick to the same plan throughout this chapter.}) ({•} 5. c4 d4 {is not what we want.}) 5... Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 (6... Be7 7. e4 {will transpose to the main line.}) 7. e4 O-O 8. Re1 Qc7 ({Black tries to stop e4-e5.} 8... Bc7 9. c3 $1 {is annoying for Black: White wants e5 and d4, while an exchange on e4 would lead to a better pawn structure for White.}) 9. Qe2 $1 {Threatening e5 again.} Nd7 10. c3 {We want d4 next and the opening of the h1-a8 diagonal (if ...dxe4 Nxe4) could turn nasty for Black.} (10. Nh4 $5 {with the idea of pushing f4 makes sense too.}) 10... d4 11. Nc4 e5 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 13. Nh4 {We got the bishop pair and can bring a typical (reversed) King's Indian attack, aiming for the f5-square or to push f2-f4 as soon as possible.} *

