1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Bd6 $6 {Only here we're changing our plan.} 5. c4 (5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 {would now allow} e5 {which I believe is fine for Black.}) 5... O-O 6. d4 $1 {We're transposing into a good variation of the Catalan for White.} h6 7. Qc2 (7. Nc3 {with the idea to meet ...b6 with Nd2 and e4 is good as well. Here Black almost always goes} Nc6 {and after} 8. b3 {White simply has a good position, e.g.} dxc4 9. bxc4 e5 10. e3 {The cute 10.Nxe5!? Nxe5 11.c5! Bxc5 12.dxc5 Qe7 13.Be3 definitely deserves attention as well.} exd4 11. exd4 $14 {and White won in the game Duda - Kovalev, chess.com 2023.}) 7... b6 8. cxd5 (8. b3 {is possible as well, e.g.} Bb7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nc3 Rc8 {10...a6 11.Nd2! c5 12.cxd5 exd5 13.e4! with concrete problems for Black.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 {winning the bishop pair.}) 8... exd5 9. Nc3 Bb7 (9... a6 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11. Nh4 {creates concrete problems.}) 10. Nb5 {We're winning the bishop pair, which is White's dream in that type of position.} Z0 ({For example, after} 10... Re8 11. Be3 $5 {White will follow up with Rac1, provoke ...c6 and take the bishop pair. After that, he'll play Bf4, Ne5, with a stable advantage. Note that taking on d6 earlier, provoking ...cxd6, is also a bit better for White, but Black remains solid and I like the idea of weakening the dark squares more by forcing him to take back on d6.}) *

