1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Nbd7 5. d3 ({Again, here} 5. d4 {followed by c4 is a good version of the Catalan, as for example after} Be7 6. c4 O-O 7. Qc2 {Black likes that the White bishop is on d2 here (having included ...Bb4+ Bd2 before ...Be7) so that White cannot just go b3-Bb2 and/or Nc3/Nbd2/e4 too easily. I invite you to look into it, even if I'll just suggest something that goes along with our usual plans.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Now if Black wants to avoid a bad version of the main line (with the knight on d7 instead of having played ...c5 and ...Nc6) he should take on e4.} dxe4 8. dxe4 e5 9. b3 {White has been crushing in practice, but Black always missed the only way not to be much worse: ...b6!} c6 $2 10. Bb2 Qc7 11. Nc4 Nxe4 12. Nfxe5 {This is already bad for Black.} *

