1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 Nc6 $5 {A very decent move, I must admit!} 7. d4 $1 {We need to change our tune and go for that one. The alternative 7. e4 is discussed in the next variation. [/variation/32244407/#/7/w]} Ne4 8. c3 f5 9. Ne1 e5 10. dxe5 $146 (10. Ndf3 {is the alternative, as played three times by Rapport.}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nd3 Bf6 (11... Nxd3 $6 12. exd3 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 {favors White as ...f5 is very weakening.}) 12. Qb3 Kh8 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Rd1 Z0 ({And here we are able to press, for example} 14... Nxd2 15. Bxd2 {15.Rxd2 f4! 16.Rxd5 Qf6 is dangerous for White.} c6 16. c4 dxc4 17. Qxc4 {and after} Qd4 18. Qxd4 Bxd4 19. Bb4 Rd8 20. Bc5 Bf6 21. Rxd8+ Bxd8 22. Rd1 Bf6 23. Bd4 Be7 {White play} 24. Rd3 $1 {when Re3 or Rb3 (in order to paralyze the c8-bishop) will follow, with problems for Black.}) *

