1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} Qc7 {This might look useless, but it will free the f8-rook later on.} ({Black can play} 8... dxe4 {and after} 9. dxe4 {the game will transpose to the previous position [/variation/32014182/#/8/w].}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Qe2 b5 {The most sensible move. White has extra ideas against the c7-queen once the bishop is on f4.} 11. Nf1 a5 12. h4 Ba6 13. Bf4 $1 b4 14. Ne3 {Here we have extra ideas like Nxd5.} Nb6 15. Ng4 {And now Nf6+ could be annoying too. White will push h5 and is likely to sac on h6 if Black pushes his h-pawn.} *

