1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} Qc7 {This might look useless, but it will free the f8-rook later on.} ({Black can play} 8... dxe4 {and after} 9. dxe4 {the game will transpose to the previous position [/variation/32014182/#/8/w].}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Qe2 b5 {The most sensible move. White has extra ideas against the c7-queen once the bishop is on f4.} 11. Nf1 a5 12. h4 Ba6 13. Bf4 $1 Rfc8 14. Ne3 Qd8 {This might be the best plan for Black, with the idea to answer h5 with ...h6 and consolidate with ...Bf8.} 15. c3 {A novelty. We want to be able to meet ...b4 with c4.} (15. h5 h6 16. Ng4 Bf8 17. c3 {was played in Bachmann - Mekhitarian, Florianopolis 2022, 0-1, but as I believe White has other options than h5 and Ng4, I like to keep a status quo on the kingside for a short time.}) 15... h6 {This is bad.} 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. e6 fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 (18... Kf8 $4 19. Ng5 $1 hxg5 20. Bxd5 {and Black cannot avoid mate.}) 19. Ng5 {And the h-pawn being on h6 instead of h7 changes everything.} Bxg5 (19... hxg5 $2 20. hxg5 Nf8 21. Qh3+ Kg8 22. Qf5 {is crushing, Black's only way to prevent Bxd5+ is} Nb4 23. cxb4 Bb7 {but after} 24. Bh3 Rc6 25. Qe5 $1 {White wins his piece back, as} Ng6 $6 {loses to} 26. Be6+ Kh8 27. Qf5) 20. hxg5 Nf8 21. Qg4 {And while Black would be completely safe had the h6-pawn been on h7, here he has serious problems to solve.} *

