1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} Qc7 {This might look useless, but it will free the f8-rook later on.} ({Black can play} 8... dxe4 {and after} 9. dxe4 {the game will transpose to the previous position [/variation/32014182/#/8/w].}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Qe2 b5 {The most sensible move. White has extra ideas against the c7-queen once the bishop is on f4.} 11. Nf1 a5 12. h4 Ba6 13. Bf4 $1 Rfc8 14. Ne3 Qd8 {This might be the best plan for Black, with the idea to answer h5 with ...h6 and consolidate with ...Bf8.} 15. c3 a4 16. Ng5 {The best plan in my opinion.} Nf8 (16... h6 $2 {allows} 17. Nxe6 $3 fxe6 18. Qg4 {with compensation.}) 17. Rac1 (17. Qh5 Qe8 18. Nf3 {is also possible.}) 17... Bb7 (17... d4 18. cxd4 Nxd4 19. Qh5 {would be highly unpleasant for Black.}) 18. a3 {And while the position is probably objectively unclear, it is hard to find what are Black's next moves, while White will play Qg4, answer ...h6 with Nf3, and Black remains under pressure. Another plan is to go Ng4, h5, as after ...h6 Nh3/f3 Black won't be in time for ...Bf8. Note that d3-d4 remains an option at any time, although for now we give priority to the kingside attack.} *

