1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} b5 {The most sensible move for Black: starting a counter-attack on the queenside.} 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 a5 {Again, keeping the queenside expansion is the most sensible way to play.} 11. h4 b4 12. N1h2 a4 13. Ng4 Ba6 ({Here only two moves have been played according to the database:} 13... Ba6 {and}) (13... a3 {.}) 14. h5 h6 {Black cannot afford to allow h6 as he would get smashed on the dark squares.} (14... Nd4 $2 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. h6 g6 17. a3 {is just bad for Black.}) 15. a3 $1 (15. Bxh6 $2 gxh6 16. Qd2 {now fails as after} Nd4 {the Black bishop will be coming to g5.}) 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 $1 (16. bxa3 Rb8 17. Nxh6+ gxh6 18. Bxh6 Re8 19. c4 {was tried in Jakubowski - Shuvalov, chess.com 2021, but it seems that after} dxc4 {White does not have enough, though the engine proposes the very cute} 20. Nd4 $1 {here, with the idea of Qg4, but unfortunately it only enables White to stay in the game as after} Ncxe5 21. Nc6 Qc7 22. f4 Kh7 {Black is at least fine.}) 16... Bb7 17. Ra1 $146 ({Black is under heavy pressure, always having to watch out for sacs on h6, while} 17. Bxh6 $4 gxh6 18. Qd2 {was played in Nepomniachtchi, - Le, Dubai 2014, but here after} Nd4 $1 {White would just be lost due to the black bishop coming to g5.}) 17... Nd4 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. Nxh6+ gxh6 20. Bxh6 Kh8 21. Bxf8 Qxf8 22. f4 {This is just a good position for White.} *

