1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 (2... e6 {will transpose as the black knight will develop on f6 anyhow.}) 3. Bg2 e6 {Against this setup we'll go for a typical KIA setup.} 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 {Here White's plan is to push e5, then go Nf1, h4, h5, N1h2, Ng4, with possible sacs on h6. Doing an exhaustive analysis of this position is basically impossible as Black has plenty of options, but White's ideas remain the same. So, let's see how the game can go.} b5 {The most sensible move for Black: starting a counter-attack on the queenside.} 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 a5 {Again, keeping the queenside expansion is the most sensible way to play.} 11. h4 b4 12. N1h2 a4 13. Ng4 a3 ({Here only two moves have been played according to the database:} 13... Ba6 {and}) (13... a3 {.}) (13... h5 $2 {$146 is always too weakening:} 14. Ngh2 Qc7 15. Bf4 {and the h5-pawn will become a target.}) 14. bxa3 bxa3 15. h5 h6 {Again Black can't afford to allow White to push h6.} 16. c3 $5 {We want to control the d4-square and also stop any possible central break, as again ...c4 allows d4 and ...d4 allows c4. Black is again under heavy pressure.} (16. Bxh6 $4 gxh6 17. Qd2 {fails again to} Nd4 $1 {-+}) (16. Nxh6+ gxh6 17. Bxh6 Kh8 {is at least fine for Black.}) 16... Re8 $5 17. Bxh6 {Before Black plays ...Bf8.} gxh6 18. Qd2 Bf8 19. Nxh6+ Bxh6 20. Qxh6 Nf8 $1 (20... f6 $6 21. Qg6+ Kh8 22. exf6 Nxf6 23. Ng5 Ra7 24. Rab1 $1 Rg7 25. Nf7+ Rxf7 26. Qxf7 {would be very unpleasant for Black.}) 21. c4 Nd4 22. Nxd4 cxd4 23. Rab1 Z0 ({Next is Rb5 with a total mess, e.g.} 23... Ra7 $5 24. Rb5 Nh7 25. cxd5 exd5 26. Bxd5 Kh8 27. Re4 Qg5 28. Qb6 Rae7 29. Qxd4 Be6 {and the position is unclear, in fact totally equal according to the engine. Anyhow, congratulations if Black managed to survive the attack in an OTB game!}) *

