1. Nf3 c5 {A frequent move against 1. c4, but less so against 1. Nf3. The reason is simple: only Sicilian players can play it, as here White can play 2. e4 and transpose! Something I regularly do myself. I also like 2. c4 systems, but this is a KIA course so let's go for 2. g3!} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O (4. c4 {will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters (with ...Nf6 and ... c5) or one of the next ones.}) 4... d5 ({The same goes for} 4... Nc6 5. c4 {etc., this too will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters.}) 5. d4 (5. c4 {is the main alternative. Here} Nf6 {is a reasonable option (which can transpose to lines we've seen if White trades on d5 and plays d4), but I've got to say my main reason for giving preference to 5. d4 is that after 5...d4 6.e3 Nc6 7.exd4 cxd4 8.d3 Nf6 9.Re1 we have transposed into a Reserved Benoni, in one of rare lines (...g6 being the symmetrical version of g3 against the Classical Benoni) where the tempo doesn't seem very useful. Here for example after 9...O-O (9... Nd7 to prevent ...Ne5 is also possible.) 10.a3 10.Nbd2 Bf5 and already we need to go for something weird like 11.Nb3 where Black seems to be fine, e.g. 11...a5 12.Ne5 Nxe5 13.Rxe5 a4 14.Nc5 Qc7 15.Bf4 Nh5 (entering a pretty much forced tactical sequence) 16.Rxf5 Nxf4 17.Rxf4 Qxc5 18.Re4 Rfb8 with equality. 10...a5 11.Ne5 Nxe5 12.Rxe5 and this position exists with reversed colors, except that the c8-bishop should be on f5. And here, it's definitely good for White to have b7 safely protected, e.g. 12...Nd7 13.Rb5 Ra7 followed by ...b5, and Black is fine.}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Nxc6 $5 ({Just giving you an alternative, although you may again transpose to something we've seen before with} 7. Nb3 Nf6 8. Nc3 e6 9. e4 {, which as you already know transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 4.O-O c5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nf6 7.Nb3 Nc6 8.Nc3 e6 9.e4 .}) 7... bxc6 {Now White should break the center one way or another.} 8. e4 $5 (8. c4 {looks like the natural move but after the logical sequence} Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. cxd5 cxd5 {White doesn't have anything better than taking the pawn and} 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Rb8 {is a typically drawish position due to the pressure on b2.}) 8... e6 {8...d4? is just bad for Black after 9.e5 followed by Re1, Nd2, and already almost a decisive advantage.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best setup.} 9. c4 Ne7 10. Nc3 O-O {just somehow forces too many simplifications:} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Rb8 {with a very drawish position due to the pressure on b2.}) 9... Ne7 10. c3 O-O 11. Nb3 a5 12. Nc5 {With a small but pleasant plus for White with his strong c5-knight.} *

