1. Nf3 c5 {A frequent move against 1. c4, but less so against 1. Nf3. The reason is simple: only Sicilian players can play it, as here White can play 2. e4 and transpose! Something I regularly do myself. I also like 2. c4 systems, but this is a KIA course so let's go for 2. g3!} 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O (4. c4 {will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters (with ...Nf6 and ... c5) or one of the next ones.}) 4... d5 ({The same goes for} 4... Nc6 5. c4 {etc., this too will soon transpose into one of the previous chapters.}) 5. d4 (5. c4 {is the main alternative. Here} Nf6 {is a reasonable option (which can transpose to lines we've seen if White trades on d5 and plays d4), but I've got to say my main reason for giving preference to 5. d4 is that after 5...d4 6.e3 Nc6 7.exd4 cxd4 8.d3 Nf6 9.Re1 we have transposed into a Reserved Benoni, in one of rare lines (...g6 being the symmetrical version of g3 against the Classical Benoni) where the tempo doesn't seem very useful. Here for example after 9...O-O (9... Nd7 to prevent ...Ne5 is also possible.) 10.a3 10.Nbd2 Bf5 and already we need to go for something weird like 11.Nb3 where Black seems to be fine, e.g. 11...a5 12.Ne5 Nxe5 13.Rxe5 a4 14.Nc5 Qc7 15.Bf4 Nh5 (entering a pretty much forced tactical sequence) 16.Rxf5 Nxf4 17.Rxf4 Qxc5 18.Re4 Rfb8 with equality. 10...a5 11.Ne5 Nxe5 12.Rxe5 and this position exists with reversed colors, except that the c8-bishop should be on f5. And here, it's definitely good for White to have b7 safely protected, e.g. 12...Nd7 13.Rb5 Ra7 followed by ...b5, and Black is fine.}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 (6... Nf6 {gives you a choice between two transpositions. • 7.Nb3 O-O 8.Nc3 e6 9.e4 Transposes to 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 4.O-O c5 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 Nf6 7.Nb3 Nc6 8.Nc3 e6 9.e4 . • 7.c4 O-O 8.cxd5 Nxd5 transposes to 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 4.O-O O-O 5.c4 c5 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 d5 8.cxd5 Nxd5}) 7. Nb3 Ne7 8. c4 {Of course we can't afford to leave Black to dominate the center.} d4 (8... dxc4 $2 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Na5 {is just awful for Black.}) 9. e3 O-O 10. exd4 exd4 {The previous moves were pretty much forced, or at least very natural. Now we need to make the d4-pawn a weakness and not a strength.} 11. Re1 $5 {The rook can't be bad there! We keep the option of not playing Bf4 right away depending on Black's next move.} Nbc6 12. Bf4 Be6 {The most natural move.} 13. Na3 $5 ({Putting the knight on the edge may look weird, but we couldn't afford} 13. N1d2 {due to} g5 {. The knight isn't that bad yet, as it can sometimes jump to b5, while the other one is about to jump to c5.}) ({Now, after} 13. Na3 {, a sample line could be} d3 14. Qd2 Qb6 {Preventing Nc5.} 15. Qxd3 $5 Bxb2 16. Nb5 Bxa1 17. Rxa1 {With enormous compensation, e.g.} Rac8 18. Nd6 Rfd8 19. Nxc8 Rxd3 20. Nxb6 axb6 21. Bf1 $14 {and the black rook has to return while White enjoys the bishop pair.}) *

