1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 Nh6 {Another way to develop the knight, heading to f5.} 6. d4 $1 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Bxh6 Bxh6 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. O-O {More or less a forced sequence.} Bg7 11. Qe3 d6 12. Rfd1 {One could think that because we've given our dark-squared bishop, we can't pretend to any advantage, but here the initiative prevails. The threats of d5, Nd5, the hanging a7-pawn if Black goes ...Rb8, the pressure on b7, make Black's position no fun to play.} Bxc3 13. Qxc3 Qc7 14. Rac1 Z0 ({And White had a stable advantage. Here's an example of how the game may continue:} 14... Be6 15. h4 h5 16. b3 Rab8 17. a4 a5 18. Bd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 {and Black will soon act on the kingside. 1-0 (25) Melkumyan, H (2634)-Schekachikhin, M (2376) chess.com 2022.}) *

