1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O h5 {Quite an aggressive reaction, but one that is definitely worth considering.} 7. Rb1 Nh6 8. a3 Nf5 9. Ng5 $146 a5 ({An interesting way to make} 9... h4 {bad, due to} 10. g4 {and ...h3 is 'legal' but defended by the g5-knight. Now, due to the hanging knight on c6 if Black moves his b-pawn, he needs one more time to manage to push ...b5. • 9.b4 h4 as in Jones, G (2665)-Le, Q (2709) chess.com 2022, 0-1 (33), is no drama, but not something I like to allow. • 9.h3 This is the typical way to prevent ...h4, as g4 would be a nasty answer when Black can't continue with ...h3, but it gives Black time to castle. 9...O-O 10.d3 Rb8 followed by ...a6 and ...b5.}) {As Black isn't in time to castle and counter d3, Bd2, b4 in time, this becomes the most natural reaction. Note that playing d3-Bd2 before playing b4 is a luxury. Playing b4 straight away is possible but then White cannot develop as smoothly due to the hanging knight on c3 if he goes d2-d3.} 10. d3 O-O 11. Bd2 Rb8 {The most logical move: one day Black would like to push ...b5 in one way or another.} 12. f4 $5 {A crazy idea which I thought of, first believing it can't be serious. I now believe it's the best move! White switches to aggressive mode and is even ready to give his bishop pair if Black goes ...Bd4+ and ...Ne3 for a few tempi in return.} Bd4+ 13. Kh1 Ne3 14. Bxe3 Bxe3 15. Nd5 Bd4 16. e3 Bg7 17. Nc3 {We've lost the bishop pair, but given the pawn structure, observing many of our pawns on the dark-squares and controlling crucial dark squares, our dark-squared bishop is no longer so important. In this position where would we put it anyway, d2? It's gone and it's not such a bad thing!} Na7 ({Black is seeking for counterplay with ...b5.} 17... e6 18. g4 $1 {is hard to meet for Black.}) 18. a4 $5 {Just neutralizing the queenside: we want to attack on the kingside!} Nc6 19. Bh3 $5 {And White has a pleasant position due to ...h5 which is weakening the black king nastily.} Z0 ({If bishops gets traded, Black won't even enjoy the bishop pair advantage, while} 19... e6 20. g4 $1 {would again be likely to turn into a nightmare for Black.}) *

