1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Nf6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {This move transposes into similar positions as chapter 1 (lines with 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5), but Black had time to play ...d6 and ... Bd7 without having to sacrifice a pawn (...d6 Nxc6 bxc6 Bxc6). That means it is worth some attention.} 9. Nc2 $5 {It makes sense to keep as many pieces as possible due to our space advantage.} (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c5 d5 $1 {doesn't give White any advantage, e.g.} 11. e4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 O-O 14. Qc2 a5 {with equality.}) 9... Qc8 {Preparing ...Bh3.} 10. b3 $5 Bh3 11. Bb2 h5 $5 12. f3 $146 {An important move: the light squared bishops are gonna be traded and this move is very much needed to be ready to face ...h4 with g4. Besides, it also prepares e2-e4. White is just better.} (12. Bxh3 $2 Qxh3 13. f3 {fails to} h4 14. g4 Nxg4 $1 15. fxg4 Bxc3 $17 {Sviridov - Panarin, chess.com 2020.}) *

