1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Bf5 $5 {An interesting move, in order to play ...Qd7, ...Bh3 and trade light squared bishops.} 7. h3 $5 {The most logical answer, with the idea to prevent the black bishop from reaching h3. Again we are at a crossroad, where Black has different ways to continue.} (7. d3 Qd7 8. Rb1 Nf6 9. a3 Bh3 10. b4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O {did not convince me, nor 7.b3 Qd7 8.Bb2 Bh3 9.e3 h5! did.}) 7... Qd7 8. Kh2 {I do not think including ...Qd7 and Kh2 is a good thing for Black, as the f5-bishop has less flexibility.} Nf6 9. d3 h6 (9... O-O 10. e4 Be6 11. Be3 {and soon or late d3-d4 will be played.}) 10. e4 Be6 11. Ng1 $146 {Even stronger than Caruana's move 11.Be3 which gave Black time to push ...g5 and ... g4.} (11. Be3 g5 12. Ng1 g4 13. h4 O-O 14. Nge2 {was nevertheless good for White in Caruana - So, Stavanger 2018.}) 11... O-O 12. Be3 {With Qd2, f4 to follow, and a wonderful position for White.} *

