1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Bf5 $5 {An interesting move, in order to play ...Qd7, ...Bh3 and trade light squared bishops.} 7. h3 $5 {The most logical answer, with the idea to prevent the black bishop from reaching h3. Again we are at a crossroad, where Black has different ways to continue.} (7. d3 Qd7 8. Rb1 Nf6 9. a3 Bh3 10. b4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O {did not convince me, nor 7.b3 Qd7 8.Bb2 Bh3 9.e3 h5! did.}) 7... e5 {A weird Botvinnik system where ...Bf5 and h3 have been included.} 8. d3 Nge7 9. a3 O-O 10. Rb1 a5 (10... Qd7 $6 11. g4 Be6 12. Ng5 {and Black loses the bishop pair - something he really does not wish.}) 11. Nd2 $5 Be6 12. Nd5 Rb8 13. b3 b5 14. Bb2 Qd7 15. Kh2 f5 16. e3 {Soon or late f2-f4 will come, and White's position is easier to play.} *

