1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Bf5 $5 {An interesting move, in order to play ...Qd7, ...Bh3 and trade light squared bishops.} 7. h3 $5 {The most logical answer, with the idea to prevent the black bishop from reaching h3. Again we are at a crossroad, where Black has different ways to continue.} (7. d3 Qd7 8. Rb1 Nf6 9. a3 Bh3 10. b4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 O-O {did not convince me, nor 7.b3 Qd7 8.Bb2 Bh3 9.e3 h5! did.}) 7... Nf6 8. d3 $1 (8. d4 Ne4 $1 {isn't convincing for White.}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 $5 {An interesting idea, a little similar to ...Bf5: we want to play Qd2 and Bh6 and trade Black's best minor piece.} (9. a3 a6 10. Rb1 Rb8 11. b4 cxb4 12. axb4 b5 {occured in Carlsen - Salgado Lopez, St Petersburg 2018, but did not convince me although White won - a victory I would put on the count that the best player in the world was holding the white pieces, and not the opening outcome.}) 9... a6 (9... h6 {trying to imitate White's move h3 would be met with} 10. Qd2 Kh7 11. d4 {and now} Ne4 $6 {is much less convincing simply due to} 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. dxc5 {winning a pawn.}) 10. Qd2 Rb8 ({Black's best, in order to push ...b5.} 10... b5 $6 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 13. Nc3 Rab8 14. Rfc1 Rfc8 15. b3 {was just an extra pawn for White in Carlsen - Vachier Lagrave, Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2019.}) (10... Qd7 $6 11. g4 $1 Be6 12. Bh6 {and Black is somehow disorganized.}) 11. Bh6 b5 (11... Nd4 12. Nh4 $5 Bd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. e3 Nf5 15. Nf3 {was similar to the text in Vachier Lagrave - Baron, Gibraltar 2020.}) 12. b3 $146 Bd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. e3 {White is sitting on the pleasant side of the board. A likley follow up would be Qb2, Ne2 in case of ...b4, followed by a f3-knight move, f4, g4, etc.} *

