1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Rb8 $5 {A weird as it seems, I believe this is one of the best moves. Black doesn't indicate how he'll develop his minor pieces, while ...Rb8 is useful in almost every line. Of course, Black's main idea is ...a6 and ...b5. After investigation, a fast reaction on the queenside or in the center is White's best chance for an advantage.} 7. a3 $5 (7. e3 {was critical until Vidit showed the path to equality.} Nf6 8. d4 O-O 9. b3 Be6 $1 10. Bb2 {10.d5?! Nxd5 is a forced line that ends up with a better position for Black: 11.cxd5 Bxc3 12.dxe6 Bxa1 13.exf7+ Rxf7 14.Ng5 Rf5 15.Bd5+ Kh8 $15 0-1 Ding Liren - Vidit, Kolkata 2019.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {12.exd4 d5 13.c5 b6 $132} Nd5 13. Qd2 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qc7 {0-1 Svidler - Vidit, chess24.com 2020.}) 7... a6 8. b4 {Trying to win the race at the cost of a pawn! I believe this is critical for the assessment of 6...Rb8.} cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4 (9... b5 $6 10. cxb5 axb5 11. d4 Nf6 {occurred in Abasov - Prraneeth, Baku 2023, and after} 12. d5 $5 {$146 Nxb4 13.Rb1 Na6 14.Nd4! Bd7 15.Nc6 Bxc6 16.dxc6 b4 17.Qa4 O-O 18.Qxa6 bxc3 19.Rxb8 Qxb8 20.Qb7 Black is in serious trouble.}) 10. d4 Nc6 11. Bb2 $146 {An interesting novelty.} Bd7 $1 {A crucial move. The idea is to be able to meet d5 with ...Na5 without losing a piece to Qa4+. After all other normal moves (11...Nf6, 11...Nh6...), Black is worse due to 12. d5.} 12. Ne4 $5 {We stick to our plan of pushing d4-d5 as soon as possible. Preferably before Black has time to complete his development!} Na5 {A good move - but not easy to play when your kingside is still undeveloped.} (12... Nh6 $2 13. Qd2 O-O 14. d5 {is just bad for Black.}) 13. c5 $5 d5 14. Nc3 Nc4 15. Bc1 {Improving the position of the white bishop.} Bc6 16. Bf4 Rc8 17. Qb3 e6 18. e4 Ne7 19. exd5 exd5 20. Rfe1 O-O 21. Bh3 {Attacking again the black rook.} Ra8 22. Ra2 {Black might objectively be fine, but Rae2 is coming and White definitely has enough compensation.} *

