1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O {We arrive at a crossroads here. Black has many possible moves.} Rb8 $5 {A weird as it seems, I believe this is one of the best moves. Black doesn't indicate how he'll develop his minor pieces, while ...Rb8 is useful in almost every line. Of course, Black's main idea is ...a6 and ...b5. After investigation, a fast reaction on the queenside or in the center is White's best chance for an advantage.} 7. a3 $5 (7. e3 {was critical until Vidit showed the path to equality.} Nf6 8. d4 O-O 9. b3 Be6 $1 10. Bb2 {10.d5?! Nxd5 is a forced line that ends up with a better position for Black: 11.cxd5 Bxc3 12.dxe6 Bxa1 13.exf7+ Rxf7 14.Ng5 Rf5 15.Bd5+ Kh8 $15 0-1 Ding Liren - Vidit, Kolkata 2019.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {12.exd4 d5 13.c5 b6 $132} Nd5 13. Qd2 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qc7 {0-1 Svidler - Vidit, chess24.com 2020.}) 7... a6 8. b4 {Trying to win the race at the cost of a pawn! I believe this is critical for the assessment of 6...Rb8.} cxb4 9. axb4 Nxb4 (9... b5 $6 10. cxb5 axb5 11. d4 Nf6 {occurred in Abasov - Prraneeth, Baku 2023, and after} 12. d5 $5 {$146 Nxb4 13.Rb1 Na6 14.Nd4! Bd7 15.Nc6 Bxc6 16.dxc6 b4 17.Qa4 O-O 18.Qxa6 bxc3 19.Rxb8 Qxb8 20.Qb7 Black is in serious trouble.}) 10. d4 Nc6 11. Bb2 $146 {An interesting novelty.} Bd7 $1 {A crucial move. The idea is to be able to meet d5 with ...Na5 without losing a piece to Qa4+. After all other normal moves (11...Nf6, 11...Nh6...), Black is worse due to 12. d5.} 12. Ne4 $5 {We stick to our plan of pushing d4-d5 as soon as possible. Preferably before Black has time to complete his development!} Nf6 13. d5 Na5 {Here White has two ways to get pleasant compensation.} 14. c5 ({The simplest way to play for White. The alternative is} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nxf6+ exf6 16. Qd4 O-O 17. Nd2 f5 18. h4 {(aiming at h5-h6)} h5 $1 19. c5 dxc5 20. Qc3 $1 b6 21. Rfe1 {followed by e2-e4 is also highly interesting.}) 14... O-O (14... dxc5 $6 15. Nxc5 Bb5 16. Ne5 O-O {? would fall into} 17. Nxf7 $3 Rxf7 18. Ne6 Qb6 19. Bd4) 15. cxd6 Nc4 16. dxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bd4 $1 {With Re1 and e4 to follow.} *

