1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O e6 {6...e5 again transposes into a Botvnnik system (last chapter, 1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5).} 7. e3 $5 (7. a3 {was initially my choice, but after} Nge7 8. b4 O-O {8...cxb4? 9.axb4 Nxb4 10.Ba3 Nbc6 11.Ne4 is horrible for Black.} 9. Rb1 b6 {with the idea of ... Bb7 I was left rather disappointed.}) 7... Nge7 8. d4 O-O 9. Re1 b6 $1 ({The most dangerous move. The idea is simple: if Black plays a random move (e.g.} 9... Re8 {) now we can push} 10. d5 {as} Na5 {will be answered with Bf1. Besides that, when Black takes on d4, the rook becomes well placed on the e-file.}) {According to played games, this is bad, but the engine brought it back to life.} 10. d5 $5 {The best try I found.} Na5 11. Nd2 Rb8 12. e4 Z0 ({Should just be good for White, e.g.} 12... e5 13. a3 f5 14. b4 Nb7 15. Rb1 {Black is dominated on the queenside.} f4 16. gxf4 $1 exf4 {16...Rxf4 17.Nf3 Rf8 18.Ng5 is problematic as well.} 17. Nb5 Ra8 18. Bb2 {with a large advantage for White.}) *

