1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O e6 (6... e5 {again transposes into a Botvnnik system (last chapter, 1...c5 with 2... Nc6 and 3...e5).}) 7. e3 $5 (7. a3 {was initially my choice, but after} Nge7 8. b4 O-O {8...cxb4? 9.axb4 Nxb4 10.Ba3 Nbc6 11.Ne4 is horrible for Black.} 9. Rb1 b6 {with the idea of ... Bb7 I was left rather disappointed.}) 7... Nge7 8. d4 O-O 9. Re1 b6 $1 ({The most dangerous move. The idea is simple: if Black plays a random move (e.g.} 9... Re8 {) now we can push} 10. d5 {as} Na5 {will be answered with Bf1. Besides that, when Black takes on d4, the rook becomes well placed on the e-file.}) {According to played games, this is bad, but the engine brought it back to life.} 10. b3 e5 $1 {The (almost) novelty that kills all the fun.} (10... Bb7 11. Bb2 Nf5 12. Ne2 {was very pleasant for White in Abdusattorov,N (2731)-Vidit,S (2731) Berlin 2023, 1-0 (76), who will play Qd2 or e4 next.}) 11. Bb2 ({•} 11. d5 $6 e4 $1 {just works for Black: 0-1 (27) Miller,D (2027)-Kalavannan,K (2339) Hastings 2019.}) ({•} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Bb2 e4 13. Ng5 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 f5 {is unclear.}) 11... exd4 12. exd4 Bg4 $1 13. h3 ({The best try, sacrificing a pawn.} 13. dxc5 dxc5 {is about equal.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Bxd4 15. Rad1 {Thanks to our domination on the light-squares, Black should be very careful.} Qd7 $1 (15... Rb8 $6 16. g4 $1 a6 {16...f5?! 17.Rxd4!! Nxd4?! 18.Qe3 just crushes, e.g. 18...Re8 19.Ne2 Nec6 20.Bd5+ Kg7 21.Qd2+-} 17. Qg3 b5 18. Bc1 {with Ne4 to come, and Black starts to have quite a few problems.}) 16. Qf4 (16. g4 $6 f5 $1 {is problematic now, as} 17. Rxd4 {is met by} Nxd4 18. Qe3 Rae8 {with a decisive advantage for Black.}) 16... Rae8 $1 17. Qd2 {White has enough compensation, but only for equality if Black is accurate.} Nf5 (17... h5 18. Kf1 $1 Nf5 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Nd5 {is tricky, but for example after} Kg7 21. g4 Bxb2 22. gxf5 Bd4 23. Qg5 Re5 {Black somehow holds.}) 18. Bxc6 {We don't need that bishop to put pressure on the light squares - with the knight on d5 it would be much less useful than the c6-knight, which protects the one on d4.} Qxc6 19. Nd5 Re6 20. g4 Nh4 21. Qxd4 $1 {A cute line! However, it only leads to equality.} Nf3+ 22. Kf1 Nxd4 23. Rxe6 Kg7 (23... fxe6 24. Ne7+ Kf7 25. Nxc6 Nxc6 26. Rxd6 Ke7 $1 {also miraculously holds!}) 24. Re7 Re8 25. Rc7 Qa8 26. Bxd4+ cxd4 27. Rxd4 {White definitely has enough compensation, but only for equality, e.g.} Rc8 28. Rd7 Rd8 29. Rc7 Rc8 {And draw. What to do! We cannot refute every line, and Black had many opportunities to go wrong.} *

