1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O e6 {6...e5 again transposes into a Botvnnik system (last chapter, 1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5).} 7. e3 $5 (7. a3 {was initially my choice, but after} Nge7 8. b4 O-O {8...cxb4? 9.axb4 Nxb4 10.Ba3 Nbc6 11.Ne4 is horrible for Black.} 9. Rb1 b6 {with the idea of ... Bb7 I was left rather disappointed.}) 7... Nge7 8. d4 O-O 9. Re1 b6 $1 ({The most dangerous move. The idea is simple: if Black plays a random move (e.g.} 9... Re8 {) now we can push} 10. d5 {as} Na5 {will be answered with Bf1. Besides that, when Black takes on d4, the rook becomes well placed on the e-file.}) {According to played games, this is bad, but the engine brought it back to life.} 10. d5 $5 {The best try I found.} Na5 11. Nd2 Ba6 12. a4 $1 {Forcing things: we want to enable Nb5.} Qd7 $6 (12... Bxc3 $6 13. bxc3 e5 14. e4 {is pleasant for White, as} Nxc4 $4 {loses to} 15. Bf1 Nxd2 16. Bxa6 {trapping the d2-knight.}) 13. Nb5 $1 exd5 14. cxd5 Bxb5 15. axb5 Qxb5 16. e4 {Gives White enormous compensation due to the misplaced knight on a5. Next could be Bf1, Ra4, h4, and slowly the pressure on the kingside will grow, while it's unclear how Black will solve his a5-knight problem.} *

