1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 (3. d4 $6 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {does not give White time to transpose into lines seen under 1...Nf6 with 2...g6 and 5...c5, and the d4-knight is under attack.}) 3... g6 (3... Nf6 {transposes to 1...Nf6 and 2... c5 lines.}) 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 d6 ({•} 5... e5 {goes straight into the last chapter (1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5), the Botvinnik System.}) ({•} 5... Nf6 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O {transposes to 1...Nf6, 2...g6 and 5... c5 lines.}) 6. O-O e6 {6...e5 again transposes into a Botvnnik system (last chapter, 1...c5 with 2...Nc6 and 3...e5).} 7. e3 $5 (7. a3 {was initially my choice, but after} Nge7 8. b4 O-O {8...cxb4? 9.axb4 Nxb4 10.Ba3 Nbc6 11.Ne4 is horrible for Black.} 9. Rb1 b6 {with the idea of ... Bb7 I was left rather disappointed.}) 7... Nge7 8. d4 O-O 9. Re1 b6 $1 ({The most dangerous move. The idea is simple: if Black plays a random move (e.g.} 9... Re8 {) now we can push} 10. d5 {as} Na5 {will be answered with Bf1. Besides that, when Black takes on d4, the rook becomes well placed on the e-file.}) {According to played games, this is bad, but the engine brought it back to life.} 10. d5 $5 {The best try I found.} Na5 11. Nd2 Ba6 12. a4 $1 {Forcing things: we want to enable Nb5.} Nxc4 13. dxe6 {The position is completely crazy, and unclear in several ways, but if you know what you are doing and your opponent does not, his chances of making a mistake are simply high. Moreover, the position is indeed not very clear but objectively more difficult for Black.} d5 (13... Ne5 {is another option, and for example the game can go nuts like this:} 14. exf7+ Rxf7 15. Nde4 Nd3 16. Rf1 d5 $1 17. Ng5 Rf6 18. Nb5 $5 {Now Black needs to find a series of only moves.} c4 19. b3 $5 Bxb5 20. axb5 Nxf2 21. Rxf2 Rxf2 22. Kxf2 Bxa1 23. Ba3 Bf6 24. Bxe7 Qxe7 25. Qxd5+ Kg7 26. Ne6+ Kh6 27. Qxa8 Qxe6 {and Black will draw this. Again, if he is able to find so many good moves, what can we do?}) 14. e4 $5 fxe6 ({After the natural} 14... d4 $2 {White goes} 15. exf7+ Rxf7 $2 16. Nb5 $1 {and Black is in serious trouble.}) 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxc4 Nxc3 17. Qg4 $1 ({Critical!} 17. bxc3 Bxc4 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 {is unclear.}) 17... Qf6 18. Bg5 Qxf2+ 19. Kh1 Qf5 20. Qh4 Z0 ({The previous sequence was forced. Now Black is fine with extremely precise play, like in the following crazy line:} 20... Qd3 21. Ne3 Nd5 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Rad1 Rae8 $3 {Wow!} 24. Be7 Qc4 25. Bxd5+ Qxd5+ 26. Rxd5 Bb7 27. Red1 Rf7 {and Black regains enough material for equality.}) *

