1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... Nxd4 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne4 $1 {This is one of the critical lines.} d5 (8... d6 $2 9. Qa4+ $1 {creates huge problems.}) 9. Qa4+ Kf8 10. Qa3+ (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc5 Ne7 12. O-O h6 {followed by ...Kg8, ...Kh7, is quite solid for Black.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nd6 dxc4 12. Bd2 Bf6 $2 (12... c3 $1 13. bxc3 Be5 $1 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. gxf4 {is unpleasant for Black, but limits the damage.}) 13. Bb4 Z0 ({Black is lost. The game Donchenko - Fier, chess24.com 2020, saw} 13... a5 14. Bc5 Kg7 15. Nxc8 Qc7 16. Bf8# {Oops!}) *

