1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... Nxd4 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne4 $1 {This is one of the critical lines.} d5 (8... d6 $2 9. Qa4+ $1 {creates huge problems.}) 9. Qa4+ Kf8 10. Qa3+ (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc5 Ne7 12. O-O h6 {followed by ...Kg8, ...Kh7, is quite solid for Black.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nd6 Be5 $1 {Trying to kick away the d6-knight.} 12. c5 $1 h5 (12... Kg7 13. O-O Nh6 14. e4 $1 dxe4 15. Nxe4 f6 16. b4 $1 {followed by Bb2, f4, offers White enormous compensation.}) 13. O-O Nh6 $6 14. Bxh6+ Rxh6 15. e4 $146 {This totally refutes the 13...Nh6 idea.} dxe4 (15... dxe3 16. Qxe3 Bg7 17. Rae1 {with enormous compensation.}) 16. f4 $3 Bg7 (16... exf3 $2 17. Rxf3 f5 18. Re1 {is basically over - next might be c6 or Rb3.}) 17. Bxe4 {White will push b4 and Black's position is in ruins.} *

