1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... Nxd4 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne4 $1 {This is one of the critical lines.} d5 (8... d6 $2 9. Qa4+ $1 {creates huge problems.}) 9. Qa4+ Kf8 10. Qa3+ (10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc5 Ne7 12. O-O h6 {followed by ...Kg8, ...Kh7, is quite solid for Black.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nd6 Be5 $1 {Trying to kick away the d6-knight.} 12. c5 $1 h5 (12... Kg7 13. O-O Nh6 14. e4 $1 dxe4 15. Nxe4 f6 16. b4 $1 {followed by Bb2, f4, offers White enormous compensation.}) 13. O-O h4 $1 {A completely computerish move, ignoring White's lead in development, that apparently holds for Black. But we're not gonna give up that easily!} 14. h3 $5 {We want to go g4 closing the h-file and practically force ...hxg3 opening the f-file.} hxg3 15. fxg3 f5 16. e4 $5 dxe3 17. Bxe3 Z0 ({The position is a mess where it is definitely easier for Black to go wrong than for White. One sample line goes} 17... Nf6 18. Bg5 Bd4+ 19. Kh1 Rh5 $1 {and after} 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. g4 fxg4 22. Rxf6+ Qxf6 23. Rf1 Rf5 24. Nxf5 exf5 25. Re1 {White has enough compensation due to the weak black king but apparently no more than for equality. Again, what to do! If Black could resist such an immense pressure, he deserves to have a reasonable position, and I'm not gonna lie in the course to pretend White wins everywhere! :)}) *

