1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. O-O Nge7 10. Nfxd4 $1 ({I believe this is the path to a slight advantage.} 10. Bf4 O-O {does not help.}) ({After} 10. Nbxd4 O-O {nothing really convinced me.}) 10... O-O 11. Be3 Nf5 $1 {Best, I believe, trying to simplify the position.} 12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. Qxd5 (13. Nd4 Bg4 14. Re1 Qf6 $1 {is just equal.}) 13... Qxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxb2 15. Rad1 Be5 {Preventing Nd6.} 16. Bc5 Z0 ({And now after the forced sequence} 16... Rfd8 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Nxa7 {Black doesn't have a draw yet!}) *

