1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ {One of the two possible moves for Black.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best try, I believe. After} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Ne7 $1 {I could not even find a good continuation for White.}) 9... Qxb5 {The obvious alternative to cxd4 , which we will see later in this chapter.} 10. a4 Qb6 11. dxc6 Ne7 $1 (11... bxc6 $2 12. Nc4 {is just dramatic for Black.}) 12. Nc4 $1 {A nice sequence starts, winning the bishop pair.} Qb4+ 13. Bd2 Qxc4 14. cxb7 Bxb7 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Rc1 Qa2 {Where else?} 17. Ba6 $1 O-O {Black couldn't allow Bb5+.} 18. b4 Qa3 $5 19. Ra1 Qb2 20. Rb1 Qa3 21. Qb3 {Forcing the queen exchange.} Qxb3 22. Rxb3 Nd5 23. Bd3 $14 {Although Black's knight is a good piece, White is going to make his king safe and will start pushing pawns on the queenside. White has a slight advantage.} *

