1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ {One of the two possible moves for Black.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best try, I believe. After} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Ne7 $1 {I could not even find a good continuation for White.}) 9... exd5 10. Nd6+ Kf8 11. O-O ({Critical. I've also checked} 11. Nxc8 Rxc8 12. O-O {but after} Nf6 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. e3 h5 $1 15. exd4 Bh6 16. Bxh6+ {it seemed pretty clear that Black had equalized in Iturrizaga, E (2607)-Pulvett, D (2476) Benasque 2021, when a draw was immediately agreed.}) 11... Nge7 12. Nxc8 (12. Nb3 Qb6 13. Nxc8 Rxc8 14. e3 {was played in Ding Liren (2805)-So, W (2754) Abidjan 2019, 0-1 (47), and here for example after} h5 15. exd4 Nxd4 16. Be3 Nef5 {I believe White is the one who should be careful in order to equalize.}) 12... Rxc8 13. Nf3 {White simply goes for positional compensation.} h6 14. Bf4 Bf6 15. b4 $1 Nxb4 16. Rb1 {And Black has problems along the b-file.} *

