1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ {One of the two possible moves for Black.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best try, I believe. After} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Ne7 $1 {I could not even find a good continuation for White.}) 9... exd5 10. Nd6+ Kf8 11. O-O ({Critical. I've also checked} 11. Nxc8 Rxc8 12. O-O {but after} Nf6 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. e3 h5 $1 15. exd4 Bh6 16. Bxh6+ {it seemed pretty clear that Black had equalized in Iturrizaga, E (2607)-Pulvett, D (2476) Benasque 2021, when a draw was immediately agreed.}) 11... Nf6 {A less natural square for the knight, as it blocks the g7-bishop's diagonal, but nevertheless a playable move.} 12. Nb3 Qb4 (12... Qb6 13. a4 $1 {with the idea of a5, adding pressure, when} a5 $2 14. Nb5 {is just awful for Black.}) 13. Nxc8 Rxc8 14. Bd2 Qe7 (14... Qb6 15. Rc1 h5 16. a4 $1 {again with the idea of a5, and Black's position is unpleasant.}) 15. Bf4 Ne4 16. e3 g5 $6 (16... dxe3 $6 17. Qxd5 Nf6 18. Qd3 exf2+ 19. Rxf2 {is already bad for Black.}) 17. Bxe4 gxf4 (17... dxe4 $6 18. Qg4 $1 {is our point - attacking c8 and g5.}) 18. Bf5 fxe3 19. Bxc8 e2 20. Qd3 exf1=Q+ 21. Rxf1 {With a pleasant edge for White due to Black's very weak pawn structure.} *

