1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 e6 {A very solid line: Black wants to play ...Nge7 and ...d5 to take control (or at least neutralize) the center.} 6. d4 $5 {The old move - and most tricky one I believe.} (6. h4 $5 {is the newest fashion, but sadly, after spending lots of hours trying to make it work, after} h6 7. d4 {7.e3 Nge7 8.d4 cxd4 9.Nxd4 d5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.O-O O-O 12.Bd2 Nxd4 13.exd4 Ne7 doesn't lead to anything either.} cxd4 8. Nb5 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O Nf6 {I had to conclude that having included h4 and ...h6 favored Black, as the g4-square is weak, when g5 is simply under control.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb5 d5 8. cxd5 Qa5+ {One of the two possible moves for Black.} 9. Nd2 $1 ({The best try, I believe. After} 9. Qd2 Qxb5 10. dxc6 Ne7 $1 {I could not even find a good continuation for White.}) 9... exd5 10. Nd6+ Kf8 11. O-O ({Critical. I've also checked} 11. Nxc8 Rxc8 12. O-O {but after} Nf6 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. e3 h5 $1 15. exd4 Bh6 16. Bxh6+ {it seemed pretty clear that Black had equalized in Iturrizaga, E (2607)-Pulvett, D (2476) Benasque 2021, when a draw was immediately agreed.}) 11... Nf6 {A less natural square for the knight, as it blocks the g7-bishop's diagonal, but nevertheless a playable move.} 12. Nb3 Qb4 (12... Qb6 13. a4 $1 {with the idea of a5, adding pressure, when} a5 $2 14. Nb5 {is just awful for Black.}) 13. Nxc8 Rxc8 14. Bd2 Qe7 (14... Qb6 15. Rc1 h5 16. a4 $1 {again with the idea of a5, and Black's position is unpleasant.}) 15. Bf4 Ne4 16. e3 Be5 $1 {Best!} 17. Bxe5 (17. Bh6+ Bg7 {doesn't help.}) 17... Qxe5 ({Not} 17... Nxe5 {because after} 18. Qxd4 {White wins a pawn thanks to the double threat of f4 and Qxa7.}) 18. exd4 {White can continue with Rc1, Nc5 and is still on the better side of the board, but Black should be able to equalize. Unfortunately, we cannot refute every line if Black finds such a long series of perfect moves!} *

