1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 {With ...g6 to follow, this is called the Botvinnik system.} 4. c4 (4. e4 Nf6 5. O-O {would transpose into 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.O-O!? e5 5.e4 .}) 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. a3 Nge7 (6... d6 7. O-O {will soon transpose.}) 7. d3 (7. O-O O-O 8. Ne1 d6 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Ne3 Qd7 $1 11. Ned5 Bh3 {isn't convincing for White at all. Radjabov - Vachier Lagrave, Terme Catez 2021.}) (7. b4 {allows} d5 $1 {with huge complications that do not favor White. 1-0 Lagarde - L'Ami, Chennai 2022.}) 7... O-O ({Again,} 7... d6 8. Rb1 {will soon transpose.}) 8. Rb1 {The simplest plan, going for b4, and one of the best tries for White in my opinion.} a5 (8... d6 9. b4 {is just nice for White - it definitely makes sense to stop b2-b4.}) 9. O-O d6 10. b3 $5 {A good try - changing plan and forgetting about b2-b4 now that Black has weakened himself with ...a5.} (10. Ne1 Be6 11. Nc2 d5 {is unsatisfying.}) 10... Rb8 11. Bb2 h6 {The most natural move: Black wants to play ...Be6 without allowing Ng5.} 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Nd5 {Of course we should stop ...d5.} b5 14. e3 f5 15. f4 Z0 ({This is pleasant for White, and ...f5 is something Black would have preferred not to do as it diminishes the e6-bishop's possibilities, e.g.} 15... exf4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. gxf4 Ng8 18. cxb5 {After 18.Qc2 White was slightly better in Shetty - Ringoir, Charlotte 2021. But the text move is much stronger, e.g.} Rxb5 19. Nc3 Rb6 20. Nc4 Ra6 21. d4 $1 cxd4 22. exd4 d5 23. Ne5 Nxe5 24. dxe5 {with a large advantage.}) *

