1. Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 {With ...g6 to follow, this is called the Botvinnik system.} 4. c4 (4. e4 Nf6 5. O-O {would transpose into 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 c5 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.O-O!? e5 5.e4 .}) 4... g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. a3 Nge7 (6... d6 7. O-O {will soon transpose.}) 7. d3 (7. O-O O-O 8. Ne1 d6 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Ne3 Qd7 $1 11. Ned5 Bh3 {isn't convincing for White at all. Radjabov - Vachier Lagrave, Terme Catez 2021.}) (7. b4 {allows} d5 $1 {with huge complications that do not favor White. 1-0 Lagarde - L'Ami, Chennai 2022.}) 7... O-O ({Again,} 7... d6 8. Rb1 {will soon transpose.}) 8. Rb1 {The simplest plan, going for b4, and one of the best tries for White in my opinion.} a5 (8... d6 9. b4 {is just nice for White - it definitely makes sense to stop b2-b4.}) 9. O-O d6 10. Bg5 $5 {This is an interesting alternative. Black should avoid a trade of bishop for knight on e7, as this would weaken his control of the d5-square.} f6 (10... Be6 $6 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nd5 Qf7 14. b4 $16 {was just bad for Black in Carlsen, M (2853)-Vachier Lagrave, M (2742) Warsaw 2023, 1-0 ( )}) 11. Be3 $5 {A fun try: basically, we put the bishop on an awkward square temporarily, in order to stop ...Be6 and ...d5 due to the hanging c5-pawn.} (11. Bd2 Be6 12. Ne1 d5 $1 {is just fine for Black. 0-1 Svidler - Giri, Moscow 2016.}) 11... Be6 12. Ne1 f5 ({•} 12... Qd7 13. Nc2 Rab8 14. b4 {is what we want.}) ({• Same goes with} 12... Rb8 {when} 13. Nc2 {followed by 14. b4 is good for White.}) 13. Bg5 ({• At first, engines like} 13. b4 {but after} axb4 14. axb4 Nxb4 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Bg2 {I believe the position has simplified significantly and White cannot claim any advantage.}) ({•} 13. Nd5 {is a fine try but after} Bf7 $1 {in order to enable ...Nxd5, I believe Black is fine.}) 13... h6 $6 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nc2 {With b4 or Ne3 to follow; this is what we hope for.} *

