1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} d6 $5 {Black also intends to fight for the center.} 3. e4 $1 g6 $6 4. exf5 Bxf5 5. d4 $1 {We get an unusual opening position on the board where Black's f-pawn has been traded for White's e-pawn. This favours White as Black's king is weaker and White can build pressure on the e-file.} Bg7 6. Bd3 {This is already very ugly for Black.} Qd7 {Avoiding the exchange of bishops would lose too much time, and if bishops have to be traded, better activate the black queen instead of the white one.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. c4 O-O 9. Bxf5 Qxf5 10. Nc3 {White enjoys a more favourable pawn structure.} Nbd7 11. h3 $146 e5 12. Be3 $16 {In this position White has much better prospects, with Qb3/c5 to come.} *

