1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} d6 $5 {Black also intends to fight for the center.} 3. e4 $1 e5 4. Nc3 $1 Nf6 $6 5. exf5 Bxf5 6. d4 $1 e4 7. Nh4 Bg4 (7... Be6 8. d5 $1 Bf7 9. Bc4 Nbd7 10. Nf5 $16) (7... Bd7 8. Bc4 $5 {$146 8...Bg4 9.Be2 transposes to 7... Bg4. 8... c6 9. d5! c5?! 10. Qe2! $16}) 8. Be2 $1 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 d5 10. Bg5 $1 {Black has concrete problems already.} Bb4 {The only way to complicate matters.} (10... c6 11. f3 $1 Be7 12. fxe4 dxe4 13. Nf5 O-O 14. O-O {+-}) 11. Qb5+ $1 Nc6 12. Qxb7 Nxd4 13. O-O-O $1 {It may seem risky, but if Black cannot prove anything concrete, his position is just doomed. Moreover, it is well known that these things do not work for Black, a judgment I fully share.} Rb8 (13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Rb8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 {transposes.}) 14. Bxf6 Bxc3 15. bxc3 gxf6 (15... Rxb7 16. Bxd8 Nb5 17. Bg5 Nxc3 18. Rde1 $16) 16. Qa6 $1 Rb6 17. Qa4+ Nc6 18. Rhe1 $1 {The whole Black idea fails for concrete reasons.} O-O 19. Rxe4 $16 {And White won in the game Cabrera - Saumweber, Santa Cruz de Tenerife 2011.} *

