1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} Nf6 $6 3. e4 $1 {"It is always too early to move the f-pawn" goes one of the most famous chess sayings (unfortunately, I cannot remember to whom it was attributed!). It simply means that playing ...f5 or ...f6 (or f4 or f3 as White) is always a weakening move. In this case, we use Black's early ...f5 to open the position as long as Black's king remains in the center.} fxe4 $6 4. dxe4 Nxe4 ({Accepting the pawn sac is the only way to justify Black’s previous moves, but he simply gets a bad position.} 4... d6 5. e5 $1 Nfd7 6. Nc3 dxe5 $2 7. Ng5 $1 {+-}) 5. Bd3 $1 Nf6 {Black wants to avoid the bad endgame we’ve seeen ( 5…d5 6.Bxe4 ) .} 6. Ng5 $1 {But White goes for an immediate attack!} e6 $2 {A bad reaction as well, for a similar reason as 6...d6.} 7. Bxh7 $1 {A harsh punishment!} Nxh7 $6 8. Qh5+ Ke7 9. Nxh7 {Material is equal, but Black is lost due to his very weak king and the threat of Bg5+.} *

