1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} Nf6 $6 3. e4 $1 {"It is always too early to move the f-pawn" goes one of the most famous chess sayings (unfortunately, I cannot remember to whom it was attributed!). It simply means that playing ...f5 or ...f6 (or f4 or f3 as White) is always a weakening move. In this case, we use Black's early ...f5 to open the position as long as Black's king remains in the center.} fxe4 $6 4. dxe4 Nxe4 ({Accepting the pawn sac is the only way to justify Black’s previous moves, but he simply gets a bad position.} 4... d6 5. e5 $1 Nfd7 6. Nc3 dxe5 $2 7. Ng5 $1 {+-}) 5. Bd3 $1 Nf6 {Black wants to avoid the bad endgame we’ve seeen ( 5…d5 6.Bxe4 ) .} 6. Ng5 $1 {But White goes for an immediate attack!} g6 7. h4 $1 ({Avoiding tricks on h7, as} 7. Nxh7 $6 {would be met with} Rxh7 8. Bxg6+ Rf7 {. However, White continues to increase his pressure on the kingside anyway!}) {No time to rest for Black! And there is no good reaction here, he is just busted.} 7... d5 (7... c6 8. h5 Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Qe5+ 10. Kf1 $1 {+-}) 8. h5 $1 {White is ready to sacrifice an exchange on h5.} Bg4 9. f3 Bxh5 10. g4 {Trapping the bishop.} Qd6 11. gxh5 Nxh5 12. Nc3 {Black has stopped the attack at the cost of a piece. He doesn’t have compensation for it and is just lost. Kazakovskiy - Kantans, Stockholm 2016.} *

