1. Nf3 f5 {Black plays in the spirit of the Dutch Defense. We will try to take advantage of the fact that white has yet to play d4.} 2. d3 $5 {White wants to play e4 which is very different to the main lines of the Dutch Defence where white is already committed to d4.} Nf6 $6 3. e4 $1 {'It is always too early to move the f-pawn' goes one of the most famous chess sayings (unfortunately, I cannot remember to whom it was attributed!). It simply means that playing ...f5 or ...f6 (or f4 or f3 as White) is always a weakening move. In this case, we use Black's early ...f5 to open the position as long as Black's king remains in the center.} d6 4. exf5 {) White aims to follow up with d4, Bd3, and Black has problems on the light squares, and especially e6.} Bxf5 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 Be7 7. O-O Qd7 8. Re1 {This kind of positions, where Black has a weakness on e6, can't be good unless Black has something concrete.} Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nc6 11. c3 $16 {White enjoys the bishop pair and a semi-open e-file. He is clearly better. Mamedyarov - Dovliatov, Baku 2001.} *

