1. Nf3 {Let's now have a look at b-pawn moves, which are very dubious for Black.} b5 $6 {This can be playable when White has played g3 and is more or less committed to Bg2, but not on move 1!} 2. e4 $1 a6 {Black simply defends his b5-pawn, but meanwhile White pushes his second central pawn and enjoys a nice space advantage.} 3. d4 Bb7 4. Bd3 e6 (4... Nf6 5. e5 Nd5 6. O-O e6 {transposes to 4... e6.}) 5. O-O c5 {Black tries to transpose into some sort of Kan Sicilian (Sicilians with ...e6, ...a6, ...b5).} 6. c3 $1 {Keeping a firm control of the center.} Nf6 7. e5 $1 {Now we're going to play for the dark squares.} Nd5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. a4 $1 Qb6 $146 (9... Nc6 $6 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Bxb5 $16) 10. Nbd2 $1 {Aiming at Ne4 or Nb3.} Nc6 11. Nb3 Be7 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Qe2 $16 {Black's position is very unpleasant: ...b5 is hanging and ...O-O can also be met with Qe4.} *

