1. Nf3 {Let's now have a look at b-pawn moves, which are very dubious for Black.} b6 2. e4 {We've transposed to an Owen Defense where White did not have time to play 3. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 to protect the e4-pawn without playing Nc3. The whole line remains quite dubious for Black anyway.} c5 {This transposes to a Katalimov Sicilian ( 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 b6 ) which is known to be very, very dubious.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {A clever move to prevent ...e6, and make ...Nf6 difficult as Black's pawn structure would be pretty bad after an exchange on f6.} Qc7 7. Nd5 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is simple and strong.} Bxd5 8. exd5 Qe5+ {The only way to justify Black's play.} 9. Be3 Qxd5 10. Be2 {Black is in serious trouble, having only his queen developed! Some sample lines.} e5 (10... Qb7 11. Bf3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 dxc6 13. Qd4 {with a large advantage.}) 11. Nf5 {White enjoys wonderful compensation on the light squares.} Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 g6 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Rxd6 Z0 ({And White will get his pawn back with a better position, as} 14... b5 $4 {loses to} 15. Bf3 Nc6 16. Rxc6 $1 {+-}) *

