1. Nf3 d6 ({Other various first moves, like} 1... g6 {,}) (1... e6 {,}) (1... b6 {, will all transpose into other chapters. Here the logical thing to do would be 2.d4 and transpose into another opening depending on what Black does. For example if 2...g6 3.e4 we have a Pirc/Modern Defense, with 2...Nf6 we can go for Classical 1. d4 lines with 3.d4 , or we can play 3.g3 accepting to play a Catalan, or again 3.Nc3 with the idea of 4. e4, as 3... d5 with ...d6 already being played makes little sense. If 2...f5 we have a weird Dutch Defense with ...d6, while if 2...Bg4 , the Wade Defense, White can just go 3. e4 followed by Nc3, h3, and this is quite a poor opening for Black. Nevertheless, if you would like to stick to a sidelines opening repertoire, I am going to suggest a sideline - but as you will see, Black equalizes with precise play.}) 2. g3 e5 3. Bg2 f5 4. d3 Nf6 5. e4 $5 {Quite similar to our repertoire against 1. Nf3 f5.} Be7 {Black follows logical development. He could have traded on e4 already, but as White is not planning to prevent it, analyzing it right now would be irrelevant.} 6. O-O O-O {Again, trading on e4 would be followed by Nh4 and transposing into our mainline.} 7. Nh4 f4 8. gxf4 exf4 9. Nf5 $1 g5 (9... Bxf5 10. exf5 {attacks b7 and f4, and after Bxf4 it won't be that easy to recapture on f5.}) 10. h4 Ne8 11. Kh1 {Followed by Rg1 with a dangerous position for Black.} *

